Achille Bocchi (1488-1562) 的《Symbolicarum Questionum》中的徽章。在书中，这个标志的上方写着“PICTURIA GRAVIUM OSTENDUNTUR PONDERA RERUM. QUAEQUE LATENT IMACES, HAEC PER MAGE APERTA PATENT”，大致翻译为“一张图片说明了重要问题的深刻见解；任何看不见的东西都可以变得可见。”

An emblem from Achille Bocchi’s (1488-1562) “Symbolicarum Quaestionum.” Above this emblem, in the book, appear the words “PICTURIA GRAVIUM OSTENDUNTUR PONDERA RERUM. QUAEQUE LATENT IMACES, HAEC PER MAGE APERTA PATENT,” which loosely translates as, “A picture illustrates the deep insights of important matters; whatever is unseen can be made visible.”

鲍勃·W·林格菲尔特 (Bob W. Lingerfelt) 作品

Also by Bob W. Lingerfelt

通过将理念与事物联系起来，一个宏大的记忆体系得以建立，并保障了它们的永恒。石碑或许会破碎，刻有文字的方尖碑或许会倾覆，羊皮纸或许会腐烂，图书馆或许会消亡，但真理与自然紧密相连，永远不会消亡，直到它的火葬柴堆被末日的火炬点燃。因此，诗人和艺术家通过他们的理想化，赋予物质以内在的光辉和隐秘的生命……我们的伦理体系是一条蜿蜒的、描绘真理的长廊。

By associating ideas with things, a grand mnemonic system is established and their perpetuity provided for. Tablets may be shattered, lettered obelisks be upturned, parchments rot, libraries perish, but truth, bound to nature, can never perish until her funeral pyre is lighted by the torch of doom. So, poets and artists, by their idealizations, impress material objects with an inner glory and a hidden life...Our ethical system is a long-drawn corridor of pictured truths.

- 霍华德·亨德森兄弟，《秋叶在印第安夏季聚集》（1907年）

- Br. Howard Henderson, Autumn Leaves Gathered in Indian Summer (1907)

前言

Preface

* * *

* * *

写到记忆宫殿，或者更确切地说，写到用于记忆单词（memoria verborum）的记忆宫殿时，很难不觉得自己像个骗子。构建记忆宫殿的艺术已经流传了两千多年，许多比我更重要、更博学的人也撰写了关于这个主题的书籍；这些人有的值得被收录进百科全书和历史书，有的则名字后面有无数的字母和点。

It is difficult not to feel a little like an imposter when writing about memory palaces, or more specifically, memory palaces used for the purpose of memoria verborum (memory of words). The art of building memory palaces has been taught for more than two millennia and many books have been written about the subject by far more important and learned people than me; people who merit entries in encyclopedias and history books or who have an extraordinary number of letters and dots after their names.

然而，这些书籍中绝大多数关注的并非记忆法（memoria verborum ） ，而是其更简单的对应词（ memoria rerum，即事物的记忆）。此外，大多数关于记忆术的书籍都是历史概述或比较研究。很少有书籍教授记忆法的实际运用，更不用说提倡了。我还没发现哪本现代教材是用记忆宫殿法来教授记忆法的。

Yet the overwhelming majority of these books focus not on memoria verborum but its simpler counterpart memoria rerum (memory of things). Additionally, most books about the art of memory are historical overviews or comparative studies. Few teach, much less advocate, its actual practice. I’m not aware of single modern text that teaches memoria verborum using the memory palace technique.

令人奇怪的是，共济会成员编写的记忆书籍，以及探讨共济会仪式与记忆术之间联系的书籍，都寥寥无几。考虑到共济会成员独特的记忆限制、我们兄弟会的迫切需求，以及关于共济会的书籍数量之多，我一直觉得这很奇怪。

There is also a curious absence of memory books of any kind written for Freemasons or which explore the ties between our craft’s rites and the art of memory. This has always seemed peculiar to me, given the unique memorization restrictions imposed on Masons, the pressing needs of our fraternity, and the great number of books available on Freemasonry in general.

话虽如此，这本书并非专为共济会成员准备。诚然，书中不时提及某些共济会的概念和实践，但掌握共济会的基本知识并非必需。任何对记忆宫殿技巧（memoria verborum ）感兴趣的人，都希望这本书能有所帮助。

That said, this book is not reserved for Freemasons. True, there are allusions here and there to certain Masonic concepts and practices, but a knowledge of Freemasonry is not needed to grasp the fundamentals. Anyone interested in the rarely taught memoria verborum memory palace technique will hopefully find this book useful.

- 鲍勃·W·林格菲尔特（Bob W. Lingerfelt），石匠大师

- Bob W. Lingerfelt, Master Mason

内布拉斯加州贝尔维尤旅馆 #325

Bellevue Lodge #325, Nebraska

Tabula Rasa Lodge #332，内布拉斯加州

1

1

记忆在技艺中的重要性

The Importance of Memory in the Craft

西虽然对记忆技巧感兴趣的非共济会会员应该会发现所罗门的记忆宫殿非常有用，但我主要为那些正在寻找更好方法来记忆共济会资料的共济会会员编写了这本书。在接下来的篇幅中，我将教你一种特殊而罕见的“位置记忆法”（method of loci），这是一种古老的记忆方法，与17和18世纪思辨共济会的建立有着神秘的联系。

While non-Masons interested in memorization techniques should find Solomon’s Memory Palace very useful, I have written it primarily for Freemasons who are looking for a better way to memorize Masonic materials. In the pages that follow I will teach you a special and rare version of the method of loci, an ancient approach to memorization which has cryptic ties to the establishment of the Speculative Freemasonry in the 17th and 18th centuries.

记忆，即储存和回忆信息的能力，在共济会中扮演着至关重要的角色。在很多方面，它都是共济会的核心。如果我们连它们的用途都记不住，我们所有的徽章、符号、象形文字和标志还有什么用处呢？如果没有人花时间记住仪式、讲座或日常事务，那么作为一个会所聚集还有什么意义呢？共济会会员晋升的门槛又是什么？我们该如何解读那些深奥的文字？

Memory, the ability to store and recall information, plays a critical role in Freemasonry. In many ways, it is at the very heart of Masonry. What would be the utility of all our emblems, symbols, hieroglyphs, and signs if we could not remember their purpose? What point would there be in gathering as a lodge if no one present had taken the time to memorize the rituals, lectures, or floor-work? What would be the criteria for a Mason to pass from one degree to another? How would we decipher the esoteric words?

记忆赋予我们智慧，没有智慧，共济会就无法维系。没有记忆将我们与过去联系起来，我们就无法成为共济会会员。没有记忆，我们就无法审慎地决定当前和未来行动的结果；而没有审慎，节制、坚韧和正义的美德就会变得盲目。我们无法在不知是非对错的情况下节制自己的行为；我们无法在不知我们的事业值得为之奋斗的情况下忍受痛苦、危险或危机；我们无法在不知何为公平公正的情况下确立正义的标准。

Memory grants us wisdom, and without wisdom, a lodge cannot be supported. Without memory to connect us to our past, we cannot make Masons. Without memory, we cannot prudentially determine the outcomes of our present and future actions, and without Prudence, the virtues of Temperance, Fortitude, and Justice are blind. We can’t temper our actions without knowing what is wrong or right; we won’t endure pain, peril, or danger without first knowing that our cause is worth fighting for; we can’t have a standard of justice without first knowing what is fair and equitable.

共济会徽章的存在是为了提醒我们特定的原则、概念、奥秘和真理。然而，只有当我们作为共济会成员牢记它们所代表的意义时，它们才能真正发挥作用。那些我们发誓绝不书写或以其他方式记录下来的秘密，以及几个世纪以来兄弟间秘密流传的秘密，又将何去何从？那些难以言喻、唯有我们心灵才能完整承载的秘密，又将何去何从？

Masonic emblems exist to remind us of specific principles, concepts, mysteries, and truths. Yet they only serve their purpose if we, as members of the craft, remember what they represent. And what would happen to those secrets which we have sworn never to write or otherwise physically record, and which have been passed brother to brother, in secret, for centuries? What would happen to those secrets that defy words, which only our minds can host in full?

许多共济会成员可能不知道，共济会历史上的关键人物威廉·肖（William Schaw）禁止任何无法证明自己精通“记忆术”的人加入会所。1599年，他命令总督“对每位共济会成员和学徒进行记忆术及其相关科学的测试”，并补充说：“共济会成员……如果没有通过充分的测试，证明其记忆术和记忆术能力，不得入会。”

Many brothers might be unaware that William Schaw, a pivotal figure in the history of Freemasonry, prohibited the admittance of anyone into a lodge who could not demonstrate skill in “the art of memory.” In 1599, he ordered the General Warden to “test every fellow of the craft and every apprentice on the art of memory and science thereof,” adding that, “fellows of craft…shall not be admitted without a sufficient test and proof of memory and art of craft.”

大约四个世纪后，作家兼历史学家弗朗西斯·A·耶茨 (Frances A. Yates) 在她的著作《记忆的艺术》中提出，推测性共济会可能受益于文艺复兴时期记忆艺术的实践者，她写道：“共济会的起源笼罩在神秘之中......我认为，这个问题的答案可能由记忆艺术的历史所暗示......它使用的不是真正的‘操作性’共济会建筑，而是记忆艺术的想象或‘推测性’建筑作为其教学的载体。”

Almost four centuries later, author and historian Frances A. Yates, in her book The Art of Memory, suggested that Speculative Freemasonry might owe a debt to Renaissance practitioners of the art of memory, writing, “The origins of Freemasonry are wrapped in mystery…I would think that the answer to this problem may be suggested by the history of the art of memory…which used, not the real architecture of ‘operative’ masonry, but the imaginary or ‘speculative’ architecture of the art of memory as the vehicle of its teachings.”

耶茨的推测值得深思。十六、十七世纪的大多数记忆术修行者都运用了本书所教授的某种形式的记忆宫殿技巧，其中许多人与那些被认定为无知推测共济会成员的人有关联。

Yates’ speculation is worthy of contemplation. Most practitioners of the art of memory in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries used some form of the memory palace technique taught in this book, and many of those practitioners can be connected to individuals identified with nescient Speculative Freemasonry.

事实上，共济会的工具和用来“建造”记忆宫殿的工具惊人地相似。两者都使用建筑——分别是神庙和宫殿——作为基础结构或框架。两者都通过大量的符号、徽章和象形文字进行交流。两者都要求实践者使用符号作为路径点进行某种精神导航。两者都使用五种感官作为连接物质世界和精神世界的门户。两者都在空白画布（可以被认为是描图板）上绘制图案。两者都利用一维、二维和三维几何图形，包括点、线、面、立方体和圆柱体。

In fact, the tools of Freemasonry and the tools used to “erect” a memory palace are strikingly similar. Both use structures – a temple and palace, respectively – as foundational structures or frameworks. Both communicate via myriad symbols, emblems, and hieroglyphs. Both require the practitioner to perform a type of mental navigation using symbols as waypoints. Both use the five senses as gateways between the physical and the mental worlds. Both draw designs on blank canvases (which can be thought of as tracing boards). Both make use of one-, two-, and three-dimensional geometric figures, to include points, lines, planes, cubes, and cylinders.

至于记忆术为何可能由思辨共济会实现并延续，我们需要深入研究文艺复兴时期学者的学说，例如朱利奥·卡米洛（约1480-1544年）、约翰·迪伊（1527-1608年）、乔尔丹诺·布鲁诺（1548-1600年）、亚历山大·迪克森（约1558-1604年）和罗伯特·弗拉德（1574-1637年）。这些人认为，记忆宫殿的作用远不止提升记忆力。他们相信，如果建造得当，记忆宫殿可以赋予其创造者神圣的洞察力——通常被称为“光明”。

As to why the art of memory might have been realized and perpetuated by Speculative Freemasonry, one needs to delve into the teachings of Renaissance scholars such as Giulio Camillo (c.1480-1544), John Dee (1527-1608), Giordano Bruno (1548-1600), Alexander Dickson (c.1558-1604), and Robert Fludd (1574-1637). These men believed that a memory palace could do more than just improve a person’s memory. They believed that, properly constructed, a memory palace could provide its creator with divine insight - often referred to as “light.”

如果您对此主题感兴趣，有很多书籍对此进行了不同程度的详细讨论。我的书架上有两本，分别是大卫史蒂文森的《共济会的起源》和罗伯特库珀的《破解共济会密码》。前面提到的弗朗西斯耶茨的《记忆的艺术》本身并不是一本关于共济会的书，但可能是迄今为止关于记忆艺术和记忆宫殿的最伟大的书籍，在书中，耶茨探讨了这门艺术与兄弟会之间的潜在联系。保罗罗西的《逻辑与记忆的艺术》一次也没有提到共济会，但共济会成员应该会在书中找到一些有趣的内容。

If this topic interests you, there are a number of books that address it with varying levels of detail. Two that are on my bookshelf are David Stevenson’s The Origins of Freemasonry and Robert Cooper’s Cracking the Freemason’s Code. Frances Yates’s The Art of Memory, previously mentioned, is not a book about Freemasonry per se but is perhaps the greatest book yet written about the art of memory and memory palaces, and in it, Yates discusses the potential ties between the art and the fraternity. Paolo Rossi’s Logic and the Art of Memory doesn’t mention Freemasonry even once, yet Freemasons should find several items of interest within its pages.

但我们还是别扯太远了。你读这本书很可能只是想知道如何有效地记住我们仪式的某些部分，为此，我感谢你。你迈出了许多兄弟永远无法迈出的一步。

But let’s not go too far afield. You’re likely reading this book because you simply want an effective way to memorize some part of our ritual, and for that, I thank you. You have taken a step that many brothers will never take.

对许多共济会会员来说，记住共济会的教材是一项繁重的额外工作，几乎没有任何价值。然而，记忆是我们共济会的基石。如果新会员不愿意记住仪式、角色和讲课，我们的兄弟会就会消亡——而且很快就会消亡。说共济会的记忆工作太多，就像说踢足球时来回跑动太多一样。两者缺一不可。

For many Freemasons, memorization of craft materials is perceived as a burdensome additional duty that has little or no value. Yet memorization is fundamental to our craft. If new Masons are unwilling to memorize rituals, roles, and lectures, our fraternity will die - and soon. Saying that there is too much memory work in Freemasonry is like saying there is too much running back and forth in football. You simply can’t have one without the other.

幸运的是，记忆宫殿为我们所有人提供了一个安全的地方来存储那些对我们的秩序如此重要的古代宝藏。

Fortunately, the memory palace provides all of us a place to safely store those ancient treasures so important to our order.

不幸的是，它们不能自行建造。

Unfortunately, they don’t build themselves.

让我们开始工作吧。

Let’s get to work.

2

2

共济会记忆的挑战

The Challenge of Masonic Memorization

那么，我将飞翔，超越我本性的这种力量，继续逐渐升向创造我的那位。我进入记忆的田野和广阔的殿堂，那里珍藏着无数通过感官从各种事物中带入的形象。记忆中也同样储存着我们所思考的一切，这些思考或通过扩大或缩小我们的感知，或通过某种方式改变感官所接触到的事物；以及所有其他被托付给它并储存在其中的东西，那些尚未被遗忘吞噬和埋葬的东西。

- 希波的奥古斯丁（354-430），《忏悔录》（约398年）

I will soar, then, beyond this power of my nature also, still rising by degrees toward him who made me. And I enter the fields and spacious halls of memory, where are stored as treasures the countless images that have been brought into them from all manner of things by the senses. There, in the memory, is likewise stored what we cogitate, either by enlarging or reducing our perceptions, or by altering one way or another those things which the senses have made contact with; and everything else that has been entrusted to it and stored up in it, which oblivion has not yet swallowed up and buried.

- Augustine of Hippo (354-430), The Confessions (c.398)

D你很难记住角色、任务、讲座或其他仪式内容吗？如果是这样，你可能已经认定你的大脑根本不适合做这些事情，这意味着你可能已经放弃了尝试。何必与自然抗争呢？对吧？

Do you struggle to memorize roles, charges, lectures, or other parts of ritual? If so, you may have decided that your brain simply isn’t wired for that kind of thing, which means you’ve probably stopped trying. Why fight nature, right?

但问题可能不在于你的大脑。真正的问题可能在于你的技巧——或者缺乏技巧。你的大脑就像一把锤子，是一种工具。锤子必须正确使用才能有效。用锤子的爪子把钉子钉进木头里是一种糟糕的技巧。用锤柄试图拔钉子也是。在这两种情况下，你都有完美的工具，只是用错了方法。

But your brain probably isn’t the problem. The real problem may be your technique - or lack of technique. Your brain is a tool, just like a hammer. A hammer has to be used correctly to be effective. Using a hammer’s claw to drive a nail into a piece of wood is bad technique. So is using the handle to try to remove a nail. In both cases you’ve got the perfect tool for the job but you’re using it the wrong way.

讽刺的是，虽然你在学校里花了好几年时间接受记忆所学内容的测试，但你可能从未学过如何记忆。事后看来，这似乎有点不公平，不是吗？这难道不应该是你最先学到的东西吗？

Ironically, while you spent years in school being tested on your ability to memorize what you were taught, the one thing you were probably never taught is how to memorize things. In hindsight, that seems a bit unfair, doesn’t it? Shouldn’t that have been the first thing you were taught?

既然你已经成年，就该独立了。当然，市面上有很多书籍、网站和视频，承诺教你记忆的秘诀。有些还不错。然而，大多数都是为学生、励志演说家、商界人士、政客、神职人员、教育工作者，当然还有演员设计的。

Now that you’re an adult, you’re on your own. Sure, there are plenty of books, websites, and videos that promise to teach you the secrets of memorization. Some of them are quite good. However, most are designed for students, motivational speakers, business professionals, politicians, clergy, educators, and, of course, actors.

这很成问题，因为这些人的需求与你不同，而且他们受的限制更少。你的目标是逐字逐句地背诵演讲材料，而大多数人（演员除外）只需要记住他们计划演讲的提纲。例如，励志演说家和大学讲师的“讲稿”就很灵活。使用讲稿的人只需以逻辑清晰的方式从一个主要话题过渡到另一个主要话题，并阐述每个话题中最重要的方面。此外，他们还可以边讲边参考笔记——这是你在课堂上无法享受到的便利。

That’s a problem because those individuals have different needs than you and operate with fewer restrictions. Your objective is to recite your material verbatim, i.e., word-for-word, while most others, excluding actors, only need to memorize the outline of what they plan to say. The “scripts” of motivational speakers and college lecturers, for example, are flexible. The individuals who use them need only to move from one major topic to another in a logical fashion, and to address the most important aspects of each topic. Also, they can refer to notes while speaking – a luxury you do not have in lodge.

对演员的要求更高。大多数情况下，演员必须一字不差地记住台词。莎士比亚戏剧的演员尤其面临着许多与共济会成员相同的挑战。他们必须记住现代社会中很少甚至从未使用过的词语，以及那些串在一起难以理解的句子。需要记住的材料数量之多令人震惊。扮演哈姆雷特的演员必须记住超过1500句台词！与共济会成员一样，演员——或者至少是舞台剧演员——在演出期间不能依赖笔记或提词器。

Actors are held to a higher standard. In most cases, actors are supposed to remember their lines verbatim. Shakespearean actors, in particular, face many of the same challenges as Freemasons. They must memorize words that are rarely if ever used in modern society and which are strung together in sentences that are difficult to comprehend. The amount of material that must be memorized is staggering. An actor portraying Hamlet must memorize more than 1,500 lines! Like Freemasons, actors – or, at least, stage actors – cannot rely on notes or teleprompters during a performance.

然而，即使是莎士比亚戏剧的演员也比共济会成员有几分优势。共济会成员被禁止撰写或录制任何讲座或片段中晦涩难懂的部分，即使是个人使用。共济会成员不得与非共济会成员或级别不合适的共济会成员一起排练，而且有些内容在会所外是不能大声说出来的。共济会成员无法在家中观看或在旅行中收听讲座的视频或音频记录。更糟糕的是，共济会的“剧本”通常是暗语。

Nevertheless, even Shakespearean actors have several advantages over Freemasons. Masons are prohibited from writing or recording any of the esoteric portions of a lecture or part, even for personal use. Masons are not permitted to rehearse with a non-Mason or a Mason not of the appropriate degree, and there are some things that cannot be said aloud outside of lodge. There are no video or audio recordings of lectures that Masons can watch in their homes or listen to while traveling. Worse, Masonic “scripts” are often in code.

大多数莎士比亚演员如果被告知他们的剧本将以密码形式呈现，会感到犹豫；有些台词将从剧本中完全省略；他们只能在舞台上排练台词，并且只能与另一位演员一起排练（即使这样，也只能与特定的演员一起排练）；并且禁止他们写下或录制台词，或者在剧院外、在任何非演员面前或在任何可能被人听到的环境中大声朗读。

Most Shakespearean actors would balk if told that their scripts would be in code; that some of the words would be omitted from the script altogether; that they could only rehearse their lines on stage, and only with another actor (and even then, only with certain actors); and that they were prohibited from ever writing or recording their lines, or saying them aloud outside the theater, or in front of any non-actors, or in any environment where they might be overheard.

共济会成员记忆的内容与励志演说家、政客、讲师或演员记忆的内容的另一个区别在于目的。在共济会之外，讲师寻求的是教育或信息。演员和歌手寻求的是娱乐。政客寻求的是说服或激励。他们的话语是面向他人的，如果没有听众，他们的话语就毫无意义。

Another thing that distinguishes what Freemasons memorize from those things memorized by a motivational speaker, politician, instructor, or actor is purpose. Outside of Freemasonry, lecturers seek to educate or inform. Actors and singers seek to entertain. Politicians seek to persuade or motivate. Their words are intended for others, and without an audience, they aren’t spoken.

在共济会，我们记忆和背诵的内容是仪式。这是共济会的“基本内容”，即使几乎没有人听（或根本没有人在听），也必须这样做。然而，这些词必须正确念出。是的，记忆和背诵的内容也有助于教育候选人和兄弟，但如果教育是唯一的目的，我们就不需要逐字逐句地记住我们的词句了。

In Freemasonry, what we memorize and recite is ritual. It is the very “stuff” of the craft, required even when there is almost no one there to hear it (or no one listening). Yet the words must be said correctly. Yes, what is memorized and recited also serves to educate candidates and brothers, but if education was the only purpose we would not be required to remember our words verbatim.

这就是为什么那么多公众可获得的记忆书籍和视频对共济会成员根本不起作用。它们是为那些比共济会成员拥有更多自由的人写的，它们建议我们去做那些我们发誓不做的事情。

This is why so many memory books and videos available to the public simply don’t work for Freemasons. They are written for individuals who have far more liberties than Freemasons do and they advise us to do things we have sworn not to do.

3

3

共济会的解决方案

A Solution for Freemasons

左幸运的是，世界上一些广为流传的记忆技巧，共济会成员也能运用。其中最有效的方法之一是记忆宫殿法，又称“位置记忆法”。这是一种古老的技巧，如前所述，它可能与共济会有着悠久的历史渊源，因此既有效又实用。

Luckily, some of the memorization techniques used by the world at large are usable by Freemasons. Among the most effective of these is the memory palace, also known as the method of loci. This is an ancient technique which, as mentioned earlier, may be historically tied to Freemasonry, making it both effective and appropriate.

关于记忆宫殿的最早描述之一可以在一本名为《Rhetorica Ad Herennium 》的书中找到，该书的拉丁语意思是《修辞：为了 Herennius》。

One of the earliest descriptions of a memory palace can be found in a book called Rhetorica Ad Herennium, which is Latin for Rhetoric: For Herennius.

修辞学指的是有说服力或有效的演讲，这本书实际上是为一位名叫盖乌斯·赫伦尼乌斯的绅士写的，我们对他一无所知。说实话，我们甚至不知道这本书的作者是谁。长期以来，人们一直认为这本书是西塞罗（公元前106年-公元前43年）的作品，但如今普遍认为他并非作者。我们确实知道这本书写于公元前80年左右。

Rhetoric refers to persuasive or effective speaking, and the book was actually written for a gentleman named Gaius Herennius, whom we know nothing about. To be honest, we don’t even know who wrote the book. It was attributed to Cicero (106 B.C.- 43 B.C.) for a long time but the consensus today is that he was not the author. We do know it was written about 80 B.C.

如果你已经觉得这个话题有点儿令人望而生畏，那只是因为里面充斥着太多拉丁语。本质上，一个穿着托加长袍的人（我们叫他卡尔）写了一本名为《有效演讲指南》的书，献给另一个穿着托加长袍的人（我们叫他哈里）。哈里或许是一位败诉太多的律师，又或许是一位在同行或代表群体中不太受欢迎的政客。

If you already find this topic a bit daunting, it’s only because there’s so much Latin been thrown around. Essentially some guy in a toga (let’s call him Carl) wrote a book called “A Guide to Effective Speaking” and dedicated to another guy in a toga (let’s call him Harry). Maybe Harry was a lawyer who’d lost a few too many cases, or a politician who wasn’t very popular with his peers or those he represented.

无论如何，卡尔为哈利写的那本书是一本好书，它被反复抄写，正因为如此优秀，印数如此之多，它才得以流传两千一百年，至今仍在我们心中。所以，下次你看到《Ad Herennium》 （ 《修辞学：为哈利而写》的简称）时，就把它想象成《为哈利而写的公共演讲》。这样就没那么吓人了，不是吗？

In any event, the book that Carl wrote for Harry was a good one, and it was copied again and again, and because it was so good and so many copies were made, it has survived twenty-one hundred years and is still with us. So, the next time you see Ad Herennium (the shortened title of Rhetorica Ad Herennium), just think of it as Public Speaking for Harry. That’s a lot less intimidating, isn’t it?

卡尔献给哈利的书是现存最古老的描述如何建造和使用记忆宫殿的书，这意味着从那时起，几乎所有其他关于这个主题的作家都引用过这本书，包括我在内——而且我会经常参考它。

Carl’s book, dedicated to Harry, is the oldest surviving book which describes how a memory palace is built and used, which means it has been referenced by almost every other writer on the topic since then, to include me – and I’ll be referring to it a lot.

让我们回到最基本的话题。记忆宫殿到底是什么？

But let’s get back to the basics. What, exactly, is a memory palace?

演示起来容易解释起来难。下面是一个非常基本的例子：

It’s easier to demonstrate than to explain. Here’s a very basic example:

想象一下你在一个房间里。任何房间都可以。比如说，你家里。随便选一个房间。明白了吗？好的，现在想象一下，其中一面墙上画着一只巨大的、充血的眼睛。

Imagine that you are in a room. Any room. In your home, for example. Just choose a room at random. Got it? Okay, now imagine there is a giant, bloodshot eye painted on one of the walls.

这很奇怪吧？怎么会有人在你的墙上画一只巨大的、布满血丝的眼睛呢？

That’s weird, huh? Why the heck would anyone paint a giant, bloodshot eye on your wall?

现在，想象一下你从那个房间走到隔壁的房间。想象隔壁房间里有一个金属罐。任何种类的罐子都可以。油漆罐，或者豆子罐。它可以放在地板上，也可以放在家具上，或者用绳子吊在天花板上。随便你怎么想。

Now, picture yourself walking from that room to an adjacent room. Imagine that in the adjacent room there is a metal can. Any kind of can. A paint can, or a can of beans. It can be on the floor, or on a piece of furniture, or dangling from the ceiling by a piece of string. Whatever you want.

很简单，对吧？

Easy, right?

所以，在一个房间里，你看到一只巨大的、布满血丝的眼睛；在另一个房间里，你看到一个罐子。回到墙上画着眼睛的房间，大声说出你看到的。“眼睛。”

So, in one room you have a giant bloodshot eye, and in the next room, you have a can. Go back to the room with the eye painted on the wall, and say aloud what you see. “Eye.”

现在在心里“走”到下一个房间，大声说出你在那里看到的东西。“可以。”

Now mentally “walk” to the next room and say aloud what you see there. “Can.”

眼-罐。

Eye - Can.

或者用简单的英语来说，“我可以。”

Or, in plain English, “I can.”

好了，你刚刚创建了一个记忆宫殿。

There you go. You just created a memory palace.

* * *

* * *

你可能会觉得“眼睛能看懂”的例子很傻。记住一个只有两个词的句子，根本不需要古老的记忆体系。这么简单的体系真的能用来记住一篇千字的讲义吗？

You may be thinking that the “eye - can” example is silly. You don’t need an ancient memorization system to remember a two-word sentence. Can such a simple system really be used to memorize a thousand-word lecture?

绝对没错。我的经验之谈。用这个系统，成为共济会会员仅仅六个月后，我就在为初级学徒和大师级共济会会员讲授第三部分的课程。我每周只花几个小时构建记忆宫殿，就能记住这些部分。

Absolutely. I speak from experience. Using this system, only six months after becoming a Mason, I was giving the third section lectures for both the Entered Apprentice’s and Master Mason’s degree. I memorized these parts by devoting just a few hours each week to building memory palaces.

我不是火箭科学家，也没有记忆宫殿技巧的经验。在学习记忆宫殿之前，我发现即使是简化的学位水平测试也很难。

I am not a rocket scientist. Nor was I experienced in the memory palace technique. Prior to learning how to use a memory palace, I found even the abridged proficiency tests for the degrees challenging.

当然，记忆宫殿有效性的真正权威，是那些毕生致力于研究大脑、记忆和记忆法的研究人员和实践者。他们怎么说呢？

Of course, the real authorities on the effectiveness of memory palaces are those researchers and practitioners who have made the brain, memory, and memorization their life’s work. What do they have to say?

让我们先从那些铁杆练习者说起。你知道什么是脑力运动员吗？他们指的是在世界各地的比赛中，将自己的记忆与数百人的记忆进行比对。也许你在电视或网络上看到过他们的精彩表现。把27副扑克牌洗在一起，然后把这堆新的大牌交给其中一位，他们就能在不到一小时内记住每张牌的点数和花色。如果给他们30分钟，有些人甚至能记住一串4000个数字。

Let’s start with the hardcore practitioners. Do you know what a brain athlete is? It’s a person who matches his or her memory against the memories of hundreds of others in competitions around the world. Perhaps you’ve seen their exploits on television or the internet. Shuffle twenty-seven decks of playing cards together and hand the new giant stack to one of these individuals and they’ll be able to memorize the ranks and suits of every card in sequence in less than an hour. Given thirty minutes, some of them can memorize a string of four thousand numbers.

乔舒亚·福尔（Joshua Foer）在其通俗易懂、趣味十足的畅销书《与爱因斯坦月球漫步：记忆一切的艺术与科学》中，对这些运动员以及他们所处的竞争环境进行了精彩的概述。归根结底，这些人对记忆非常非常认真。

An excellent overview of these athletes and the competitive world they live in is captured in Joshua Foer’s fun and accessible best-seller, Moonwalking with Einstein: The Art and Science of Remembering Everything. The bottom line is that these are people who take memorization very, very seriously.

他们的秘密是什么？你猜对了。记忆宫殿。

What’s their secret? You guessed it. The memory palace.

根据《新科学家》杂志的文章《如何训练你的大脑像记忆冠军一样》：

Per the New Scientist article, How to Train Your Brain to Be Like a Memory Champion’s:

几乎所有记忆力超群的人都依赖的策略是“位置记忆法”，即想象一条他们熟悉的路线，例如在家或上班路上，并将要学习的信息与沿途的地标联系起来。之后，他们可以通过想象同样的路线，并观察与每个地标相关的物体来检索这些信息。

The strategy almost all top memorisers rely on is the ‘method of loci’, which involves imagining a route that they know well, such as moving around their home or traveling to work, and associating the information to be learned with landmarks along that route. They can then retrieve the information later on by making the same journey in their mind and seeing the objects connected to each landmark.

我之前提到过，记忆宫殿法的古称是“位置法” 。稍后会详细介绍。

As I mentioned earlier, method of loci is the ancient name for the memory palace technique. More on that later.

* * *

* * *

这时你可能会反驳说，你不是脑力运动员。没关系，你不需要。记忆宫殿技巧任何人都可以学习。最近的研究表明，只需六周的记忆宫殿学习，就能让普通人拥有卓越的记忆力。

At this point you might object that you are not a brain athlete. No problem. You don’t need to be. The memory palace technique can be learned by anyone. Recent studies have shown that just six weeks of memory palace study can give the average person a superior memory.

荷兰拉德堡德大学（Radboud University）的一项研究发现，脑力运动员的大脑（特别是那些使用记忆宫殿的人）在解剖学上与普通大脑相似，但运作方式却截然不同。从某种意义上说，记忆宫殿专家与我们其他人使用的是一样的电脑，只是操作系统不同。更有趣的是，即使没有试图记忆，记忆宫殿的大脑仍然会以不同的方式运作。这样的大脑似乎被彻底重新编程了。

One study conducted at Radboud University, in the Netherlands, found that brain athletes’ brains (specifically, those who used memory palaces) are anatomically like any other brains, but operate differently. In a sense, the memory palace experts are using the same computer as the rest of us but with a different operating system. More intriguingly, the memory palace brains continue to operate differently even when they aren’t trying to memorize something. Such brains appear to have been completely reprogrammed.

这一发现令研究人员大吃一惊，于是他们招募了一组受试者（其中没有一个是脑力运动员），并扫描了他们的大脑。结果不出所料。之后，研究人员教这些受试者如何使用记忆宫殿，并再次扫描他们的大脑。令人惊奇的是，受试者的大脑开始像脑力运动员一样运作——即使他们没有试图记住任何事情！就像脑力运动员一样，受试者的大脑似乎仅仅通过构建记忆宫殿的练习就被重新编程了。

Surprised at this finding, researchers brought in a group test subjects (none of them brain athletes) and scanned their brains. The results were unexceptional. Then they taught them how to use the memory palace and scanned their brains again. Amazingly, the brains of the test subjects began to operate just like those of the brain athletes – even when they weren’t trying to remember anything! Just like the brain athletes, the test subjects’ brains seemed to have been reprogrammed simply by the exercise of building memory palaces.

而且它们还拥有超强的记忆力。据《新科学家》杂志报道：

And they had developed excellent memories. As reported by New Scientist:

经过仅仅六周的训练，参与者在记忆测试中的表现提高了一倍多，扫描显示他们的大脑功能更像记忆力竞赛选手的大脑。

After just six weeks’ training, participants more than doubled their performance in a memory test, and scans showed their brains were functioning more like those of competitive memorisers.

记忆宫殿最大限度地利用了我们大脑的工作方式。记忆宫殿的创建和积累依赖于大脑中一个叫做海马体的区域，它拥有一些非常奇特且有用的功能。

Memory palaces take maximum advantage how our brains work. The creation and population of memory palaces relies on a part of the brain called the hippocampus, which has some very peculiar and useful abilities.

首先，它是空间意识的核心，即记住如何从一个地方到达另一个地方、利用地标确定自身位置以及计算不同地点之间距离的能力。它还能建立空间和时间之间的关系。这些技能对于人类的生存至关重要。

First, it is the seat of spatial awareness, or the ability to remember how to get from one place to another, use landmarks to determine where you are, and calculate the distances between locations. It also establishes relationships between space and time. These skills are critical for human survival.

其次，海马体巩固短期和长期记忆。

Second, hippocampus consolidates short-term and long-term memory.

第三，海马体是大脑中神奇的区域之一，新神经元在此产生，这一过程称为神经发生，可能在学习和记忆中发挥作用。

Third, the hippocampus is one of those magical regions of the brain where new neurons are created, a process referred to as neurogenesis, which may play a role in learning and memorization.

大脑的神经网络非常灵活。通过记忆宫殿进行记忆会开辟新的神经通路，一旦大脑接触到这些通路，即使没有构建记忆宫殿，大脑也会持续使用它们。这会给大脑的工作方式带来重大而持久的变化，从而带来卓越的记忆力。

The brain’s neural networks are flexible. Memorization through memory palaces opens up new neural pathways, and once the brain is introduced to those paths, it continues to use them even when a person isn’t building a memory palace. This results in major and long-lasting changes to how your brain works, which can lead to superior memory performance.

拉德堡德大学和其他机构的研究也表明，用老式的记忆方法——通过重复把知识灌输到脑子里——并没有持久的益处。你的大脑永远不会学习新的知识，虽然你最终可能会记住你正在学习的内容，但你记忆其他内容的能力却不会提高。

The studies done at Radboud University and other institutions also demonstrated that memorization done the old-fashioned way - pounding things into your head by repetition – has no lasting benefit. Your brain never learns new paths, and while you may eventually memorize whatever you’re studying, your ability to memorize other things will not improve.

* * *

* * *

所以，你懂的。看来古代建造“记忆宫殿”的人本能地知道一些我们最近才通过科学研究和脑力运动员的壮举重新发现的东西：如果你想拥有超强记忆力，而你又没有天赋，你可以自己建造一个。

So, there you go. It appears the ancient builders of mind palaces intuitively knew something we have only recently rediscovered through scientific studies and the exploits of brain athletes: If you want a superior memory and weren’t gifted with one, you can build one.

4

4

一些鼓励的话

Some Words of Encouragement

T哼着哼着读完这本书，你会遇到很多吓人的东西：拉丁文、日期、长得怪怪的、念不出来的名字、图表、清单和示意图。甚至还有附录！任何有附录的东西都不可能方便读者阅读，不是吗？

Thumbing through this book, you’re going to encounter a lot of scary-looking things: Latin, dates, weirdly long and unpronounceable names, charts, lists, and diagrams. There’s even an appendix! Nothing with an appendix can be user-friendly, can it?!

别慌。情况远没有看起来那么糟糕。以下是一些你应该了解的事情，以及一些建议：

Don’t panic. It’s not nearly as bad as it looks. Here are some things you should know, and a few pieces of advice:

  • 这不是一本教科书。构建记忆宫殿的基础知识非常简单，这些基础知识足以让你完成这项工作。本书包含了许多超越基础知识的信息，但大部分信息仅供参考。不要被这些额外的内容吓到。你真的不需要知道同音异义词、同音异义词和同形异义词之间的区别，也不需要知道徽章和符号之间的区别。无论你使用“记忆对象”、“图像”、“阴影”还是“看起来的样子”，这些术语都没关系。
  • This is not a textbook. The basics of building a memory palace are very simple, and the basics are all you need to get the job done. I’ve included a lot of information in this book that goes beyond the basics, but most of the information is for reference purposes only. Don’t let the extra stuff intimidate you. You don’t really need to know the difference between a homonym, a homophone, and a homograph, or the difference between an emblem and a symbol. It doesn’t matter if you use the term “Memory Objects” or “images” or “shadows” or “lookedy-look-looks.”
  • 构建记忆宫殿没有完美的方法。我提供的信息，只用你需要的部分。如果你想尝试我建议之外的其他方法，那就去做吧。如果你想到更好的主意，那就用它。如果有什么让你感到困惑，那就跳过它。我读过很多关于记忆宫殿的书籍和文章，但我并没有完全照搬其中任何一本。就像你一样，我选取了吸引我的点点滴滴，然后以一种最适合我大脑运作方式的方式将它们组合在一起。
  • There is no perfect way to construct a memory palace. Of the information I provide, use only what you need. If you want to do something other than what I suggest, go for it. If you come up with a better idea, use it. If something confuses you, skip it. I’ve read many books and articles on memory palaces and I don’t follow any of them to the letter. Like you will do, I took the bits and pieces that appealed to me and hobbled them together in a way that best suited how my brain works.
  • 按照自己的节奏记忆。制定自己的时间表。如果你每天能记住一个句子，没问题。如果你每天只能记住几个单词，也没问题。也许你一个月就能记住一堂课的内容。也许需要一年。也许需要两年。即使两年也比没有强，对吧？如果你觉得自己力不从心，那就放慢速度。慢慢来，但要坚持学习。
  • Memorize at your own pace. Set your own schedule. If you can memorize a sentence a day, that’s fine. If you only have time for few words a day, that’s fine also. Maybe you’ll memorize a lecture in a month. Maybe it will take a year. Maybe it will take two years. Even two years is better than never, right? If you ever feel like you’ve bitten off more than you can chew, slow down. Take smaller bites. But keep chewing.
  • 不要放弃。永远不要忘记，你帮助的不仅是你自己，也是你的分会。事实上，你是在帮助维护整个兄弟会。你将成为一个贡献者和参与者，而不是旁观者。
  • Don’t give up. Never forget that you are helping your lodge as much as you are helping yourself. You are, in fact, helping preserve the entire fraternity. You will become a contributor and participant instead of a spectator.
  • 通过背诵仪式、经文和讲稿，你将对其中的内容有深入的了解。聆听讲稿和为了记忆和背诵而研读讲稿是截然不同的两件事。记忆需要你专注于每一个字。通过记忆，你几乎肯定会发现很多你仅仅听别人讲课永远无法获得的东西。
  • In memorizing rites, parts, and lectures you will obtain an intimate knowledge of what is contained in them. Listening to a lecture and studying a lecture for purposes of memorization and recital are very different things. Memorization requires you to focus on every word. You are almost certain to make many discoveries through memorization that you would have never made simply listening to others.
  • 创建记忆宫殿确实会改变你的大脑运作方式，而且是以一种好的方式。学习如何创建记忆宫殿，或许能为你提供所需的技能和洞察力，从而创建其他对你作为共济会成员有益的心理“宫殿”。
  • Creating memory palaces literally changes how your brain works, and in a good way. Learning how to create memory palaces may provide you with the skills and insight needed to create other mental “palaces” beneficial to you as a Freemason.
  • 共济会的仪式、部分、讲座等内容之所以难以理解，不仅因为篇幅冗长，还因为句子的构成方式。共济会的语言古朴古老。对许多现代读者来说，词序似乎不自然，甚至毫无意义。这很像读莎士比亚的作品，只不过是用密码写的。难怪这么多共济会成员不愿死记硬背。记忆宫殿技巧通过将单词转化为你选择的物品来克服这些问题。按正确的顺序记住这些物品比按正确的顺序记住单词更容易，而且这些物品还能帮助你正确地发音。
  • The rites, parts, lectures, etc., of Freemasonry are difficult not only because of their length but because of the way the sentences are formed. The language is archaic. The order of the words seems unnatural – even nonsensical - to many modern readers. It’s a lot like reading Shakespeare, but in code. It’s no wonder that so many Masons shy away from memorization. The memory palace technique overcomes these issues by transforming the words into objects of your choosing. Remembering these objects in the correct order is easier than remembering the words in the right order, and the objects will help you pronounce the words correctly.
  • 最后，但或许对你们中的一些人来说最重要的一点是：建造记忆宫殿，并在其中填充记忆物品的人，所做的不仅仅是提升记忆力。他无意中学会了如何识别、探索、解构，或者说逆向工程那些由前几个世纪的其他人精心打造，并隐藏在一些最伟大的思想家的著作和插图中的记忆宫殿。如果你是一位旅行者，某些原本不可见的路标将会变得可见，跟随它们可能会带你到达新的、令人兴奋的地方。
  • Lastly, but perhaps most importantly for a few of you in the craft: a person who builds memory palaces, and populates them with memory objects, is doing more than just improving his memory. He is inadvertently learning how to recognize, navigate, and deconstruct, or reverse-engineer, the memory palaces carefully crafted by others in previous centuries and concealed in the writings and illustrations of some of our greatest thinkers. If you’re a traveller, certain waypoints that were invisible will become visible, and following them may lead you to new and exciting places.

5

5

记忆的类型

Types of Memorization

想要获得“单词记忆”的学生，其起点与“事物记忆”的学生相同；也就是说，他要记住那些用来存放图像的位置。但他面临的任务更为艰巨，因为记住一篇演讲的所有单词所需的位置，远比记住其概念所需的位置要多得多。

The student wishing to acquire ‘memory for words’ begins in the same way as the ‘memory for things’ student; that is to say he memorizes places which are to hold his images. But he is confronted with a harder task for far more places will be needed to memorize all the words of a speech than would be needed for its notions.

- 弗朗西斯·耶茨，《记忆的艺术》

- Frances Yates, The Art of Memory

T建造记忆宫殿来保存记忆，是一项古老的习俗，早在公元前就已存在，并经历了数个世纪的改良、忽视、嘲笑和赞扬。它是众多用于增强人工记忆（即通过训练提高记忆力）的方法之一。众多增强人工记忆的方法统称为“记忆的艺术”，尽管更确切地说，应该称之为“记忆的艺术”。

The building of memory palaces to retain memories is an ancient practice that pre-dates the birth of Christ and which has undergone centuries of refinement, neglect, ridicule, and praise. It is one of many methods that have been taught to increase artificial memory, which is simply memory improved by training. The numerous methods to enhance artificial memory are collectively known as the art of memory, though this might be more clearly understood as the art of memorization.

记忆宫殿通常用于以下两个目的之一：

Memory palaces are generally used for one of two purposes:

1. 帮助你记住一系列不同的项目，通常按照规定的顺序

1. To help you remember a list of distinct items, often in a prescribed sequence

2. 帮助您逐字逐句地记住长篇书面文章。

2. To help you remember long written passages verbatim (word-for-word).

这些通常被称为memoria rerum（事物的记忆）和memoria verborum（词语的记忆）。

These are commonly known as memoria rerum (memory of things) and memoria verborum (memory of words).

这些术语之所以是拉丁语，是因为这些技巧最早的记录是用拉丁语写的，而且自那时起，学者们也一直在使用它们。长期以来，提高记忆力一直被认为是一门艺术，而非科学。许多关于这个主题的权威文献都是几个世纪前由神学家、哲学家、科学家和神秘主义者撰写的，他们各自宣扬着自己的解读、理念和技巧。最早的手册和评论是用希腊语和拉丁语写的。后来，又增加了意大利语、西班牙语、法语和英语的版本。

These terms are Latin because our oldest records of the techniques are in Latin and scholars since then have continued to use them. Improvement of the memory has long been considered more art than science. Many of the most authoritative texts on the subject were written centuries ago by theologians, philosophers, scientists, and mystics, each promoting their own interpretations, agendas, and techniques. The earliest manuals and commentaries were written in Greek and Latin. Later additions were made in Italian, Spanish, French, and English.

在本书中，我试图将这些不同的来源整合、消化并重新引入，使其易于现代读者理解，同时，同样重要的是，也对我们古老教派的现代仪式实践者有所裨益。因此，本书中使用的一些方法和术语在其他资料中找不到——至少没有明确提及。我将一些复杂的概念提炼为精髓。只要有可能，我都会使用浅显易懂的英语来代替古语或外来语。

In this book, I’ve attempted to reconcile, digest, and reintroduce these varied sources in such a way that they are accessible to the modern reader, and, of equal importance, useful to the modern ritualists in our ancient fraternity. For that reason, some of the methods and terms I use in this book will not be found in other sources - at least not explicitly. I’ve distilled certain complicated concepts down to the essentials. Whenever possible I use plain English in lieu of archaic or foreign words.

为了遵循这一原则，我将把“memoria rerum”称为“列表记忆”，将“memoria verborum ”称为“逐字记忆”。下文将对此进行解释。

In keeping with that policy, I will be referring to memoria rerum as “list memorization” and memoria verborum as “verbatim memorization.” These are explained below.

列表记忆（memoria rerum）

List Memorization (memoria rerum)

列表记忆法是竞技脑力运动员使用的主要记忆系统。它用于记住一系列物品、事实、数字或谈话要点，通常按特定顺序排列。你可以用这个系统记住的东西包括购物清单、一长串数字、州名，或者一副扑克牌的顺序。

List Memorization is the primary system used by competitive brain athletes. It is used to remember a list of items, facts, numbers, or talking points, usually in a specific order. Things you might memorize using this system are a shopping list, a long string of numbers, the names of states, or the order of playing cards in a deck.

数千年来，列表记忆法一直受到政治家、演说家、讲师和律师的青睐，因为它可以用来记住个人想要演讲的一系列话题，以及这些话题的呈现顺序。这些人无需撰写演讲稿并逐字逐句地背诵。例如，一位政治家可能想与他的选民讨论以下话题：

List memorization was favored for thousands of years by politicians, orators, lecturers, and lawyers because it can be used to memorize a list of topics which an individual wishes to speak about, as well as the sequence in which the topics are to be presented. These individuals do not need to write a speech and memorize it word-for-word. A politician, for example, might want to discuss the following topics with his constituents:

  • 税收
  • taxes
  • 移民
  • immigration
  • 有组织的劳工
  • organized labor
  • 自然灾害
  • natural disasters
  • 战争
  • war

他的民调数据显示，选民最关心的是税收问题，因此他首先讨论这个问题至关重要。其他议题按重要性依次递减，战争目前是最重要的议题，因此他计划在演讲结束时简要谈及战争。为了准备这次演讲，他搭建了一个简单的五室记忆宫殿。一号房间里有一堆钱；二号房间里有一道铁丝网；三号房间里有一位拿着抗议标语牌的工会成员；四号房间里有一场火灾；五号房间里有一位士兵。

His polling data shows that voters are most concerned about taxes, so it’s important he discuss those first. The other topics are listed in descending order of importance, with war being, for now, the least important issue, so he plans on touching on that topic only briefly toward the close of his speech. In preparation for this speech he constructs a simple five-room memory palace. Room one contains a pile of money; room two, a barbed wire fence; room three, a union member with a picket sign; room four, a fire; and room five, a soldier.

确实，他可以在讲话时简单地参考索引卡来避免使用记忆放置。第一张卡片上可能写着“税收”，第二张卡片上写着“移民”等等。或者，他可以参考存储在智能手机上的项目符号列表。但如今，与过去一样，政客和其他公众演讲者在公开演讲时会避免使用参考资料。他们希望显得聪明自信，并且希望与听众保持目光接触。不断地瞥一眼智能手机或笨拙地摆弄索引卡或书面稿会破坏演讲者和听众之间的催眠联系。这就是为什么今天的高级官员使用提词器和耳机，它们就像记忆宫​​殿一样，对观众来说是看不见的。

True, he could avoid the use of a memory placing by simply referring to index cards while speaking. Card one might read, “Taxes,” card two “Immigration,” etc. Or he could refer to a bullet list he’s stored on his smart phone. But today, as in the past, politicians and other public speakers avoid the use of reference materials when speaking in public. They want to appear smart and confident, and they want to maintain eye contract with their listeners. Continually glancing at a smart phone or fumbling with index cards or a written script destroys the hypnotic connection between speaker and listener. That’s why today’s high-ranking officials use teleprompters and ear pieces, which, like memory palaces, are invisible to audiences.

事实上，这就是为什么我们的老朋友“卡尔”在《论证论》一书中专门设立了关于记忆的章节。记住，这本书讲的是说服性演讲，而不是记忆。这本书的大部分内容与记忆无关。但是，就像今天一样，如果一位公众演讲者中断与听众的目光接触，转而查阅笔记，他的说服力就会大打折扣。

In fact, this is why our old friend “Carl” included a section on memory in Ad Herennium. Remember, the book was about persuasive speaking, not memory. Most of the book has nothing to do with memory. But then, as today, a public speaker was a lot less persuasive if he broke eye contact with his audience to refer to his notes.

逐字记忆（memoria verborum）

Verbatim Memorization (memoria verborum)

逐字记忆，又称单词记忆，用于逐字逐句地记住演讲、角色、讲座等内容。巧合的是，“verbatim”（逐字记忆）是一个拉丁词，至今仍被英语使用者使用和理解。逐字记忆显然比列表记忆需要付出更多努力，因为你需要创造更多的空间和记忆对象。你不是仅仅记住列表上的条目，而是试图记住整段——实际上是整页——逐字逐句地记住。

Verbatim Memorization, or memory of words, is used to memorize a speech, role, lecture, etc., word-for word. It is a happy coincidence that “verbatim” is a Latin word still used and understood by English speakers today. Verbatim memorization obviously requires much more effort than list memorization because you’ll need to create a lot more Spaces and Memory Objects. Instead of remembering just a list of items, you’re attempting to memorize entire paragraphs – entire pages, in fact. Word-for-word.

以下场景应该可以帮助您理解列表和逐字记忆技术之间的区别。

The following scenarios should help you understand the difference between list and verbatim memorization techniques.

想象一下，在一所学校里，一位名叫贝克夫人的科学老师要求她的学生记住太阳系所有行星的名称、它们与太阳的距离，以及它们卫星的数量和名称。这可不是一件容易的事。仅土星就有超过五十颗卫星！

Imagine a school in which a science teacher, Mrs. Baker, has instructed her students to remember the names of all the planets in our solar system, the planets’ distances from the sun, and the number and names of each their moons. This is no easy task. Saturn alone has over fifty moons!

幸运的是，贝克老师教会了学生们如何使用列表记忆法来构建记忆宫殿。每个学生都认真地运用这项技术记住所有需要的信息，将每颗行星放在记忆宫殿的特定房间里，然后小心翼翼地将相应的卫星摆放在角落、家具顶部、灯具内等等。

Luckily for the students, Mrs. Baker has taught them how to build memory palaces using the list memorization technique. Each student dutifully uses the technique to memorize all the information required, placing each planet in a specific room of his or her memory palace and then carefully placing the corresponding moons into corners, atop furniture, inside lamps, etc..

一周后，贝克老师让几名学生在课堂上站起来，说出土星的卫星名称。令她欣喜的是，他们都答对了。然而，他们说的并不完全一样。一个学生可能按字母顺序列出土星的卫星。第二个学生可能按它们与土星的距离排序。第三个学生则按从大到小的顺序排列。即使所有学生都记住了卫星的顺序，他们仍然会用自己的话来描述这个顺序。一个学生可能会说：“离土星最近的卫星是米纳斯……”，而另一个学生可能会说：“离土星最近的卫星叫米纳斯……”等等。确切的措辞并不重要，只要列表正确即可。

A week later, Mrs. Baker asks several students to stand up in class and name the moons of Saturn. To her joy, they all answer correctly. Yet they do not all say the same thing. One student might identify Saturn’s moons in alphabetical order. The second might identify them in order of their proximity to Saturn. The third, from largest to smallest. Even if all of the students memorized the moons in the same order, they’d still use their own words to describe that order. One might say, “The nearest moon to Saturn is Minas...” while another could say, “The moon closest to Saturn is called Minas...” and so on. The exact words don’t matter, so long as the list is correct.

在这种情况下，列表记忆对学生很有帮助。

In this situation, list memorization has served the students well.

然而，隔壁的美国历史老师史密斯先生却要求学生们背诵葛底斯堡演说。他的学生不像贝克夫人的学生那样有“奢侈”的条件，他们没有回旋的余地。每个学生都必须按照林肯讲话的顺序，背诵每一个字。如果要求在课堂上背诵演讲稿，每个学生都必须背诵完全相同的内容。

But, next door, Mr. Smith, an American History teacher, has tasked his students to memorize the Gettysburg Address. His students don’t have the luxury of Mrs. Baker’s students. They have no wiggle room. Every student will need to memorize every word of Lincoln’s speech in the exact order in which Lincoln spoke them. If asked to recite the speech in class, every student will be expected to say exactly same thing.

在这种情况下，列表记忆是行不通的。史密斯先生的学生需要的是逐字记忆。

In this scenario, list memorization won’t get the job done. What Mr. Smith’s students need is verbatim memorization.

展望未来

Going Forward

本书的其余部分将致力于教你如何构建一个可用于逐字记忆的记忆宫殿。由于这种方法只是将列表记忆提升到了一个更高的层次，因此你实际上会同时学习这两种方法。你选择使用哪一种取决于你的需求、能力和偏好。如果你擅长记忆句子甚至段落，并且你只需要一种组织思路的方法，那么列表记忆可能就足够了。在这种情况下，你真正需要的只是一系列记忆对象，它们会提醒你每个段落的内容及其在正确顺序中的位置。

The rest of this book is dedicated to teaching you how to build a memory palace that can be used for verbatim memorization. Because this approach is simply list memorization taken to a much higher level, you’ll actually be learning both methods at once. Which you elect to use depends on your needs, abilities and preferences. If you are good at memorizing sentences or even paragraphs, and you simply need a way to organize your thoughts, list memorization may be sufficient. In such cases all you really need is a series of Memory Objects that will remind you of the content of each paragraph and its place in the proper order of things.

如果你需要帮助记忆单词本身，你可以使用逐字记忆法。这种方法需要为每个单词或词组创建一个记忆对象。因此，这种方法比列表记忆法更复杂，需要的时间也更多。

If you need help memorizing the words themselves, you’ll want to use the verbatim approach. It requires the creation of a Memory Object for every word, or cluster of words. It is thus more complex and requires much more time than list memorization.

6

6

建筑学

Architecture

“人工记忆包括背景和图像。我所说的背景是指自然或人工营造的小规模、完整且醒目的场景，以便我们能够通过自然记忆轻松地掌握和拥抱它们。”

- Ad Herennium

“The artificial memory includes backgrounds and images. By backgrounds I mean such scenes as are naturally or artificially set off on a small scale, complete and conspicuous, so that we can grasp and embrace them easily by the natural memory.”

- Ad Herennium

T记忆宫殿有两个主要组成部分：

There are two primary components to a memory palace:

模型

The Model

模型是现实世界位置的心理图像，例如你的房子、学校、杂货店等。模型的目的是提供结构并组织你的记忆对象（接下来会讨论）。它确保你以正确的顺序记忆和背诵单词。从历史上看，这些被称为loci，在拉丁语中是地点的意思。这就是为什么记忆宫殿技术通常被称为位置法，即位置法。从共济会的角度来看，模型类似于一块空白的描图纸，而你的记忆对象类似于在描图纸上绘制的标志或符号。记忆宫殿非常像描图纸，只不过它们只存在于你的脑海中，并且是三维的。或者，你可以将你的模型想象成一本空白页的日记，而将记忆对象想象成你将在日记中绘制的图画。

The model is a mental image of a real-world location, such as your house, school, grocery store, etc. The Model’s purpose is to provide structure and organize your Memory Objects, discussed next. It ensures that you’ll memorize and recite the words in the correct order. Historically, these have been referred to as loci, which is Latin for places. That is why the memory palace technique is often referred to as the Method of Loci, i.e., the Location Method. Masonically, a Model is analogous to a blank tracing board, and your Memory Objects are analogous to the emblems or symbols drawn or painted on that tracing board. Memory palaces are very much like tracing boards, except that they exist only in your mind, and are three-dimensional. Alternatively, you can think of your Model as a journal of blank pages, and the Memory Objects as drawings you’ll be making in that journal.

内存对象

Memory Objects

记忆对象是指在脑海中对物体的想象，它们能提醒你需要记住的概念或词汇。在其他新旧书籍中，这些可能被称为助记符、助记对象、形容词或想象。

Memory Objects are mental visions of objects that remind you of concepts or words you need to memorize. In other books, old and new, these might be referred to as mnemonics, mnemonic objects, adjects, or imagines.

Mnemonic是一个古希腊词，既可以作形容词（“与记忆有关”），也可以作名词（“帮助记忆的东西”）。n之前的m不发音。我不会用这个词，因为我觉得它会让英语读者读得磕磕绊绊。任何单词以mn开头都会显得有些不自然，而且会让人分心。我向那些纯粹主义者致歉。

Mnemonic is an old Greek word which can be either an adjective (“pertaining to memory”) or a noun (“a thing that assists the memory”). The m before the n is silent. I won’t be using that term because I think it causes English readers to stumble. There’s something unnatural about starting any word with mn and it can be very distracting. My apologies to the purists.

Imagines 的意思是“想象的事物”或“心理图像”。如今，这个词通常被翻译成英文为image。我不喜欢image这个术语，因为它暗示了一种被心灵之眼“看到”的二维事物，比如绘画或照片。但用来记忆单词的事物最好被想象成三维的。想象的事物更好，但你下面描述的 Model 也是想象出来的（尽管通常是真实地点的想象版本）。我们需要一个术语来将 Model 与用来记忆单词的事物区分开来。因此，在本书中，我们将使用Memory Object这个术语。

Imagines means “imagined things” or “mental pictures.” Today, this term is most often translated into English as image. I don’t like the term image because it implies a two-dimensional thing which is “seen” by the mind’s eye, like a painting or photograph. But the things used to remember words are best imagined as three-dimensional. Imagined things is better, but your Model, described below, is also imagined (though typically an imagined version of a real place). We need a term this distinguishes the Model from the things used to remember words. So, in this book, we’ll use the term Memory Object.

你可能会想，为什么要费心记住两套东西（记忆对象及其相关词汇），而不是一套（词汇）。这难道不效率低下吗？你不是把需要记住的东西翻倍了吗？为什么不干脆用老办法，一遍遍地读，直到牢牢记住所有知识点？你在学校不就是这么做的吗？这难道还不够有效吗？

You might wonder why you should bother memorizing two sets of things (Memory Objects and their related words) instead of just one set of things (the words). Isn’t that inefficient? Aren’t you basically doubling the amount of stuff you need to memorize? Why not just do things the old-fashioned way and read, read, and re-read all your material until it gets pounded into your head? Isn’t that what you did in school? Didn’t that work well enough?

这是个好问题。事实上，数千年来，对记忆宫殿逐字记忆法持批评态度的人一直在指责它。即使是罗马修辞学家昆体良（约公元35年-约公元100年），这位将记忆宫殿作为基本记忆手段的著名支持者之一，也认为它对记忆长篇大论毫无用处。他写道：“然而，它（记忆宫殿）在保留词性方面却作用不大……这种技巧又怎能掌握一系列连贯的词语呢……我们说话的流畅性难道不会不可避免地因为记忆中强加的双重任务而受到阻碍吗？因为，如果我们必须回顾每个单词的不同形式，又怎么能指望我们在连贯的言语中流畅地表达呢？”

It’s a good question. In fact, critics of the verbatim form of the memory palace have leveled that accusation against the technique for thousands of years. Even the Roman rhetorician Quintilian (c. 35 – c. 100 AD), one of the most famous proponents of the system as a basic memory device, thought it useless for remembering long passages. He wrote, “It [the memory palace] will however be of less service in retaining the parts of a speech...how can such an art grasp a whole series of connected words...will not the flow of our speech inevitably be impeded by the double task imposed on our memory? For how can our words be expected to flow in connected speech, if we have to look back at separate forms for each individual word?”

即使那些承认该技术有效的人也常常会大声质疑建立记忆宫殿的努力是否值得。

Even those who acknowledge that the technique is effective often wonder aloud whether the effort of building a memory palace is worth the reward.

弗朗西斯·耶茨写道：“毫无疑问，这种方法对任何愿意认真练习记忆术的人都会有效”，但他也承认，“我自己从未尝试过……”尽管作者戴维·史蒂文森得出结论认为“该系统显然有效”，但他指出，“对记忆艺术的第一反应很可能是，它肯定会阻碍而不是帮助不幸的演说家……”而作者罗伯特·库珀写道：“从罗马时期流传下来的大量材料表明，这种技术效果很好，而且被广泛使用……”然而，“在今天的世界，我们可能会认为这种技术很奇怪，甚至很荒谬……”

Frances Yates wrote “There is no doubt that this method will work for anyone who is prepared to labour seriously at these mnemonic gymnastics,” yet admitting, “I have never attempted to do so myself…” Though concluding that “the system evidently worked,” author David Stevenson noted that, “A first reaction to the art of memory is likely to be that it would surely hinder rather than help the unfortunate orator...” And author Robert Cooper writes that “the amount of material that has come down to us from the Roman period shows that the technique worked well and was widely used...” yet, “In today’s world we may think this technique strange, even absurd...”

平心而论，大多数撰写记忆宫殿相关著作的历史学家并非实践者，他们也并非故作姿态。他们的著作为理解记忆宫殿的历史以及记忆艺术提供了宝贵的洞见，对此我们深表感激。这些著作精彩绝伦，我愿意向所有人推荐。但它们是历史著作，而非自助书籍。

To be fair, most historians who write about memory palaces are not practitioners. They do not pretend to be. Their books provide valuable insight into the history of memory palaces and the art of memory in general, and for that we are indebted to them. They are fantastic books I’d recommend to anyone. But they are histories, not self-help books.

让我澄清一些人（不一定是这些作者）对使用记忆宫殿进行逐字记忆的一些误解。

Let me clear up a few misconceptions some people (not necessarily these authors) have about using memory palaces for verbatim memorization.

第一，在诵读时，修行者必须先想着记忆对象，然后等待相应的词语浮现在脑海中，这导致诵读速度缓慢、费力，有时还不方便。

The first is that, during recitation, a practitioner must first think of the Memory Object and then wait for the corresponding word to come to him, which results in a slow, laborious, and at times, awkward, recitation.

第二，用来记忆单词的记忆对象必须被永久记住。这意味着，如果你忘记了一个记忆对象，你也会忘记与之相关的单词。

The second is that a Memory Object used to memorize a word must be forever remembered. This would mean that if you forget a Memory Object you’ll also forget the word or words associated with it.

如果这两个反对意见成立，我同意记忆宫殿并不适合逐字记忆。幸运的是，它们并不准确。事实上，你不需要记住你用来构建记忆宫殿的记忆对象——至少不需要记住太久。事实上，你甚至可能在起身背诵你记住的内容之前就忘记了它们。

If these two objections were valid, I’d agree that a memory palace is not suited for verbatim memorization. Fortunately, they are not accurate. You don’t, in fact, need to remember the Memory Objects you used to build your memory palace - not for long, anyway. In fact, you may forget them even before you stand up in lodge and recite what you’ve memorized.

记忆对象是暂时的。它们就像你第一次尝试记忆一段文字时，用来将正确单词刻印到你大脑中的模具。你可以把它们想象成歪牙上的牙套，断臂上的石膏，或是儿童自行车上的辅助轮。记忆对象塑造你的记忆的方式也大致相同。它们并非永久存在。它们会在你的记忆中停留几个小时、几天、几周或几个月，最终逐渐消失。

Memory Objects are temporary. They are like molds used to impress the correct words into your brain when you first endeavor to memorize a passage. Think of them like braces on crooked teeth, or a cast on a broken arm, or training wheels on child’s bicycle. The Memory Objects mold your memory in much the same way. They are not intended to be permanent. They’ll remain in your memory for a few hours, days, weeks, or months, before eventually receding into the background.

但这些话将会保留下来。

But the words will remain.

《Ad Herennium》的作者似乎深谙此道，他写道：“……这种意象的编排只有当我们用符号来激发自然记忆时才能成功。因此，我们首先要把某一节经文背诵两三遍，然后用图像来表达这些文字。这样，艺术就能补充自然。因为单靠艺术和自然都不够强大……”

The author of Ad Herennium seems to have understood this, writing, “…such an arrangement of images succeeds only if we use our notation to stimulate the natural memory, so that we first go over a given verse twice or three times to ourselves and then represent the words by means of images. In this way art will supplement nature. For neither by itself will be strong enough…”

一旦单词在我们脑海中扎根，记忆对象就永远消失了吗？那些模具会被打破并丢弃吗？我不知道。我记忆中用来记忆讲座的记忆对象，现在能回忆起的不到5%，但我感觉它们仍然在那里，就像幽灵一样，在我的大脑的某个角落。也许它们仍然在默默地将我的单词固定在某个地方。也许它们已经沉入我的潜意识，但仍在发挥着某种作用。我可以肯定地说，我很少会为那些我记忆超过一个月的讲座中的任何单词召唤记忆对象。单词是自然而然地出现的。

Are the Memory Objects forever lost once the words have taken root in our brains? Are the molds broken and discarded? I don’t know. I can recall fewer than 5% of the Memory Objects I used to memorize lectures, yet I feel they are still there, like ghosts, in some part of my mind. Perhaps they are still anchoring my words in place, unseen. Perhaps they have sunk into my subconscious but are still performing some purpose. What I can say, with confidence, is that I rarely summon Memory Objects for any words in those lectures I’ve known for more than a month. The words come automatically.

如果你对此感到惊讶，不妨想想，我们小时候学习字母表中的每个字母及其发音，阅读小学课本时，也会非常小心地发出单词中每个字母的音。直到我们读出一个书面单词的最后一个字母，我们才知道这个词是什么，以及它所指代的意思。

If this surprises you, consider that, as children, we learn each letter of the alphabet and its pronunciation, and when we read elementary texts we take great care to pronounce each letter of a word. It’s not until we pronounce the last letter of a written word that we know what the word is, and what it alludes to.

然而，作为成年人，我们仅仅通过浏览电脑屏幕或纸张上的单词来理解文字，却不关注单个字母及其发音。这是否意味着我们小时候学习字母和单词的发音毫无意义？当然不是。那是学习过程中必不可少的一个阶段。我们今天不像最初那样学习阅读，这无关紧要。一个阶段自然而然地先于另一个阶段。

Yet as adults, we grasp what is written by merely scanning the words on a computer screen or piece of paper, paying no attention to the individual letters or how they are pronounced. Does this mean it was pointless for us to learn the pronunciation of the letters and words as children? Of course not. That was a necessary stage in the learning process. That we don’t read today as we were initially taught to read is irrelevant. One phase naturally preceded the other.

记忆对象的工作原理类似。我们用它们将单词以正确的顺序深深地印入大脑。完成后，记忆对象就可以被丢弃了。

Memory Objects work in a similar manner. We use them to deeply impress words into our brains, in the proper order. When that is done, the Memory Objects can be discarded.

然而，模型会保留在原处，单词也会依附于它。换句话说，尽管记忆对象会随着时间的推移而消失，但你会发现你记住的单词仍然与模型中的特定位置相关联。因此，即使记忆对象消失了，你仍然可能会发现自己的思绪在旧的记忆宫殿中徘徊，同时背诵着你记住的某些部分。你的心眼会聚焦于该记忆对象先前的位置，而这个位置本身就能触发单词。通过这种奇妙的方式，后面讨论的焦点取代了记忆对象，并最终发挥着相同的作用。

The Model, however, will remain in place, and the words will remain attached to it. Put another way, though the Memory Objects tend to evaporate over time, you’ll find that the words you’ve memorized remain associated with specific locations within your Model. Consequently, you may still find your mind wandering your old memory palace while reciting some part that you’ve memorized even if the Memory Objects are gone. Your mind’s eye will focus on the former location of that Memory Object, and the location can, by itself, trigger the word. In this curious way, the Focus Points later discussed take the place of the Memory Objects, and ultimately serve the same purpose.

非实践者提出的另一个反对意见是，使用记忆宫殿进行逐字记忆会在某种程度上妨碍学生掌握所记内容的含义。这种反对意见认为，人们头脑中杂乱的记忆对象使得他们能够记住所需的单词，而无需真正理解自己在说什么。

Another objection made by non-practitioners is that the use of memory palaces for verbatim memorization somehow prevents a student from grasping the meaning of what is being memorized. This objection assumes the jumble of Memory Objects in a person’s head allows him to remember the required words without actually comprehending what he is talking about.

然而，同样的论点也适用于死记硬背，即用老式的方法记住单词、句子和段落——阅读、重复、阅读、重复，直到记住为止。人们很容易重复死记硬背的单词，而无法理解这些单词的整体含义。

Yet this same argument could be made against rote memory, i.e., memorizing words, sentences, and paragraphs the old-fashioned way - reading and repeating, reading and repeating, until the words stick. It is easy for a person to regurgitate words memorized through rote efforts without comprehending what the words mean, as a whole.

记忆宫殿至少需要你思考你正在记忆的单词以及它们之间的联系。死记硬背只需要你能够像鹦鹉学舌一样背诵它们。

The memory palace at least requires you to think about the words you’re memorizing and how they connect to one another. Rote memorization merely requires that you be able to parrot them.

7

7

内存对象

Memory Objects

任何映入眼帘的事物都会立即引起人们的注意，并在记忆中留下严肃而庄严的真理。

- 威廉·普雷斯顿，《石工插图》（1775年）

Everything that strikes the eye more immediately engages the attention, and imprints on the memory serious and solemn truths.

- William Preston, Illustrations of Masonry (1775)

一个记忆对象是你用想象力创造的一个或一组东西，然后放置在记忆宫殿中的特定位置，以提醒你一个或多个单词。

A Memory Object is a thing or group of things that you create with your imagination and then place in a specific location in your memory palace to remind you of a word or words.

“事物”在用于记忆对象时含义非常广泛。事物包括人、物体、动物、阳光、闪电、阴影、雾气、植物、颜色等等。无论“它”是什么，只要你能看到、感觉到、触摸到、尝到或听到，它都可以作为记忆对象，或者作为记忆对象的组成部分。

“Thing” has a very broad meaning when applied to Memory Objects. Things include people, objects, animals, sunlight, lightning, shadows, mist, plants, colors, and much more. If you can see, feel, touch, taste, or hear it, whatever “it” is, that thing can be used as a Memory Object, or as a component of a Memory Object.

如果你正在努力记住“友善行为”这句话，你的记忆对象可能是一位身穿条纹囚服的囚犯。他面对着你，双臂高举，仿佛要投降。他的右手握着一支带高倍瞄准镜的步枪。左手抓着一只鸭子。他的头可不是普通的头——事实上，那是一头牛！不知为何，他的囚服胸前绣着一个巨大的“E”。也许他的名字叫艾德？

If you were trying to memorize the phrase, “Amiable Conduct, ” your Memory Object could be a convict in a striped prisoner’s uniform. He stands facing you, his arms raised in the air, as if surrendering. In his right hand, he holds a rifle with a powerful scope. In his left hand, he holds a duck. His head isn’t a normal head – in fact, it’s the head of a bull! For some reason, a giant “E” has been stitched on to the front of his uniform. Maybe his name is Ed?

在你的脑海中顺时针移动，你会看到：一支带瞄准镜（瞄准）的步枪，一个牛头囚犯头上的字母“E”，以及一只鸭子。这给了你一个由“瞄准”+“E”+“牛”+“con”+“鸭子”组成的记忆对象。

Moving clockwise in your mind’s eye, you see this: a rifle with scope (aim), an “E” on a convict with a bull’s head, and a duck. This gives you the Memory Object consisting of aim+E+bull+con+duck.

和蔼可亲的行为。

Amiable Conduct.

这画面很奇怪，不是吗？不过，你很快就会明白，记忆对象越奇怪，就越容易记住。

It’s a weird image, isn’t it? But as you’ll learn, the weirder the Memory Object, the easier it is to remember.

此示例演示了记忆对象可能由多个事物组成。实际上，将一组事物聚集在一起形成一个记忆对象是很正常的。英语中的大多数单词，尤其是多音节单词，都需要这样做。在很多情况下，你可以将整个句子压缩成一个记忆对象。

This example demonstrates that a Memory Object may consist of multiple things. In fact, it’s normal to cluster a group of things together to form a Memory Object. Most words in the English language, especially ones with several syllables, will require it. There are many situations in which you can squeeze an entire sentence into a single Memory Object.

你可能会问：“如果一个记忆对象可以由多个元素组成，我该如何区分它们呢？如果它们并排摆放，岂不是看起来像一堆垃圾？”

This might lead you to ask “If a Memory Object can be composed of several things, how can I distinguish one Memory Object from the next? Aren’t all of them, side by side, just going to resemble a collection of junk?”

否，原因如下：

No, and for the following reasons:

首先，作为一条规则，聚集在一起形成记忆对象的所有事物必须彼此物理接触。

First, as a rule, all the things you cluster to together to form a Memory Object must be in physical contact with one another.

其次，正如稍后将讨论的，每个记忆对象都占据一个单独的焦点，焦点是更大区域内的特定位置。这些焦点通常彼此相距一臂之遥。这有助于你将记忆对象彼此隔离。

Second, as will be discussed later, each Memory Object occupies a single Focal Point, which is a specific location within a larger Area. These Focal Points are, in general, an arm’s length from one another. This will help you keep your Memory Objects segregated from one another.

根据您的需要，可以采用三种方式之一使用内存对象。

Memory Objects can be used in one of three ways, depending on your needs.

单独使用

Used Alone

这是使用记忆对象最简单但最不全面的方法，由前面提到的 Quintillian 等记忆艺术评论家推广。这只是记忆对象的构建，也就是说，你不是在构建记忆宫殿。相反，你以最适合自己的方式（也许使用老式的死记硬背法）记住讲座或部分内容，但为特别困难的单词、句子或句子的片段构建记忆对象。在这里，记忆对象的目的只是帮助你解决你正在努力的部分。如果一个词是古词（今天不再使用）或者句子的结构对你来说不合逻辑，这种方法会特别有用。大脑可能会顽固地抵制记住它不喜欢的东西。

This is the simplest but least comprehensive method of using Memory Objects, and was promoted by art of memory commentators such as Quintillian, already mentioned. This is the construction of Memory Objects only, i.e., you are not building a memory palace. Instead, you memorize your lecture or part in whatever way suits you best (perhaps using the old-fashioned rote repetition method) but build Memory Objects for particularly difficult words, sentences, or portions of sentences. Here, the Memory Object's purpose is to help you only with the part you're struggling with. This can be particularly useful if a word is archaic (not used today) or if the sentence is structured in a way that seems illogical to you. The brain can be stubbornly resistant to memorizing something it doesn't like.

例如，想象一下你正在尝试记住《仲夏夜之梦》中的这句台词：

For example, imagine that you're trying to memorize this line from A Midsummer Night's Dream:

唉，我读过的所有书，

听过的故事或历史，

真爱之路从来都不是平坦的，

但要么是血统不同……

Ay me, for aught that I could ever read,

Could ever hear by tale or history,

The course of true love never did run smooth,

But either it was different in blood…

也许你已经掌握了除了“哎，我，为了你”之外的所有单词，因为感觉不对劲。你的大脑不喜欢这些单词，也不喜欢它们的顺序。于是，你创造了一个记忆对象：一个眼球被收缩包裹在一包肉里（真恶心！——但令人难忘！），周围缠着一根打了四个结的绳子。眼球-肉-四个结=哎，我，为了你。

Perhaps you have mastered all the words except "Ay me, for aught," because it just doesn't feel right. Your brain doesn't like the words or the order of them. Consequently, you create a Memory Object consisting of an eyeball shrink-wrapped into a package of meat (yuck! - but memorable!), surrounded by a rope with four knots in it. Eye-meat-four-knot = Ay me, for aught.

请注意，这不是记忆宫殿（位置法）的方法，因为你没有将记忆对象放置在模型中（因此，没有位置，即位置）。换句话说，你不是在构建记忆宫殿。你只是根据需要随意使用记忆对象，它们在你的脑海中彼此独立地存在。

Note that this is not a memory palace (method of loci) approach because you are not placing the Memory Object in a Model (thus, there are no loci, i.e., locations). In other words, you aren’t building a memory palace. You're just using Memory Objects here and there, as needed, and they exist in your mind independent of one another.

如果这是您唯一的需要，您可以跳过第 10 章至第 23 章。

If this is your only need, you should can skip Chapters 10 through 23.

一起使用

Used Together

如前所述，在记忆宫殿的战略位置放置多个记忆对象，不仅能帮助你记住单词，还能帮助你记住这些单词的顺序。一个记忆宫殿可能容纳数十个、数百个甚至数千个记忆对象。正是这些记忆对象的摆放位置以及它们之间的相互作用，才能在一个原本拥挤混乱的心理结构中维持秩序。

As discussed earlier, the placement of multiple Memory Objects at strategic locations within your memory palace will help you to remember not only words, but the order of those words. A memory palace may house dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of memory objects. It is the placement of these objects, and their interactions with one another, that maintains order in what would otherwise be a very crowded and messy mental construct.

8

8

记忆对象的性质

The Qualities of Memory Objects

米emory 对象应该具备四个主要特质：

Memory Objects should have four primary qualities:

  1. 它们必须是明智的事情，而不是智力的事情
  2. They must be sensible things, not intellectual things
  3. 它们一定是人造的东西，而不是真实的东西
  4. They must be artificial things, not real things
  5. 他们应该很奇怪
  6. They should be strange
  7. 它们应该是个人的
  8. They should be personal

明智的事情

Sensible Things

我所说的“明智”是什么意思？可能和你的想法不一样。如今，“明智”的意思是通情达理、务实或谨慎。例如，为退休储蓄是明智之举。如果一个兄弟即将做一件蠢事，你可能会警告他“要明智”，或者“醒悟过来！”

What do I mean by sensible? Probably not what you think. Today, sensible means reasonable, or practical, or prudent. Saving money for retirement is a sensible thing to do, for example. If a brother is about to do something stupid, you might warn him to “be sensible,” or to “come to your senses!”

但我们不会用这个词的现代定义。我们会用“sensible”这个词最初的用法，尤其是那些学习记忆宫殿的学生。这种用法更……嗯，更合理。

But we’re not going to use that modern definition of the word. We’re going to use sensible as it was originally used, particularly by students of memory palaces. It’s a usage that makes more…well, sense.

这里是：

Here it is:

感知 = 任何可以被感知的事物。

Sensible = anything that can be sensed.

或者换句话说，任何可以被五感感知的事物，即视觉、听觉、触觉、嗅觉或味觉感知到的事物，都属于可感知的事物。例子几乎无穷无尽，例如汽车、房屋、花朵、人、云朵、行星和岩石。

Or, put another way, a sensible thing is anything that can be detected by the five senses, i.e., seen, heard, touched, smelled, or tasted. The examples are almost infinite, but include things like cars, houses, flowers, people, clouds, planets, and rocks.

勒内·笛卡尔（1596-1650）在《私人思想》（ Cogitationes Privatae ）中写道：“正如想象力使用图形来构思物体一样，理智也使用可感知的物体，例如风和光，来代表精神事物……可感知的事物可以帮助我们构思奥林匹克事物：风象征着精神，时间的运动象征着生命，光象征着理解，热象征着爱，而突发事件则象征着创造。”

In Cogitationes Privatae (“Private Thoughts”), René Descartes (1596-1650) wrote, “as the imagination uses figures to conceive of bodies, so the intellect uses sensible bodies, like the wind and light, for representing spiritual things…Sensible things can help us to conceive of Olympian things: the wind signifies the spirit, motion of time signifies life, light signifies understanding, heat signifies love, and sudden activity signifies creation.”

知识性事物

Intellectual Things

难道所有事物不都是合乎情理的吗？不。比如说道德。你知道道德是什么，但它是什么样子？味道如何？听起来又是什么？它会从架子上掉下来砸到你的头上吗？它的颜色是什么？质地是什么？尺寸是多少？一个鞋盒里能装下多少道德？

Aren’t all things sensible? No. Consider, for example, morality. You know what morality is, but what does it look like? Taste like? What does it sound like? Can it fall off a shelf and hit you on the head? What is its color? Its texture? What are its dimensions? How many moralities can you fit into a shoebox?

道德无法被感官感知。它是一个智力概念。诸如道德、勇气、恐惧、嫉妒和正义之类的事物，无法被五种感官感知，被称为智力事物。弗朗西斯·培根爵士在其关于记忆宫殿的讨论中写道：“象征将智力事物降格为感性事物；因为感性事物总是比智力事物更能打动记忆，也更能迅速地展现出来。”

Morality is undetectable by the senses. It is an intellectual concept. Things like morality, courage, fear, envy, and justice, which cannot be sensed by the five senses, are called intellectual things. In his discussion on memory palaces, Sir Francis Bacon wrote, “Emblems bring down intellectual things to sensible things; for what is sensible, always strikes the Memory stronger, and sooner expresses itself, than what is intellectual.”

换句话说，像剑这样感性的事物，比像骑士精神这样理性的事物更容易被记住。事实上，我敢打赌，你们很多人一看到“骑士精神”这个词，就会立刻想到中世纪的骑士。

In other words, it is easier to remember a sensible thing, such as a sword, than an intellectual thing, such as chivalry. In fact, I would wager that many of you, upon reading the word chivalry, immediately thought of a medieval knight.

为什么？因为骑士是理智的。我们从书籍和电影中了解骑士的形象。我们想象他们身披铠甲，能听到他们行走时盔甲的铿锵声。我们能想象阳光照耀着他们的铠甲，能想象他们拯救少女，或手持长矛相互厮杀。

Why? Because a knight is sensible. We know from books and movies what knights looked like. We envision them in suits of armor. We can hear the clang of the armor as they walk. We can imagine the sun glinting off their plate mail. We imagine them rescuing damsels or facing off against one another with lances.

骑士是骑士精神的象征。它们是理性的。骑士精神并非理性的。它没有实体的外表，没有气味，也没有味道。它不会发出声音，也无法触碰。它是一种智慧的产物。

Knights are emblems of chivalry. They are sensible things. Chivalry is not sensible. It has no physical appearance, or smell, or taste. It makes no sound and cannot be touched. It is an intellectual thing.

人造事物（记忆对象）

Artificial Things (Memory Objects)

记忆对象是指模型中尚未存在的事物。换句话说，它们并非真实存在。记忆对象是你在脑海中添加到模型中的东西，其唯一目的是帮助你记忆单词。它们是所谓的人工记忆的一部分。

Memory Objects are things that don’t already exist at a location within your Model. In other words, they are not real. Memory Objects are things that you mentally add to your Model for the sole purpose of helping you memorize words. They are part of what’s called artificial memory.

让我们回到你的厨房台面，假设你正在上课，需要记住“canopy”（天篷）这个词，就像“canopy of Heaven”（天堂的天篷）一样。为了做到这一点，你可以想象你的台面上有一罐豌豆。Can-of-peas = Can-o-py。这罐豌豆是一个记忆对象，因为你在脑海中把它添加到你的厨房台面上，是为了提醒你“canopy”（天篷）这个词。它是一个人造的东西，因为在现实世界中，你想象的位置上并不存在这罐豌豆。

Let’s revisit your kitchen counter, and let’s assume that you are halfway through a lecture and need to remember the word “canopy,” as in “canopy of heaven.” To accomplish this, you might envision a can of peas on your counter. Can-of-peas = Can-o-py. This can of peas is a Memory Object because you added it to your kitchen counter in your mind to remind you of the word canopy. It is an artificial thing because the can of peas doesn’t exist in the real world at the location you imagined it.

真实事物（背景物体）

Real Things (Background Objects)

你为记忆宫殿选择的模型基于一个真实的地方，那里显然充满了真实的东西，比如家具、画作、照片、架子、电视和电器。重要的是，你要记住这些东西不是记忆对象。它们是背景对象。它们是你模型的一部分。你的沙发只是一张沙发。你的咖啡机只是一台咖啡机。这些现实世界中预先存在的物体偶然出现在你的模型中。你把它们放在那里并不是为了帮助你记住什么。

The Model you select for your memory palace is based on a real place which is obviously full or real things, like furniture, paintings, photographs, shelves, televisions, and appliances. It’s important that you remember those things are not Memory Objects. These are background objects. They are part of your Model. Your couch is just a couch. Your coffeemaker is just a coffeemaker. These real-world, pre-existing objects are in your Model by coincidence. You didn’t put them there to help you remember anything.

背景物体存在于你的自然记忆中。你毫不费力就能记住它们。比如你的床。你可能从未站在卧室门口，专注于床的位置，因为害怕忘记它在哪里。你也不会去研究沙发、冰箱或淋浴间的位置。你的大脑会自动记录真实事物的存在和位置——车钥匙是个神秘的例外。

Background objects exist in your natural memory. You remember them without effort. Your bed, for example. You’ve probably never stood at your bedroom doorway and concentrated on the location of your bed for fear of forgetting where it is. You don’t study the location of your couch, or refrigerator, or shower. Your brain records the existence and placement of real things automatically – car keys being a mysterious exception.

换句话说，真实物体是被动记忆的，而人造物体是主动想象的。

Put another way, real objects are passively remembered; artificial objects are actively imagined.

假设你以你的家作为模型。想象一下你的厨房，并放大你的厨房台面。想想现在你台面上的所有东西。这可能包括饼干罐、咖啡机或碗碟架。因为这些东西在现实世界中已经存在于你的厨房台面上，所以它们被视为背景物体。你的饼干罐是用来盛放饼干的，而不是用来提醒你任何词语的。你的咖啡机是用来煮咖啡的。你不是用你的想象力创造这些物体的。你记住它们是因为它们是真实的。

Let’s assume you’re using your home as your Model. Think of your kitchen and zoom in on your kitchen counter. Think of everything that is currently on your counter, right now. That might include a cookie jar, or a coffeemaker, or a dish rack. Because such things already exist on your kitchen counter in the real world, they are considered background objects. Your cookie jar is there to hold cookies, not to remind you of a word. Your coffeemaker is for making coffee. You aren’t creating these objects with your imagination. You’re remembering them because they are real.

这是否意味着你需要从模型中移除背景对象？完全不是。保持它们原样就好。背景对象在记忆宫殿中扮演着重要的角色。最重要的是，它们帮助你区分不同的空间。

Does this mean that you need to remove background objects from your Model? Not at all. Leave them just as they are. Background objects play important roles in memory palaces. Of greatest importance, they help you distinguish one Space from another.

每年一次：

Per Ad Herennium:

“...必须确保形式和性质各异的背景，以便能够清晰地区分它们；因为如果一个人采用了许多[相似的]空间，它们彼此之间的相似性会使他感到困惑，以至于他将不再知道在每个背景中设置了什么。”

“...backgrounds differing in form and nature must be secured, so that, thus distinguished, they may be clearly visible; for if a person has adopted many [similar] spaces, their resemblance to one another will so confuse him that he will no longer know what he has set in each background.”

如果你在一栋空荡荡、没有家具的房子里有三间卧室，你可能很难在脑子里区分其中两间。它们都是空荡荡、毫无特色的立方体。但带家具的房间很容易区分，因为每间都有独特的家具、墙面装饰、床单等等。

If you have three bedrooms in an empty and unfurnished house, it can be difficult to distinguish one from the other two in your mind. They’re all empty, featureless cubes. But furnished rooms are easy to distinguish from one another because each will have unique furniture, wall decorations, linen, etc.

背景物体也有助于将区域划分为焦点。在一片空白、毫无特色的墙壁上导航非常困难，因为没有参考点。但大多数装饰有绘画、钟表、照片、证书等的墙壁很容易导航。这些装饰物中的每一个都可以用作参考点，或者作为焦点的基础。

Background objects are also helpful in dividing Areas into Focal Points. It is difficult to navigate a blank, featureless wall. There are no reference points. But most walls decorated with paintings, clocks, photographs, certificates, and so forth, are easy to navigate. Each of those decorations can be used as a reference point, or basis for a Focal Point.

背景物体也可以用作道具。以现实生活中的饼干罐为例。虽然你厨房里的饼干罐不可能是记忆对象（它是真实存在的，而不是想象出来的），但你可以将你的记忆对象放在饼干罐上、下或里面。你可以在饼干罐的正面画上你的记忆对象的图像。

Background objects can also be used as props. Consider the example of a real-life cookie jar. Though the cookie jar in your kitchen can’t be a Memory Object (it is a real thing, not an imagined thing), you can place your Memory Objects on the cookie jar, or under it, or inside it. You can paint an image of your Memory Object on the front of the cookie jar.

充分利用模型中的背景对象。但要记住，它们不能用作内存对象。

Use the background objects in your Model to your advantage. Just understand that they cannot be used as Memory Objects.

背景物体。上图中所示的所有家具（地毯、钢琴、架子、窗户、绘画等）都被视为背景物体，因为它们真实存在，并非你的想象。背景物体可以帮助你从一个地方导航到另一个地方，但不能代表文字。

Background objects. All of the furnishings shown in the illustration above (rug, piano, shelves, window, painting, etc.) are considered background objects because they really exist and were not imagined by you. Background objects can help you navigate from one place to another but do not represent words.

记忆对象。我把一个随机的记忆对象（一个人造物体）放在同一个区域的背景上。通常情况下，每个区域都会有多个记忆对象。只有中间那个显眼、造型怪异的图形才是记忆对象。在你的脑海中，这个奇怪的东西可能代表着几个单词（也许是三个，根据火球、太阳头和赫尔墨斯权杖的图案来看）。图中的其他所有东西都是背景对象。

Memory Objects. I’ve put a random Memory Object (an artificial thing) against the background of the same Area. Normally you’ll have several Memory Objects for each Area. Only the conspicuous, weird-looking figure in the center is a Memory Object. In your mind, this strange thing could represent several words (perhaps three, based on the fiery globe, the sun-head, and the rod of Hermes). Every other thing in this illustration is a background object.

* * *

* * *

奇怪的事情

Strange Things

为了使记忆对象能够留存并且不被误认为是背景对象，它应该尽可能奇怪和荒谬。

For a Memory Object to stick and for it not to be mistaken as a background object, it should be as strange and absurd as possible.

疯狂。古怪。荒谬。疯狂。

Crazy. Wacky. Ridiculous. Insane.

这是因为大脑喜欢刺激。奇特的事物令人兴奋，而平凡的事物则不然。奇特的事物值得思考、储存和沉思。平凡的事物会被归档到大脑中“去过那里，做过那事”的区域，并在混乱中被遗忘。

That’s because the brain loves stimulation. Weird things are stimulating. Mundane things are not. Weird things are worth pondering, storing, and contemplating. Mundane things are filed away in the “been there, done that” section of your brain, and lost in the shuffle.

这就是为什么《Ad Herennium》的无名作者写道，记忆对象应该显眼，“以便我们可以轻松地掌握和拥抱它们”，以及为什么威廉·普雷斯顿写道：“一切映入眼帘的事物都会立即引起人们的注意，并在记忆中留下严肃而庄严的真理。”

This is why the unknown author of the Ad Herennium wrote that Memory Objects should be conspicuous, “so that we can grasp and embrace them easily,” and why William Preston wrote, “Everything that strikes the eye more immediately engages the attention, and imprints on the memory serious and solemn truths.”

幸运的是，你的想象力喜欢疯狂的事情。还记得你上次做的那个梦吗？那个梦里，你开着一辆水泥车穿过土星环，因为你迟到了圣诞派对，而且你的魔法传送环坏了。

Luckily, your imagination loves nutty things. Remember that last dream you had? The one in which you were driving a cement truck through the rings of Saturn because you were late to a Christmas party and your magical teleportation ring wasn’t working?

是的，这就是让这些记忆宫殿物体发挥作用所需要的疯狂。

Yep, that’s the kind of crazy you need to make these memory palace objects work.

个人物品

Personal Things

重要的是，你要能够创造大部分你自己的记忆对象。我将在附录中提供一些记忆对象的示例，只是为了说明它们是如何组合的，但最好的记忆对象是你创造的。

It’s important that you conjure most of your own Memory Objects. I will provide some sample Memory Objects in the Appendix simply to illustrate how they might be composed, but the best Memory Objects are the ones you create.

乔达诺·布鲁诺在其1582年出版的著作《论观念的阴影》（ De Umbris Idearum）中写道：“每个人对热的感受并非相同，而主要取决于个人的敏感度。出于同样的原因，你应该从实践中构建你的意象（记忆对象）……而不是从你无法分享的他人见解中构建。”

In his 1582 book, De Umbris Idearum (“On the Shadows of Ideas”), Giordano Bruno writes, “The sensation of heat does not feel the same to everyone, but depends mostly on the degree of one’s sensitivity to it. For that same reason, you should devise your images [Memory Objects] from practice...not from the insights of others which you will be unable to share.”

《Ad Herennium》的作者对此表示赞同。“我们为什么要剥夺任何人的主动性？为了让他免于自己寻找，我们把所有已经搜索好的东西都交给他？一个人更容易被一种相似之处所打动，另一个人则更容易被另一种相似之处所打动。例如，当我们公开宣称一个人长得像另一个人时，许多听众会不同意，因为每个人对事物的感知都不同。对于图像（记忆对象）也是如此：对你我来说似乎不错的选择，在别人看来可能很糟糕。因此，每个人都应该设计适合自己感知的图像。”

The author of Ad Herennium agrees. “Why do we wish to rob anybody of his initiative, so that, to save him from making any search himself, we deliver to him everything searched out and ready? One person is more struck by one likeness, and another person by another likeness. For example, when we publicly declare that one person looks like another, many listeners will disagree, because everyone perceives things differently. The same is true with respect to images [Memory Objects]: one that seems a good choice to you or me could appear a bad choice to others. Every person, therefore, should devise his own images, suitable to his own perception.”

换句话说，没有人能告诉你应该使用什么记忆对象。对我或其他兄弟很有效的方法，对你来说可能完全无效。对你有效的方法，对我可能无效。这并不意味着你必须回避所有建议或示例。这只是意味着你永远不应该觉得有义务使用别人创建的记忆对象。

In other words, no one can tell you what Memory Objects you should use. What works great for me, or for another brother, might not work at all for you. What works for you might not work for me. That doesn’t mean you have to avoid all suggestions or examples. It only means that you should never feel obligated to use a Memory Object someone else has created.

如果它对你有用，那很好，但如果没有，请忽略它并寻找其他有用的方法。

If it works for you, great, but if it doesn’t, ignore it and find something that does.

如何创建内存对象

How to Create Memory Objects
