如果你的需求很简单，你可以在记忆宫殿中多次使用同一个地标。例如，如果你只是想把讲座分成四个部分，你可以使用同一个地标（比如一个巨大的发光柱子，上面写着数字，例如1、2、3、4），并将其放置在记忆宫殿的正确位置。显然，这需要你先花时间把讲座分成四个相等的部分，这样你就知道该把地标放在哪里了。

If your needs are simple, you can use the same Landmark several times in your memory palace. For example, if you simply want to divide your lecture into four quarters, you use the same Landmark (let’s say a giant, glowing column with a number on it, i.e., 1, 2, 3, and 4), placing it in your memory palace at the correct location. Obviously, this requires that you take the time to first break the lecture into four equal parts, so that you’ll know where to place the Landmarks.

如果您的需求更为复杂，不妨使用彼此不同的地标。例如，如果您的讲座探讨的是道德、平等和正直的人生等主题，您可以在相关空间的门口放置一个巨大的正方形、水平仪和铅垂线作为地标。

If your needs are more complicated, you may wish to use Landmarks that differ from one another. For example, if your lecture addresses topics such as morality, equality, and rectitude of life, you could place a massive square, level, and plumb as Landmarks in the doorways of the related Spaces.

再次强调，这些需要以某种引人注目的方式添加。仅仅想象一个正方形钉在门上是不够的。相反，想象一座正方形的大理石雕像，它比人还大，像太阳一样明亮，或者镶嵌着珠宝，或者霓虹灯。

Again, these need to be added in some striking manner. It’s not enough just to imagine a square nailed to a door. Instead, imagine a marble statue of a square that is bigger than a man and glows as brightly as the sun, or is covered in jewels, or neon lights.

我们的老朋友，《Ad Herennium》的匿名作者，在这方面提供了建议：“为了确保背景（空间）的数量万无一失，每五个背景（空间）都应该标记。例如，如果我们在第五个背景（空间）中放置一只金手，在第十个背景（空间）中放置一位名叫德西默斯的熟人，那么在每个连续的五个背景中放置类似的标记就很容易了。”

Our old friend, the anonymous author of Ad Herennium, provides advice in this regard: “And that we may by no chance err in the number of backgrounds [Spaces], each fifth background [Space] should be marked. For example, if in the fifth we should set a golden hand, and in the tenth some acquaintance whose first name is Decimus, it will then be easy to station like marks in each successive fifth background.”

作者用一只金色的手来表示第五空间，因为手有五个手指。拉丁语中“Decimus”意为“第十”，当时是一个专有名词，所以把一个叫“Decimus”的人戳进房间，会让你想起那是第十空间。如今，更合适的说法是把这个人想象成“Dexter”或“Dixie”。

The author uses a golden hand for the fifth Space because a hand has five fingers. Decimus, the Latin word for “tenth,” was then a proper name, so poking a guy named “Decimus” into a room would remind you that it was the tenth Space. Today, it would be more appropriate to think of a person named “Dexter” or “Dixie.”

我猜想地标在两千年前会更重要，因为那个时代的建筑和房间彼此之间不像你我所习惯的那样泾渭分明。作者建议使用地标来避免混淆不同的空间。对于现代记忆宫殿的建造者来说，这应该不成问题，但我们仍然可以将这项技术用于我上面描述的目的，例如，以一种特殊的方式索引我们已经记住的内容，或者提示我们在讲座或课程内容的指定时间点执行某些操作。

I suspect Landmarks would have been more important two thousand years ago because the buildings and rooms of the era were not as distinct from one another as what you and I are used to. The author is recommending the use of Landmarks to avoid confusing one Space with another. That should be not a problem for the modern builder of a memory palace, but we can still use this technique for the purposes I described above, i.e., to index what we’ve memorized in a special manner, or to cue us to perform some action at a prescribed point in a lecture or part.

18

18

规划你的记忆宫殿

Planning Your Memory Palace

我提前规划好你的记忆宫殿非常重要。你希望第一个记忆对象位于你的起点，最后一个记忆对象位于你的终点，并且所有位于中间的记忆对象都应按逻辑顺序分布。

It’s important that you plan your memory palace in advance. You want the first Memory Object to be at your start point and your last Memory Object to be at your end point, and all the Memory Objects in-between logically distributed.

具体过程如下：

Here’s the process:

* * *

* * *

步骤 1： 将模型划分为空间

Step 1: Divide your Model into Spaces

a. 选择您的型号。

a. Select your Model.

b. 计算模型中的空格数量。你的目标是每个段落都有一个空格。换句话说，10 个空格 = 10 个段落。

b. Count the number of Spaces in your Model. Your goal is to have a Space for each paragraph. In other words, 10 Spaces = 10 paragraphs.

c. 如果你有想要记住的内容的出版版本（书籍、小册子、密码、监视器等），可以用书写工具在每个段落下方画一条线。如果某个段落特别长，可以在逻辑点画一条线，将其分成两段。如果某个段落特别短，不要在段落下方画线，而是用括号将其作为上下段落的一部分。这些被分割或合并的段落正是你需要空格的地方。

c. If you have a published version of what you want to memorize (a book, pamphlet, cipher, monitor, etc.), use a writing instrument to draw a line under each paragraph. If a paragraph is unusually large, feel free to divide it into two paragraphs by drawing a line at logical point. If a paragraph is unusually small, don’t draw a line under it, but instead include it as part of either the paragraph above or below it using brackets. These divided or combined paragraphs are the ones you’ll need Spaces for.

d. 将模型中的空格数与带下划线的段落数进行比较。如果段落数多于空格数，则有两种选择：

d. Compare the number of Spaces in your Model to the number of underlined paragraphs. If you have more paragraphs than Spaces, you have two options:

#1. 寻找更多空间。您可以利用那些经常被忽视的地方，例如壁橱、阁楼、杂物间、楼梯间和走廊（室内），或者沙井、龙头、地块角落或电表（室外）？

#1. Find more Spaces. Could you use often-overlooked places like closets, attics, utility rooms, staircases, and hallways (indoors), or manholes, spigots, lot corners, or utility meters (outdoors)?

#2. 使用更大的空间来容纳两个段落。除非你的房间特别大（通常是家庭活动室或书房），否则尽量避免这样做。如果你确实要把两个段落放在一个房间里，可以找一些背景物体作为分界点，这样你就能知道每个段落的起始和结束位置。否则，把两个主题放在一个房间里可能会造成混淆。

#2. Use a larger Space to house two paragraphs. Try to avoid this unless you have an unusually large room (usually a family room or den). If you do put two paragraphs into a room, find some background objects to use as demarcation points so you’ll know where each one starts and ends. Otherwise, putting two topics in a room can result in confusion.

e. 留出足够的空间后，给每段编号，即 1、2、3、4、5……等。

e. Once you have enough spaces, number each paragraph, i.e., 1, 2, 3, 4, 5…etc.

f. 确定你穿过模型空间的路径。请参阅“移动”一章，获取有关此过程的建议。你可以螺旋式地向内、向外、之字形移动，或者使用任何最适合你的方式。关键在于移动要自然且合乎逻辑。如果移动毫无规律，你可能记不住空间的顺序，这很糟糕，因为这也是段落的顺序，而你肯定不希望段落顺序混乱。画出模型的草图，并在各个空间之间画上箭头，可能会有所帮助。

f. Decide on your path through the Spaces of your Model. Refer to the “Traveling” chapter for advice on this process. Spiral in or spiral out, or zig-zag, or use whatever method works best for you. The key is that the movement should be natural and logical. If it’s erratic, without any pattern, you may not be able to remember the order of your Spaces, which is bad, because that’s also the order of your paragraphs, and you don’t want to get your paragraphs out of order. It might be helpful to draw out a sketch of your Model and draw arrows from one Space to the next.

g. 一旦你确定了从一个空间到另一个空间的路径，你需要为每个空间匹配正确的段落。你可以随心所欲地做这件事。你可以直接在包含你正在记忆的信息的书的空白处记下空间的名称（如果你这样做，我强烈建议你用铅笔！）。或者，你可以在你的模型草图上写上段落编号。或者，你可以在另一张纸上创建一个索引。它看起来像这样：

g. Once you know the path you’re going to take from one Space to another, you need to match each Space with the right paragraph. You can do this however you want. You could just jot the name of the Space in the margin of the book which contains the information you’re memorizing (if you do this, I strongly recommend using a pencil!). Or you could write the paragraph number on a sketch of your Model. Or you could create an index on a separate sheet of paper. It would look something like this:

前廊=第1段

Front porch = Paragraph 1

人行道=第2段

Sidewalk = Paragraph 2

车道=第3段

Driveway = Paragraph 3

……等等。你可能会绕着整个院子和房子走，最后才结束，例如：地下室=第35段

…and so on. You might wind through your entire yard and house before finishing with, for example: Basement = Paragraph 35

* * *

* * *

第 2 步：将空间划分为区域。

Step 2: Divide your Spaces into Areas.

a. 计算每段的句子数。

a. Count the number of sentences in each paragraph.

1）用垂直线将异常长的句子分成两个或多个句子片段。

1) Divide unusually long sentences into two or more sentence fragments with a vertical line.

2）用括号将短句组合成句组。

2) Combine short sentences into sentence groups by bracketing them.

例如：

For example:

众议院由各州人民每两年选举一次的议员组成，每州选举人应具备该州立法机关人数最多的一院选举人的资格。

The House of Representatives shall be composed of Members chosen every second Year by the People of the several States, and the Electors in each State shall have the Qualifications requisite for Electors of the most numerous Branch of the State Legislature.

（1 句话）

(1 sentence)

- 可以这样划分：

- could be divided in this way:

众议院由

The House of Representatives shall be composed

每两年选举一次的成员

of Members chosen every second Year

由各州人民

by the People of the several States

各州选举人应

and the Electors in each State shall

具备选民资格

have the Qualifications requisite for Electors of

州立法机构中人数最多的部门

the most numerous Branch of the State Legislature

（这样，1句话就变成了6个句子片段，它们在你的记忆宫殿中被视为句子）

(Thus, 1 sentence becomes 6 sentence fragments, which are treated like sentences in your memory palace)

- 或者 -

- or –

盒子是棕色的。

The box is brown.

为什么是棕色的？

Why is it brown?

这些材料未经漂白。

The materials are unbleached.

（3 句话）

(3 sentences)

- 可以按如下方式分组：

- could be grouped in this way:

[这个盒子是棕色的。为什么是棕色的？]

[The box is brown. Why is it brown?]

[材料未经过漂白。]

[The materials are unbleached.]

（这样，3 个句子就变成了 2 个句组）

(Thus, 3 sentences become 2 sentence groups)

b. 句子划分和分组完成后，写下段落的句子数量。这是每个对应空间所需的最小区域数量。如果需要，你可以将多个句子分配到一个区域。

b. Once you’ve divided and grouped your sentences, write the number of sentences in the paragraph down. This is the minimum number of Areas you will need in each corresponding Space. You may assign more than one sentence to an Area if you’d like.

例如，假设第1段包含8个句子，并且你使用前廊作为该段落的空间。这意味着你需要将前廊划分成8个区域。你可以将门廊与地面齐平的每条边作为一个区域（总共4个区域），并将门廊上方天篷的每条边作为另外4个区域。这样你就可以为这8个句子分配8个区域。另一个选择是将门廊的每个边作为一个区域，并将门廊的每个角作为一个区域。发挥你的想象力，总有办法让一切变得完美。

For example, assume that paragraph #1 contains 8 sentences and that you’re using your front porch as the Space for that paragraph. This means you’ll need to divide your Front Porch into 8 Areas. You could use each edge of the porch at ground level as an Area (for a total of 4), and each edge of a canopy over your porch as another 4 Areas. This gets you to 8 Areas for the 8 sentences. Another option would be two use each edge of the porch as an Area, and each corner of the porch as an Area. Use your imagination. There’s always a way to make things fit.

c. 使用任何你喜欢的技巧，将段落中的句子分配到空间中的区域。把它记在你的模型草图上，或者创建一个索引。这和你之前将段落绑定到空间的过程是一样的。

c. Use whatever technique you like to assign the sentences in the paragraph to the Areas in the Space. Jot it down on a sketch of your Model, or create an index. This is the same process you used to tie your paragraphs to Spaces.

* * *

* * *

步骤 3： 将你的区域划分为焦点

Step 3: Divide your Areas into Focal Points

焦点的唯一规则是它们之间应保持合理的距离。传统上，距离是一臂之长，但最多不超过两臂之长。每个区域可能需要一个，也可能需要八个。使用多少个焦点，以及将它们排成一排、堆叠或两者结合，完全由您决定。

The only rules for Focal Points is that they should be a reasonable distance apart from one another. Traditionally, that’s an arm’s length, but no more than two arm’s lengths. Maybe you’ll need one per Area, or maybe eight. It’s completely up to you how many you use and whether you put them in a line, or stack them, or a combination of both.

我建议你暂时不要限定焦点的数量和顺序。先为一个区域设计一些记忆对象，了解它们的大小，然后再决定每个对象应该放在哪里。充分利用该区域的背景。例如，如果你的区域是一面客厅墙，里面有一张躺椅、一扇窗户和一台电视机，你可以像这样设置焦点：

I would suggest not committing yourself to the number and order of your Focal Points at this point. Develop your Memory Objects for an Area first so that you’ll know their sizes, and then determine which should go where. Use the background of the Area to your advantage. If your Area is, for example, a living room wall which contains a recliner, a window, and a television, you could set up your Focal Points like this:

焦点 1 – 躺椅左侧

Focal Point 1 – left of recliner

焦点 2 – 躺椅上

Focal Point 2 – on recliner

焦点 3 – 躺椅右侧

Focal Point 3 – right of recliner

焦点 4 – 窗户下方或前方

Focal Point 4 – under or in front of the window

焦点 5 – 电视机下方、前方或上方

Focal Point 5 – under, or in front of, or on top of, the television

再次强调，此时只需制定一个基本计划。等到你开发出记忆对象后，再决定将哪个对象放在哪里。只有这样，你才能真正知道一个区域需要多少个焦点。

Again, just come up with a basic plan at this point. Wait until you’ve developed your Memory Objects before deciding which to put where. Only then will you really know how many Focal Points you need in an Area.

步骤4. 创建并放置内存对象。请参阅第7章。

Step 4. Create and place your Memory Objects. Refer to Chapter 7.

19

19

运动与互动作为粘合剂

Motion and Interaction as Cement

米动作和互动应该作为粘合剂，将记忆对象按正确的顺序连接在一起。一个记忆对象会提醒你另一个记忆对象，并且了解哪些记忆对象对哪些记忆对象起作用，从而保持记忆对象的正确顺序。通过一个记忆对象作用于另一个记忆对象，我们利用因果关系或预期的事件序列来记住句子中单词的顺序。

Motion and interaction should be used as cement to bind Memory Objects together in their proper order. One reminds you of the other and knowing what is acting on what keeps the Memory Objects in the right order. By having one Memory Object act on another Memory Object, we are using cause and effect or an anticipated sequence of events to remember the order of words in a sentence.

让记忆中的事物动起来，几乎和让它们变得奇特一样重要，正如《Ad Herennium》的作者所说：“因此，我们应该树立一种能够在记忆中停留更久的形象。如果我们能建立尽可能引人注目的相似性，如果我们树立的形象不多也不模糊，但却能有所作为，那么我们就能够做到这一点。”

Putting our Memory Objects into motion is almost as important as making them strange, as noted by the author of Ad Herennium: “We ought, then, to set up images of a kind that can adhere longest in the memory. And we shall do so if we establish likenesses as striking as possible; if we set up images that are not many or vague, but doing something.”

同样，詹巴蒂斯塔·德拉·波尔塔 (Giambattista della Porta) 在《回忆的艺术》( Ars reminiscendi ) 中写道，图像 (记忆对象) 是“我们在想象中回忆起来的动画图片，用来代表某个事实或词语。”

Similarly, Giambattista della Porta, in Ars reminiscendi (“Art of Recollection”), wrote that an image (Memory Object) was “an animated picture which we recall in the imagination in order to represent a fact or word.”

举个例子或许能解释我的意思。假设我给你五张索引卡。每张卡上都有一张图片。图片如下：

An example might help explain what I’m talking about. Imagine I gave you five index cards. There is a single picture on each card. The pictures are:

#1：一名可疑男子在房子周围放置炸药箱

#1: A suspicious man placing boxes of dynamite around a house

#2：一个火山口，里面有一栋房屋的余烬

#2: A crater containing the smoldering remnants of a house

#3：一名可疑男子从火柴盒中抽出一根火柴

#3: A suspicious man pulling a match from a matchbook

#4：爆炸

#4: An explosion

#5：点燃的导火索

#5: A lit fuse

如果我让你按时间顺序排列这些卡片，你很可能会按照这个顺序排列：1、3、5、4、2。我甚至不用告诉你发生了什么。你知道发生了什么，也知道导致事情发生的顺序：一个形迹可疑的男子在一栋房子周围埋了几盒炸药，然后从口袋里掏出一根火柴，点燃了火柴，然后将火柴头放在导火索上，导火索燃烧殆尽，直到炸药被点燃，房子爆炸了。剩下的只是一个弹坑和一些碎石。

If I asked you to put these cards in chronological order, you’d probably put them in this sequence: 1, 3, 5, 4, 2. I don’t even have to tell you what happened. You know what happened, and you know the order of events that led to what happened: A suspicious man planted boxes of dynamite around a house, pulled a match from his pocket, lit the match, then placed the tip of the match against a fuse, and the fuse burned down until the dynamite was ignited and the house exploded. All that is left is a crater and debris.

这是一个显而易见的事件顺序。同样，对于一个男孩来说，他必须先把手伸进饼干罐，才能拿出饼干；而饼干必须先拿出来，才能吃。

This is an obvious sequence of events. In the same way, it’s obvious to a boy that he must first put his hand into the cookie jar before he can retrieve a cookie, and that the cookie must be retrieved before it can be eaten.

好的...那么我要说什么呢？

Okay...so where am I going with this?

在上面的例子中，如果你翻转这些卡片，你会发现我在每张卡片的背面写了文字：

In the example above, if you flipped those cards over, you’d find that I’d written words on the back of each card:

#1：你

#1: YOU

#2：人

#2: PERSON

#3：是

#3: ARE

#4：很棒

#4: GREAT

#5：A

#5: A

或者，按照您之前排列的顺序，“您是一个伟大的人。”

Or, in the order in which you earlier arranged them, “YOU ARE A GREAT PERSON.”

你看到你做了什么了吗？你只是把卡片背面的单词排列成一个句子，却根本不知道这些单词是什么，句子是什么，或者哪张卡片背面是什么单词。你只是根据卡片正面的图片，按照“自然”顺序排列卡片，就做到了这一点。

Do you see what you’ve done? You just arranged the words on the back of the cards into a sentence without even knowing what the words were, or what the sentence was, or what word was on the back of which card. And you did that by simply placing the cards in their “natural” order, based on the pictures you saw on the front.

这就是你如何利用动作和互动来确保单词以正确的顺序被记住。你将单词与记忆对象绑定，然后让记忆对象以某种令人难忘的方式进行互动。记忆对象互动的时间顺序与对应单词出现的时间顺序类似。

This is how you use motion and interaction to ensure that words are remembered in proper order. You tie words to Memory Objects and then have the Memory Objects interact in some memorable way. The chronological order in which Memory Objects interact is analogous to the chronological order in which the corresponding words appear.

你可能会反对我之前的说法，虽然我之前说过，内存对象的所有组件都应该物理上相互接触，但为了避免混淆，内存对象之间应该保持一臂之遥。难道一个内存对象与另一个内存对象交互不是违背了这条规则的初衷吗？

You might object that I previously stated that all components of a Memory Object should be physically in contact with one another, but that Memory Objects should be an arm’s length from one another to avoid confusion. Isn’t having one Memory Object interacting with another defeating the purpose of that rule?

不会。你首先单独观察一个记忆对象，然后想象它与另一个记忆对象交互。“A”与“B”交互的事实不应该导致你混淆A和B。它们的生命起点仍然是独立的。它们在后续运动中接触的事实不应该造成混淆。

No. You first view a Memory Object by itself, and then imagine it interacting with another Memory Object. The fact that “A” is interacting with “B” shouldn’t cause you to confuse A with B. They still begin their lives at separately. The fact that they come into contact as a result of subsequent movement shouldn’t cause confusion.

20

20

记忆宫殿示例

Memory Palace Example

我是时候把你学到的东西付诸实践了。让我们引用阿尔伯特·派克弟兄的《道德与教条》中的一句话：

It’s time to put what you’ve learned into practice. Let’s use this quote from Br. Albert Pike’s Morals and Dogma:

共济会是世界伟大的和平组织。无论它存在于何处，它都致力于防止国际困难和争端；并将共和国、王国和帝国团结成一个伟大的和平友好联盟。如果共济会成员了解自己的力量并珍视自己的誓言，那么他们的奋斗就不会常常徒劳无功。

“Masonry is the great Peace Society of the world. Wherever it exists, it struggles to prevent international difficulties and disputes; and to bind Republics, Kingdoms, and Empires together in one great band of peace and amity. It would not so often struggle in vain, if Masons knew their power and valued their oaths.”

首先，将其分解成句子。

First, break it down into sentences.

1.共济会是世界伟大的和平组织。

1.Masonry is the great Peace Society of the world.

2.无论它存在于何处，它都努力防止国际困难和争端；并将共和国、王国和帝国团结成一个伟大的和平与友好的联盟。

2.Wherever it exists, it struggles to prevent international difficulties and disputes; and to bind Republics, Kingdoms, and Empires together in one great band of peace and amity.

3.如果共济会成员了解自己的力量并重视自己的誓言，那么他们的斗争就不会那么频繁地徒劳无功。

3.It would not so often struggle in vain, if Masons knew their power and valued their oaths.

句子#2和#3太长了。我们把它们分解成几个句子片段吧。

Sentences #2 and #3 are too long. Let’s break them down into sentence fragments.

  • 共济会是伟大的和平协会
  • Masonry is the great Peace Society
  • 世界。
  • of the world.
  • 无论它存在于何处，
  • Wherever it exists,
  • 它努力阻止
  • it struggles to prevent
  • 国际困难和争端
  • international difficulties and disputes
  • 并约束各共和国，
  • and to bind Republics,
  • 王国和帝国
  • Kingdoms, and Empires
  • 组成一个伟大的乐队
  • together in one great band
  • 和平与友好。
  • of peace and amity.
  • 它不会常常徒劳地挣扎，
  • It would not so often struggle in vain,
  • 如果共济会成员知道他们的力量
  • if Masons knew their power
  • 并珍视他们的誓言。
  • and valued their oaths.

回想一下，我们通常为每个段落使用一个空间。本例中的段落很短，因此我们有足够的空间进行创作。假设我们使用一栋房子作为模型，将家庭活动室作为空间。由于段落较小，我们只使用墙壁作为区域。假设有四面墙，简单的数学运算（12 除以 4）告诉我们，我们将为每面墙分配三个句子（在本例中为句子片段）。

Recall that we generally use one Space for every paragraph. This example is a very short paragraph, so we’ll have plenty of room to work with. Let’s assume we’re using a house for a Model and the family room for our Space. Because it’s a small paragraph, we’ll only use the walls as Areas. Assuming there are four walls, simple math (12 divided by 4) tells us that we’ll be assigning three sentences (or sentence fragments, in this case) to each wall.

因此：

Thus:

墙 #1

Wall #1

共济会是伟大的和平协会

Masonry is the great Peace Society

世界。

of the world.

无论它存在于何处

Wherever it exists

墙＃2

Wall #2

它努力阻止

it struggles to prevent

国际困难和争端

international difficulties and disputes

并约束共和国

and to bind Republics

墙#3

Wall #3

王国与帝国

Kingdoms and Empires

组成一个伟大的乐队

together in one great band

和平与友好

of peace and amity

墙#4

Wall #4

它不会常常徒劳地挣扎，

It would not so often struggle in vain,

如果共济会成员知道他们的力量

if Masons knew their power

并珍视他们的誓言

and valued their oaths

因为每面墙只有三句话，所以我们只需要几个焦点。回想一下，焦点是区域中任何你可以注视或“放大”的部分。

Because we have only three sentences per wall, we’ll only need a few Focal Points. Recall that a Focal Point is any section of an Area that you can stare at or “zoom in” on.

让我们从墙＃1开始，构建一些记忆对象。

Let’s start with Wall #1, and build some Memory Objects.

共济会是伟大的和平协会

Masonry is the great Peace Society

世界的

of the world

无论它存在于何处……

Wherever it exists…

“Masonry”指的是一种大型梅森罐（就像用来装自制果冻的那种）。梅森罐是很好的记忆物件，因为它们是透明的。我们可以把其他东西放进去、放在上面或下面。

“Masonry” is a large mason jar (the kind you’d use for canning homemade jelly). Mason jars are great Memory Objects because they are transparent. We can put other things into them, on them, or under them.

“是”一条蛇，发出嘶嘶声。

“is” is a snake, hissing.

“the” 是冠词，因此是可选的。如果你想用记忆对象来表示“the”，你可以用茶包或高尔夫球座作为例子。在本例中，我们将用茶包作为记忆对象。

“the” is an article, and thus optional. If you want a Memory Object for “the,” you might use, as examples, a tea-bag or a golf tee. We’ll use a tea bag as our Memory Object in this instance.

“great” = 葡萄，或任何紫色的东西

“great” = grape, or anything the color purple

“和平”=和平标志

“Peace” = a Peace sign

“社会”= Sew + sigh + 外星人（“ET”）

“Society” = Sew + sigh + an extraterrestrial (an “ET”)

“of” = 一管紫外线防晒霜

“of” = a tube of UV sunscreen

“the” = 茶包

“the” = tea bag

“世界”=地球仪

“world” = a globe

“wherever” = 这个很难回答，对吧？不过我听着挺像“hair lever”。记住，越疯狂越好！

“wherever” = this is a tough one, right? But this sounds to me a lot like “hair lever.” Remember, the crazier, the better!

“it” = mitt（厨房手套、接球手套或名为“Mitt”的人）。

“it” = mitt (a kitchen mitt, catcher’s mitt, or someone named “Mitt”).

“exists” = 两个出口标志（exits = exist）。

“exists” = two exit signs (exits = exists).

因此，我们可以想象一个玻璃瓶翻倒了，然后一条嘶嘶作响的蛇从里面钻了出来。蛇滑过一个茶包，朝着地板上的一颗葡萄爬去。这颗葡萄旁边是抗议活动留下的“和平”标志。在标志的另一边，我们看到一双缝纫的手。我们听到一声叹息，然后发现这叹息来自外星人（显然外星人喜欢缝纫！）。外星人将一些防紫外线防晒霜挤到茶包上，然后开始用茶包擦拭地球仪（这可以防止全球变暖）。地球仪的另一边是一个毛茸茸的杠杆，上面插着一只厨房手套。手套的拇指指向墙上的两个出口标志。

Thus, we might imagine a mason jar tipping over, then a hissing snake emerging from it. The snake slithers over a tea bag and toward a grape on the floor. The grape is next to a “peace” sign left over from a protest. On the other side of the sign, we see the hands of someone sewing. We hear a sigh and then see that the sigh came from the extraterrestrial (apparently aliens loves to sew!). The alien squirts some U.V. sunscreen lotion onto a tea bag, and then begins to rub the tea bag onto a globe of the world (this prevents global warming). On the other side of the globe is a hairy lever with a kitchen mitt impaled upon it. The thumb of the mitt points toward two exit signs on the wall.

在脑海里循环这些图像几次。一开始可能会很笨拙，速度也会很慢。但重复几次之后，你会发现你对单词顺序的记忆会赶上你对记忆对象的记忆，最终单词的记忆速度会比记忆对象更快。几个小时、几天或几周后，记忆对象就会逐渐消失，只有当你再次忘记单词时，你才会想起它们。

Cycle through these images a few times in your head. It will be a clumsy exercise at first. It will be slow. But after a few repetitions, you’ll find that your memory of the order of the words will catch up to your memory of the Memory Objects, and eventually the words will come to you faster than the Memory Objects, and in a few hours, days, or weeks the Memory Objects will fade into the background, only to be tapped if you find yourself forgetting the words again.

如果你真的想在记忆宫殿里测试记忆对象的有效性，那就等一周，然后试着用记忆对象作为引导，记住这段文字的这一部分。我敢打赌，你一定能记住，而且顺序正确。也许你需要集中注意力几分钟，但你一定会记住。然而，如果你只是像大多数人一样，只是把这些单词读几遍，然后默念几遍，而不使用记忆对象，那么很可能不到一周你就会忘记它们。

If you really want to test the effectiveness of Memory Objects in a memory palace, wait a week and then try to remember just this section of the paragraph, using the Memory Objects as your guide. I’d bet that you’ll remember them and in the right order. Maybe it’ll take you a few minutes of concentration, but you’ll remember. However, if you merely read the words and repeated them to yourself a few times, as most people do when trying to memorize things, without using Memory Objects, odds are that within a week you’ll forget them.

我建议你不要试图每天记住多个区域，这意味着如果你真的想记住这个段落，你现在就停下来，明天你就会开始为下一个区域创建记忆对象。

I’d suggest you never try to remember more than one Area a day, which means that if you were really trying to memorize this paragraph, you’d stop now, and tomorrow you’d start creating Memory Objects for your next Area.

假设您想继续前进，让我们前往下一个区域，即您刚刚使用的墙壁右侧的墙壁。

Assuming you want to press forward, let’s go to the next Area, which is the wall to the right of the wall you just used.

墙＃2：

Wall #2:

它努力阻止

it struggles to prevent

国际困难和争端

international difficulties and disputes

并约束共和国

and to bind Republics

米特·罗姆尼就是“它”

Mitt Romney is “it”

“struggles” 很难。我打算用两只海鸥啄地毯来表达。记住，怪异是好的，把一个以“s”开头、以“gulls”结尾的单词和“rug”结合起来，就能达到目的了。

“struggles” is tough. I’m going to use two seagulls pecking at a rug. Remember, weird is good, and combining a word that starts with “s” and ends in “gulls” with the word “rug,” will get the job done.

“防止”——我要把这两个词合并成一个记忆对象，它是墙上的一个通风口，上面贴着一张价格标签。标签上写着“2美元”，但被划掉了，在原价格下方写着“免费”。Two -Free-Vent。防止。

“to prevent” – I’m going to combine these two words into one Memory Object, which is a vent in the wall with a price sticker on it. The sticker has “$2” on it, but that’s crossed out, and below the old price is the word, “Free.” Two-Free-Vent. To prevent.

国际——这个看起来也挺难的，但其实真的需要点创意。听起来像是 Enter + nat + shunnel。我会想象一个“ENTER”的标志，上面爬满了小蚊蚋。这些小蚊蚋被贴在标志上的一瓶开着的香奈儿香水吸引住了。

International – this one seems like it would be difficult, too, but all that is really required some creativity. This sounds like Enter + nat + shunnel. I’ll picture an “ENTER” sign, swarming with gnats. The gnats are attracted to an open bottle of Chanel perfume that’s been taped to the sign.

困难——一只身穿黑色长袍的傻鸭子（他属于邪教组织）坐在一把EZ椅上。所以，傻鸭邪教。

difficulties – a daffy duck in a dark robe (he’s in a cult) sitting in an EZ-chair. Thus, daffy-cult-eez.

并且——我有时会把它想象成一根橡皮筋，连接着前后的记忆对象，或者一把吉他（乐队的乐器）。其他时候，我会用一只蚂蚁，一只手，或者沙子。你也可以用其他完全不同的东西。这次我选吉他。

and – I sometimes picture this as a rubber band connecting the Memory Objects before and after it, or a guitar (an instrument from a band). On other occasions, I’ll use an ant, or a hand, or sand. You might use something else entirely. I’ll go with the guitar this time.

争端——两艘潜艇。“靴子。”

disputes - two submarines. “Das boots.”

我会把这些结合起来，想象一只巨大的蚂蚁，上面画着“2”

and to – I’ll combine these, imagining a giant ant with a “2” painted on it

束缚——邦德。詹姆斯·邦德。

bind – Bond. James Bond.

共和国——香蕉（香蕉共和国）

Republics –bananas (banana republics)

现在让我们开始行动吧。米特·罗姆尼把两只海鸥从地毯上赶下来，朝着一个 2 美元/免费的通风口跑去。通风口上方是一个进入标志，上面爬满了小蚊虫，因为上面贴着一瓶香奈儿香水。香水滴在了一只傻鸭子身上（它愤怒地抬头看着我）。鸭子穿着一件深色长袍，坐在一把 EZ 椅子上。EZ 椅子旁边有一把吉他，吉他放在两个模型潜艇上。吉他和潜艇开始移动，因为有一只画着数字“2”的大蚂蚁在推它们。蚂蚁撞上了詹姆斯·邦德，他双手各拿着一根香蕉，双臂交叉抱在胸前。

Now let’s put these into motion. Mitt Romney chases two seagulls off a rug and toward a $2/Free vent. Above the vent is an ENTER sign swarming with gnats because a bottle of Chanel perfume has been taped to it. The perfume is dripping on a daffy duck (who angrily looks up). The duck is wearing a dark robe and sitting in an EZ chair. Next to the EZ chair is a guitar, which is propped on top of two model submarines. The guitar and submarines begin to move, because there is a giant ant with a “2” painted on it pushing against them. The ant bumps into James Bond, who is holding a banana in each hand, his arms crossed over his chest.

很荒唐吧？但过一段时间就会记住。

Absurd, right? But memorable. After awhile.

墙＃3：

Wall #3:

王国与帝国

Kingdoms and Empires

组成一个伟大的乐队

together in one great band

和平与友好……

of peace and amity…

王国：一位国王左右各手持一个圆顶盘子。

Kingdoms: A king holding two dome-covered platters, one in each hand.

和帝国：一只蚂蚁在篝火旁戳来戳去

and Empires: An ant poking at a campfire

合在一起：涂满焦油的托加

together: Toga covered in tar

一杆进洞：高尔夫球“一杆进洞”

in one: a golf ball “hole in one”

很棒：奶酪磨碎器

great: a cheese grate

绷带：绷带

band of: a bandage

和平：和平标志

peace: a Peace sign

和：一把吉他

and: a guitar

友谊：一本书，《鬼哭神嚎》

amity: A book, The Amityville Horror

一位国王踉踉跄跄地向前走，努力保持手中圆顶大盘的平衡。他踩到了一只坐在篝火前的蚂蚁。然后，他跌倒在一件涂满黏糊糊、散发着恶臭焦油的托加袍上。一颗高尔夫球从他的口袋里掉了出来，滚落到一个奶酪烤架上，烤架上用创可贴连接着一个和平标志。和平标志倒在一把吉他上。吉他倒下，砸在了那本《鬼哭神嚎》的书上。

A king is stumbling forward, trying to balance the domed platters in his hands. He steps on an ant sitting in front of a campfire. He then falls on a toga covered in gooey, stinky tar. A golf ball falls out of one of his pockets. It rolls to a cheese grate, which is connected to a peace sign by a Band-Aid. The peace sign topples over onto a guitar. The guitar falls over and onto the book, The Amityville Horror.

墙＃4：

Wall #4:

它不会常常徒劳地挣扎，

It would not so often struggle in vain,

如果共济会成员知道他们的力量

if Masons knew their power

并珍视他们的誓言。

and valued their oaths.

米特·罗姆尼再次回归，为“它”工作

Mitt Romney is back again for the work “it”

不会：一块有结的木头

would not: a piece of wood with a knot in it

经常使用：织物柔顺剂片

so often: fabric softener sheet

斗争：一根吸管，上面有一只海鸥

struggle: a straw with a gull balanced on top of it

徒劳无功：顶部带有 N 的风向标

in vain: a weather vane with an N on top

如果是石匠：一个上面有 F 的石工罐

if Masons: A masonry jar with an F on it

了解它们的威力：新型发粉

knew their power: new hair powder

和：吉他

and: guitar

价值：任何手持尤克里里琴的名叫“Val”的人

valued: any person named “Val” holding a Ukulele

他们的誓言：燕麦发（呸）

their oaths: hair oats (yuck)

米特·罗姆尼拿着一块多节的松木。他用这块多节的松木将一片柔顺剂片在地板上推，直到一根垂直插在地板上的吸管把他挡住了。吸管顶端是一只海鸥。海鸥受惊飞走，飞过一个上面写着“N”的风向标。风向标转动并撞倒了一个前面用胶带写着“F”的玻璃罐。玻璃罐里装满了白色粉末，它倒下并将粉末洒在了一个假发上。一些粉末飘落在假发上，并覆盖了旁边的一把吉他。瓦尔帮他扶直吉他，她的另一只手拿着一把尤克里里琴。她把尤克里里琴掉进了一碗脏兮兮的燕麦中，里面还有一团头发。

Mitt Romney holds a knotty pine piece of wood. He the knotty wood to push a fabric softener sheet along the floor until he is stopped by a perpendicular straw stuck in the floor. At the top of the straw is a gull. The gull, scared, flies away and over a weather vane with an N on top of it. The weather vane turns and knocks over a masonry jar with an F taped to the front of it. The jar is full of white powder, and falls over and pours the powder onto a wig. Some of the powder floats over the wig and coats a nearby guitar. The guitar is help upright by Val, who holds a Ukulele in her other hand. She drops the Ukulele into a nasty bowl of oats with a wad of hair in it.

真恶心！但令人难忘。

Disgusting! But memorable.

因此：

Thus:

如果共济会成员了解自己的力量并重视自己的誓言，那么他们的斗争就不会那么徒劳无功

It would not so often struggle in vain, if Masons knew their power and valued their oaths

通过图像记忆为：

is memorized thru images as:

米特木结软化稻草鸥N叶片（如果）梅森新发粉和Val U'd发燕麦。

Mitt wood knot soften straw gull N vane (if) Mason new hair powder and Val U’d hair oats.

好了，完成了一段。记住这一段后，才能进入下一个空间（也就是下一段）。记住，要循序渐进。不要试图一次性把整个记忆宫殿都建起来。

There you go. One paragraph down. Only after you memorize this paragraph should you move to the next Space (and thus your next paragraph). Remember, pace yourself. Do not try to build your entire memory palace at once.

21

21

流程概述

Process Overview

B以下是前几章讨论的过程的总结。

Below is a summary of the processes discussed in previous chapters.

理解你正在记忆的内容

Understand what you’re memorizing

  • 如果你不认识某个单词，就去查一下。如果你不知道某个单词怎么发音，互联网可以帮你。如果你不明白某个句子的意思，或者不明白你正在记忆的内容的要点，就去问一位兄弟。
  • If you don’t know a word, look it up. If you don’t know how to pronounce a word, the internet can help you. If you don’t understand the meaning of a sentence or the point of what you’re memorizing, ask a brother.

组织你的工作

Organize your work

  • 给段落编号。
  • Number the paragraphs.
  • 将短段落（一两句话）合并为一个段落进行编号。
  • Combine short paragraphs (one or two sentences) into a single paragraph for numbering.
  • 将较大的段落分成较小的段落以便编号。
  • Split up larger paragraphs into smaller paragraphs for numbering.

创建你的宫殿

Create your palace

  • 找到适合你记忆内容的模型
  • Find a Model that is an appropriate size for what you’re memorizing
  • 将模型划分为空间
  • Divide the Model into Spaces
  • 将空间划分为区域
  • Divide the Spaces into Areas
  • 将区域划分为焦点（可选 - 您可以稍后在为该区域创建内存对象时执行此操作）
  • Divide the Areas into Focal Points (optional – you may do this later, when creating Memory Objects for that Area)

旅行

Travel

  • 确定您将通过模型采取的路径
  • Determine the path you will take through your Model
  • 确定你在每个空间中要走的路径
  • Determine the path you will take through each Space
  • 确定查看区域中焦点的顺序
  • Determine the order in which you will look at Focal Points in an Area

任务

Assignment

  • 将段落分配给空间
  • Assign paragraphs to Spaces
  • 将句子分配到区域
  • Assign sentences to Areas
  • 将单词分配给焦点
  • Assign words to Focal Points

用记忆对象填充你的宫殿

Populate your palace with Memory Objects

  • 前往你第一个空间的第一个区域，寻找合适的焦点，然后开始将单词转换为记忆对象，并将它们放置在这些焦点中或焦点上。在记住当前区域的单词之前，请勿为下一个区域构建记忆对象。
  • Go to your first Area of your first Space and look for good Focal Points, then begin converting words to Memory Objects and placing them in or on those Focal Points. DO NOT BUILD MEMORY OBJECTS FOR THE NEXT AREA UNTIL YOU HAVE MEMORIZED THE WORDS FOR YOUR CURRENT AREA.
  • 让你的记忆对象相互交互
  • Make your Memory Objects interact with one another
  • 前往下一个区域，再前往下一个区域，直到你用完该空间的所有区域，然后前往下一个空间。重复此操作，直到你的空间被填满。
  • Proceed to the next Area, then the next, until you have used all your Areas in that Space, then travel to the next Space. Repeat until your place is fully populated.

加强

Reinforcement

  • 根据需要重新访问已完成的区域和空间，即使在构建新的区域和空间时也是如此，以便将单词深深地印在您的记忆中。
  • Revisit completed Areas and Spaces as needed, even as you build new ones, in order to keep the words impressed deeply into your memory.

22

22

忽略的力量

The Power of Omission

一个记忆宫殿鲜为人知却非常强大的功能是，当你记不住某个单词或句子时，它会缩小你的选择范围。简而言之，记忆宫殿会告诉你某个句子或单词是否错误，让你快速排除它，并寻找更好的替代方案。请考虑上一章中示例段落的以下变体：

A little-recognized but very powerful aspect of memory palaces is that they narrow your pool of options when you can’t remember what a word or sentence is. In short, a memory palace tells you when a sentence or word is wrong, allowing you to quickly rule it out and seek a better alternative. Consider these variations of the example paragraph from the previous chapter:

  • 共济会是世界上一个伟大的和平团体。无论它存在于何处……
  • Masonry is a great Peace Society of the world. Wherever it exists…
  • 共济会是一个美好的和平团体。无论它存在于何处……
  • Masonry is a wonderful Peace Society. Wherever it exists…
  • 共济会是世界上最伟大的团体。无论它存在于何处……
  • Masonry is the great Society of the world. Wherever it exists…
  • 世界上最伟大的和平团体是共济会。无论它存在于何处……
  • The great Peace Society of the world is Masonry. Wherever it exists…
  • 共济会是世界上伟大的和平团体。无论它存在于何处……
  • Masonry is the great Peace Society of the world. Wherever it exists…
  • 共济会是世界上伟大的和平团体。无论它在哪里……
  • Masonry is the great Peace Society of the world. Wherever it is found…
  • 共济会会员组成了世界伟大的和平协会。它存在于……
  • Masons form the great Peace Society of the world. Where it exists…
  • 哪里有共济会，哪里社会就和平。
  • Wherever Masonry exists, society is peaceful.

哪一个是正确的？如果你用死记硬背的方法记忆，你可能不确定。它们说的几乎都是一样的，只是表达方式不同。你怎么知道哪个是正确的版本呢？

Which one is correct? If you used the rote repetition approach to memorization, you may not be sure. They all say pretty much the same thing, just in a different way. How are you supposed to know which is the correct version?

首先，让我们先来讨论一下，看看这些候选词中哪个包含正确的单词。我想你会同意，在这个语境中， great和wonderful非常相似。Exists和is found似乎也指代相同的事物，而where和everywhere非常相似。

First, let’s address the issue of knowing which of these candidates contains the correct words. I think you’d agree that great and wonderful are very similar in this context. Exists and is found both seem to mean about the same thing, too, and where is a lot like wherever.

但是，如果你用记忆对象来记住这段话，你几乎立刻就能知道哪些词不对。你会知道你没有为“wonderful”（精彩的）、 “ form”（形式）或“found” （发现）这些词创建记忆对象。知道哪些词不对，就成功了一半。

But, if you used Memory Objects to memorize this paragraph, you’d know almost immediately what are not the right words. You’d know that you didn’t create a Memory Object for the words wonderful or form or found. Knowing which words are not correct is half the fight.

如果你集中注意力，你就会记得有一颗葡萄，而那个记忆物体一定代表一个单词，很快你就会记得那个单词很棒。

If you concentrate, you’ll remember that there was a grape and that Memory Object must have represented a word, and in a short time, you’ll remember that word is great.

那些出口标志呢？有的，对吧？还有那个可怕的毛杆？随便什么地方。

What about those exit signs? Exists, right? And that terrible hair-lever? Wherever.

现在你只需要把这些词按正确的顺序排列。比如：“世界上伟大的和平团体是共济会。无论它存在于何处……”

Now you just need to put the words in the right order. Perhaps: “The great Peace Society of the world is Masonry. Wherever it exists…”

不。你知道这不对，因为第一个记忆物件不是葡萄。第一个记忆物件是一个玻璃罐，里面有一条发出嘶嘶声的蛇。Mason+Hiss 就是Masonry。

No. You know that’s not right because the first Memory Object was not a grape. The first Memory Object was a mason jar with a hissing snake come from it. Mason+Hiss is Masonry is.

你的大脑非常擅长记住事物的位置。我们的大脑在这方面一定非常非常擅长，否则人类物种早就灭绝了。记不住蓝莓灌木丛在哪里，记不住猎鹿的最佳地点，记不住水源，记不住我们的洞穴在哪里，就意味着死亡。

Your brain excels at remembering the placement of things. Our brains had to be really, really good at that or the human species would have perished long ago. Not being able to remember where the blueberry bushes were, or the best place to hunt deer, or to find water, or where our cave was, meant death.

然而，记住单词的准确顺序对我们的生存来说并非至关重要，这就是为什么我们在这方面仍然相当糟糕。如果你试图在不使用记忆对象的情况下记住我们例子中的单词顺序，你很容易会自欺欺人地认为这个句子确实是以“伟大的和平……”开头的。毕竟，这个句子的意思和正确的句子完全一样。但记住正确的意思并非你唯一的目标。你也希望记住单词的正确顺序。

Remembering the exact order of words, however, was not crucial to our survival, which is why we are still pretty terrible at it. If you tried to memorize the order of words in our example without the use of Memory Objects, it would be easy for you to fool yourself into thinking that the sentence really did begin “The great Peace…” After all, that sentence has exactly the same meaning as the correct one. But getting the meaning right isn’t your only goal. You want to get the words right, too, and in the right order.

23

23

区域划分

Compartmentalization

一个记忆宫殿的好处在于它能教会你如何将所学内容进行分类。每个空间大约对应一个段落，每个区域对应一个或多个句子。不使用记忆宫殿的人经常会在听课时忘记讲到哪里而不知所措。对很多这样的人来说，讲座就是一长串单词，即使忘记一个单词也会让讲师不知所措。

A benefit of the memory palace is that it teaches you to compartmentalize what you’ve learned. Each Space corresponds to approximately one paragraph and each Area correlates to one or more sentences. Individuals who don’t use memory palaces are often stumped if they lose their place in a lecture. For many such individuals, the lecture is one long chain of words, and forgetting even a single word can paralyze the lecturer.

但你不会遇到这个问题。最糟糕的情况是，如果你完全记不住宫殿某个区域中记忆物品对应的单词，你可以跳到下一个区域，甚至下一个空间。这虽然算不上完美，但总比像被车灯照到的鹿一样站在小屋中间要好得多。

But you won’t have this issue. In a worst-case scenario, if you absolutely cannot remember the words corresponding to the Memory Objects in one Area of your palace, you can skip to the next Area or even the next Space. That’s short of perfection, but it’s a lot better than standing in the middle of the lodge like a deer in the headlights.

事实上，有了记忆宫殿，你就能真正地记住你的讲课内容。不一定非要记住单词（虽然你也可以，只要努力一点），而是记住段落。你不用从起点螺旋式地走到终点，而是可以反向进行。

In fact, with a memory palace, you will literally know your lecture forward and backward. Not the words, necessarily (though you could, with some effort), but the paragraphs. Instead of spiraling in from your starting point to your finish point, you can just reverse course.

在石匠大师讲座的第三部分，我从邮箱开始，盘旋到我的房子，最后到达地下室。从地下室开始，盘旋回头，最后到达邮箱，完全没有问题。为什么会这样呢？因为我了解房子和院子的布局，也知道哪些段落应该放在哪些空间。你会发现，只要多加练习，你也能做到。

In the third section of the Master Mason’s lecture, I start at my mailbox and spiral into my house and finish in my basement. It’s no problem at all starting in my basement and spiraling backward to end at my mailbox. Why should it be? I know the layout of my house and yard, and I know what paragraphs are assigned to what Spaces. You’ll find that you can do the same, with practice.

你还可以从课程开始和结束之间的任意一点开始学习。如果一位师兄要求你跳到课程的某个部分，你只需要问他希望你从哪个主题开始，然后跳转到你记忆宫殿中保存该主题的空间即可。

You will also have the ability to start a lecture from any point between the start and finish. If a brother asks you to skip forward to a certain point in a lecture, you need only ask him what topic he wants you to start with, and then jump to the Space in your memory palace that holds that topic.

如果同一位兄弟说：“不，不是这个……这之前是什么？”，你可以轻松地后退一个空间告诉他。你也可以告诉他前两段、前四段、前五段的主题是什么。很简单。你只需在空间中倒退即可。

If that same brother were to say, “No, that’s not it…what comes before that?”, you can easily step back a Space and tell him. You can also tell him what the topic was two paragraphs before, or four, or five. It’s easy. You’re just walking backward through your Spaces.

但想想如果没有记忆宫殿，这将是多么具有挑战性！

But think how challenging this would be without a memory palace!

24

24

最佳实践

Best Practices

B构建记忆宫殿是记忆长篇文章的绝佳方法，但操作需巧妙。以下是一些记忆的“最佳实践”。

Building memory palaces is an excellent way to memorize long passages, but it should be done smartly. What follows are some memorization “best practices.”

理解

Comprehension

这应该不言而喻，但在尝试记忆之前，你真的需要先理解材料。把冗长的句子简化一下。我们的仪式很多内容很久以前就由好心的兄弟们写下来，他们显然是按字数收费的（如果是生僻词或五个或五个以上音节的词，或许还会有额外奖励）。

This should go without saying, but you really need to comprehend material before you attempt to memorize it. Take long, wordy sentences and dumb them down. Much our ritual was written long ago by well-meaning brothers who were apparently getting paid by the word (and perhaps a bonus for obscure words or words with five or more syllables).

我发现一个有效的技巧是给每个段落都加一个标题。如果你想不出标题，很可能你并没有真正理解这个段落。一旦你给每个段落都加了标题，再回顾一下标题，你或许就能看到“整体图景”，也就是作者想要表达什么，以及如何表达。

One technique I’ve found effective is to give a title to each paragraph. If you can’t come up with a title, odds are you don’t really understand the paragraph. Once you have each paragraph titled, review the titles and you may see the “big picture,” i.e., what the author was trying to convey, and how.

找出你不认识的单词的意思，并确保你知道怎么发音。如果一个单词看起来很熟悉，但用法很奇怪，就去查一下。试着确定这个单词在仪式记录时的用法。它可能与今天的用法大相径庭。

Find the meaning of words you don’t know, and be sure you know how to pronounce them. If a word seems familiar but is used in a weird way, look it up. Try to determine how the word was used when the ritual was written. It might be very different than how the word is used today.

以“dispose”一词为例。如今，我们通常将这个词与另一个词“disposal”（处置）联系在一起。我们被要求妥善处理可回收物、废油和垃圾。因此，“disposal of something”（处置某物）的含义变成了“把它处理掉”。

Take, for example, the word “dispose.” Today, we normally connect this word with another word: disposal. We are asked to properly dispose of our recyclables and used oil and trash. Disposing of something has thus come to mean “getting rid of it.”

但这并不是它的本意。这个词源于拉丁语disponere，意为“安排”。在古法语中，它变成了poser，意为“放置”。你有没有被摄影师摆过姿势拍照？

Yet this wasn’t the original meaning. The word’s origin is the Latin word disponere, which meant “to arrange.” In old French, this became poser, which meant, “to place.” Have you ever been posed for a photograph by a photographer?

综合起来，我们可以推断，一个世纪前 dispose 的意思是“放置或安排”，而不是“摆脱或扔掉”。这一点很重要。从这个意义上来说，dispose 的意思是“将某人或某物移到另一个地方”。

Taken together, we can assume that a century ago dispose meant “to place or arrange” and not “to get rid of or throw away.” This is important. In this sense, disposing means to “move someone or something to another location.”

现在，想想看。如果你被安置在收容所，你很可能被从一个地方转移到另一个地方。因此，如果你没有被从一个地方转移到另一个地方，你就没有被处置。如果你站在原地，你就没有被处置。

Now, think about that. If you are being disposed in lodge, you’re probably being sent from one location to another. It follows that if you’re not being moved from one location to another, you’re not being disposed. And, if you’re standing in place, you haven’t been disposed.

与此相关，在古代，conduct的意思是“引导”。因此，如果你被安排（指示从一个地方移动到另一个地方），但不知道如何到达那里，那么你可能会被别人带去那里。

Related to this, in ye olden times, conduct meant “to guide.” Thus, if you were disposed (instructed to move from one location to another), and didn’t know how to get there, you would probably be conducted there by someone else.

因此，我们预期“disposed”和“conducted”这两个词会成对出现。一个接一个。如果我记住了一个包含“ disposed ”的句子，我就会预期下一个句子可能包含“conducted”这个词。如果我认为一个句子包含“ conducted ” ，但前一个句子没有包含“disposed”这个词，我就有理由怀疑自己的记忆，并再思考一会儿接下来要说的话。

Consequently, we’d expect the words disposed and conducted to be paired. One should follow the other. If I had memorized a sentence that contained the word disposed, I’d anticipate that next sentence might contain the word conducted. If I thought a sentence contained the word conducted, but the previous sentence didn’t contain the word disposed, I’d have a reason to doubt my memory and to think a moment longer about what I was about to say.

分析

Analysis

在学习某个部分、讲座等时要注意以下几点：

Here are some things to look for when studying a part, lecture, etc.:

模式。相信我，它们就在那里。一旦你找到了模式，你就能理解你正在记忆的内容的“节奏”，这对记忆课文会有很大的帮助。

Patterns. Trust me, they’re there. Once you find the patterns, you’ll understand the “rhythm” of what you’re memorizing, which can be a tremendous help in memorizing the text.

锚点。例如，如果“then”这个词在一个段落中出现了四次，你可以把“then”作为一个锚点，也就是一系列记忆对象的开头或结尾。这会在心理上提示你开始下一个记忆对象系列。

Anchors. For example, if the word “then” is used four times in a paragraph, you can make “then” an anchor, i.e., either the start or end of a series of Memory Objects. That will mentally cue you to start the next series.

成对词。仪式中会用到很多成对的词。这些词通常是同义词，或者近义词。例如，“这里，在这个地方”，或者“秘密的，看不见的”，或者“禁止的，不允许的”。造成这种情况的原因有很多，这里就不一一赘述了，但仔细研究这些词对可能会有所帮助。通常，它们会揭示出某种模式。试着为这些成对的词想出一个记忆对象。

Pairs. The rituals use a lot of paired words. These words are usually synonymous, or nearly so. For example, “here and in this place,” or “secret and unseen,” or “forbidden and not permitted.” There are reasons for this, none of which can be discussed here, but zooming in on these word pairs can be useful. Often, they will reveal a pattern. Try to come up with a single Memory Object for paired words like these.

分块

Chunking

组块化就是把你想要记忆的内容分成小块。切勿贪多嚼不烂，也不要试图一次性记住太多内容，以免给自己造成负担。记忆是一个循序渐进的过程。不堪重负会导致失败，失败会导致沮丧，最终可能导致你彻底放弃记忆。

Chunking is the division of what you’re trying to memorize into bite-size portions. Never bite off more than you can chew, and never overtask yourself by trying to memorize too much at once. Memorization is a gradual process. Overwhelming yourself will result in failure, and failure will result in discouragement, and that could cause you to give up on memorization altogether.

有句谚语说：“如果演讲很长，就把内容分成片段来学。”两千年前，这是一条可靠的建议，今天，它依然是一条可靠的建议。

Per Ad Herennium, “If a speech is on the long, learn it in fragments.” It was solid advice two thousand years ago, and it’s solid advice today.

我建议你一开始就设定一个目标，每天学一句话，然后熟悉接下来的句子。你可能会觉得这太简单了，那就提高一下水平，每天背两句话。如果太难，那就每天只背几个单词。这不是一场比赛。选择最适合你的方式。你试图记住的东西已经存在很久了。它不会消失。

I’d suggest you start with the goal of learning one sentence a day and becoming familiar with the following sentence. You might find this too easy, in which case you should up your game and memorize two sentences a day. If that’s too tough, just go for a few words a day. This isn’t a race. Do what works best for you. The stuff you’re trying to memorize has been around for a long, long time. It’s not going anywhere.

记住，我所说的“句子”既包括普通句子，也包括句子片段，长度不应超过十个单词，也不应该少于五个单词。毕竟，记住一个只有两个单词的句子并不费力，而记住一个有一百个单词的句子就太过头了。

And remember, by “sentence” I’m referring to both regular sentences and sentence fragments, which shouldn’t be any longer than about ten words, or any shorter than about five. Memorizing a two-word sentence isn’t much of an effort, after all, while memorizing a sentence with hundred words is over-doing it.

用你的记忆宫殿来表达，你应该尝试每天记住一个区域。

Put in terms of your memory palace, you should try to memorize perhaps an Area a day.

学习间隔

Study Intervals

这一点很重要。你必须采取系统化的记忆方法，这种方法需要包含所谓的“间隔重复”。这也被称为“间隔检索”、“渐进间隔”或“间隔排练”。

This is important. You must take a systematic approach to memorization, and that approach needs to include what is known as “spaced repetition.” This is also referred to as “spaced retrieval,” or “graduated intervals,” or “spaced rehearsal.”

把你的大脑想象成一块肌肉。如果你有过举重经验，你就会知道每天或每天多次锻炼同一块肌肉实际上会阻碍肌肉的生长。肌肉在锻炼后需要时间恢复，大块肌肉比小块肌肉需要的时间更长。

Think of your brain as a muscle. If you’ve had any experience with weightlifting, you know that working the same muscles every day, or several times a day, will actually retard muscle growth. Muscles need time to recuperate after a workout, with the larger muscles needing more time than the smaller ones.

因此，认真的举重运动员会制定一个训练计划。比如，他们可能每三天锻炼一次二头肌，这段时间的间隔刚好够让肌肉达到最大生长速度，然后再进行一次压力训练，希望能够获得更大的增长。

Consequently, serious weightlifters maintain a schedule. They might exercise their biceps every three days, for example, that interval being just long enough to allow the muscles to reach maximum growth before again stressing them in hopes of gaining still more growth.

大脑的运作方式也大同小异。记忆就像举重一样，最好通过间歇训练来实现。

The brain works in much the same way. Memorization, like weightlifting, is best accomplished through interval training.

在记忆中，我们关注的不是肌肉的大小，而是记忆得有多好。我们记忆得最好的部分——比如一段话的前两句话——应该比我们记忆得最差的部分——比如同一段话的第三句和第四句——学习得少。

In memorization, we don’t focus on the size of the muscle. We focus on how well we’ve memorized something. Those things which we have memorized best – perhaps the first two sentences of a paragraph – should be studied less often than those things we’ve memorized least - perhaps the third and fourth sentences of the same paragraph.

看到这里，你们很多人都点头附和，嘟囔着：“当然了。我为什么要浪费时间学习那些我已经记住的东西？学习那些我还没记住的讲座或部分内容才有意义。我不需要你告诉我！”

Here, many of you are nodding your heads and mumbling, “Of course. Why should I waste time studying what I’ve already memorized? It only makes sense to study the portions of a lecture or part which I haven’t memorized. I don’t need you to tell me that!”

你说得对。问题是，我们很多人除了学习那些还没背下来或没完全背下来的内容外，还会继续学习已经记住的内容。我们这样做的目的是，认为学习得越多，就越好。我们假设每天学习同一个句子，即使我们已经背下来了，也比每隔几天或几周学习一次要好。难道反复学习同一个句子，真的能把这个句子牢牢地印在脑子里吗？即使这看起来像是在浪费时间，这难道不是一件好事吗？

And you’re right. The thing is, many of us do continue to study what we’ve already memorized, in addition to those things we haven’t memorized, or haven’t fully memorized. We do this thinking that the more we study everything, the better off we’ll be. We assume that studying the same sentence every day, even if we’ve already memorized it, is better than studying it every few days, or every few weeks. Doesn’t constantly studying the same sentence, again and again, really hammer that sentence into our brains? Isn’t that a good thing, even if it might seem like a waste of time?

不。事实上，这很糟糕。你实际上是在伤害你自己——或者至少是你的记忆。

No. In fact, that’s a bad thing. You’re actually hurting yourself – or at least, your memory.

事情是这样的：

Here’s the deal:

当你第一次记住一个句子时，它并不在你的长期记忆中。它存在于你的短期记忆中。根据定义，你的短期记忆只能在短时间内可靠。你希望你记住的内容能够存储在你的长期记忆中。你的短期记忆只能暂时保存相对少量的信息，而你的长期记忆几乎可以毫不费力地在更长的时间内保存大量的信息。

When you first memorize a sentence, it is not in your long-term memory. It is in your short-term memory. By definition, your short-term memory is reliable for only a short period of time. You want what you’ve memorized to be stored in your long-term memory. Your short-term memory is only capable of holding a relatively small amount of information, on a temporary basis, while your long-term memory can hold a massive amount of information with almost no effort for a much longer period.

那么，我们如何才能将你记住的句子从短期记忆转化为长期记忆呢？答案是让大脑自然地做到这一点。通过按照规定的时间间隔学习某些内容，你就是在“告诉”你的大脑，你正在记住的东西不会消失。它会在一段不确定的时间内不断出现，一次又一次。高效的大脑会迅速采取行动，开始将这些东西从“临时存储”（你的短期记忆）转移到长期记忆，或者说“永久存储”。

So, how do we get that sentence you memorized from short-term memory to long-term memory? By letting the brain do it naturally. By studying something at prescribed intervals, you are “telling” your brain that the thing you are memorizing isn’t going away. It’s going to keep appearing, again and again, for an indefinite period of time. The brain, which is highly efficient, will salute smartly and begin moving that thing from “temporary holding” – your short-term memory – into the long-term memory, or “permanent storage.”

但是，如果你过于频繁地学习已知的知识，你的大脑就不会将其放入长期记忆中。它只会停留在短期记忆中。任何记忆从短期记忆转移到长期记忆，只有当你忽略它一段时间，然后重新引入它，再忽略它更长时间，然后重新引入它，如此反复，才会发生。

But if you study something you already know, too frequently, your brain won’t put it into long-term memory. It will remain in short-term memory. Movement of anything remembered from short-term memory to long-term memory only happens if you ignore it for a prescribed period, and then reintroduce it, and then ignore it again for an even longer period, then reintroduce it, and so on.

打个比方：如果你能随时随地从附近的杂货店买到任何你想要的食物，你就没有理由在家里储存食物。但如果发生经济衰退或战争，你可能会发现你的杂货店经常缺货几天、几周甚至几个月。在这种情况下，你不会依赖杂货店（你的“短期”供应商），而是会在有货时尽可能多地购买食物必需品，然后把它们储存起来以备将来使用（“长期储存”）。

Here’s an analogy: If you can get any food you want, whenever you want, from your local grocery store, there’s no reason for you to store food in your home. But if there is an economic depression, or a war, you might find that your grocery store is often out of the things you need for days, weeks, or even months. Under such circumstances, you would not rely on your grocery store (your “short-term” supplier), but would instead buy as many food necessities as you could afford when they were available, and then you’d store them away for future use (“long-term storage”).

你的大脑也以类似的方式运作。你需要让它坚强起来，然后说：“听着，我不会每天都重复这句话，因为说实话，这会让你变得懒惰。我要暂时剥夺你读这句话的权利，然后再考验你，你最好做好准备。”

Your brain works in a similar manner. You need to toughen it up and say, “Look, I’m not going to keep going over this same sentence every day, because, honestly, it’s making you lazy. I’m going to deprive you of it for a while, and then test you, and you better be ready when that happens.”

您如何知道何时该停止学习某样东西，以及要等多久才重新开始测试自己？

How do you know when it’s time to stop studying something, and how long do you wait before your return to it to test yourself?

最简单的方法是使用电脑软件或移动设备应用程序。你可以在互联网上搜索“抽认卡软件”或“抽认卡应用程序”来找到它们，或者直接访问维基百科页面，向下滚动几段文字即可找到。

The easiest approach is to use computer software or a mobile device app. You can find these via an internet search for “flashcard software” or “flashcard app,” or by just going to the Wikipedia page for one of these terms and scrolling down a few paragraphs.

这些程序和应用程序通常使用虚拟抽认卡。在对你试图记住的内容进行测试后，它们会问你一个问题，例如“答对这个答案有多难？” 它会为你提供“容易”、“有点难”、“困难”和“不可能”等答案选择。

The programs and apps typically use virtual flashcards. After quizzing you on something you’re trying to memorize, they’ll ask you a question such as “How difficult was it to get the answer right?” It will offer you a choice of answers like “easy,” “a little difficult,” “difficult,” and “impossible.”

如果你点击“简单”，程序会在一段时间内（可能是几小时、几天或几周）不再显示该卡片。如果你选择“有点难”，间隔会更短。如果你选择“不可能”，你可能会在几分钟甚至几秒钟内再次看到该问题（程序会假设你在继续测试之前已经花时间学习过）。

If you so you click on “easy,” the program won’t show you the card again for a period of time – it could be hours, days, or weeks. If you select “a little difficult,” the interval will be shorter. If you select “impossible,” you’ll probably see that question again within minutes or even seconds (the program assumes that if you’ve taken the time to study before continuing the quiz).

你可能想知道如何使用包含深奥材料的软件或应用程序。毕竟，程序必须知道该问你什么，对吧？这难道不意味着你必须把深奥材料输入到程序里吗？

You may wonder how you can use software or an app with esoteric materials. After all, the program has to know what to ask you, right? Doesn’t that mean you have to type the esoteric materials into the program?

不。记住，你正在构建一座记忆宫殿。虚拟抽认卡的“正面”，也就是“问题”，可以是“厨房，带水槽的墙”，或者“后院，花园”，或者“客厅，中间”。抽认卡的“背面”，也就是正确的“答案”，可以是一个或多个你的记忆对象列表——无论需要多少个，只要能让你想起正确的单词就行（这里要注意——不要让任何人，包括非共济会会员或低等级的共济会会员，都明白答案）。

No. Remember, you’re building a memory palace. The “front” of the virtual flashcard, which is the “question,” can be “Kitchen, wall with sink,” or “Backyard, garden,” or “Living Room, center.” The “back” of the flashcard, which is the correct “answer,” can be a list of one or more of your Memory Objects – however many it takes to remind you of the right words (be cautious here – don’t make the answer obvious to anyone, including non-Masons, or Masons of lower degrees).

你实际上并没有记录单词本身。如果你完全被难住了，甚至连你的记忆对象都无法给你正确的单词，那么你就该回去参考你的密码、监视器或其他兄弟了。

You don’t actually record the words themselves. If you are so utterly stumped that even your Memory Objects don’t give you the right words, it’s time for you to refer back to your cipher, or monitor, or another brother.

以我们的“和平社会”为例，对于抽认卡＃1，我会在程序中输入以下信息：

Using our “Peace Society” example, for flashcard #1, I would enter the following information into the program:

抽认卡正面（“问题”）：客厅，墙#1

Front of flashcard (the “question”): Living Room, Wall #1

抽认卡背面（“答案”）：罐子 – 蛇 – 葡萄 – 标志 – 外星人 – 地球仪 – 头发 – 杠杆 – 出口标志

Back of the flashcard (the “answer”): Jar – Snake – Grape – Sign – Alien – Globe – Hair – Lever – Exit Signs

如果你是老派，更喜欢使用真正的抽认卡，那么你应该研究一下莱特纳系统。有很多网站和视频可以教你如何将抽认卡整理成不同的堆或盒，从而帮助你安排学习时间。如果你想完全回归传统，或许可以在当地图书馆找到这方面的书籍。

If you’re the old-fashioned type and would rather use real flashcards, you should investigate the Leitner System. There are plenty of websites and videos that can teach you how to organize your flashcards into separate piles or boxes to help you space your studies. If you want to go completely retro, you can probably find a book on that subject at your local library.

重温原始资料

Revisit the Source Material

虽然达到认为自己已经记住了所有需要记住的内容的程度是一个很大的成就，但在你过于自信之前，重新回顾一下你的原始资料还是有好处的。我曾经以为自己把一堂课的内容从头到尾都背下来了，结果却发现我在背的过程中遗漏了一个记忆对象。我从未注意到，其他人也没有，因为其他人都不了解这堂课的内容，而且我说的话仍然很有道理。只是它错了。

While it’s a great achievement to reach a point at which you think you’ve memorized everything you need to memorize, it pays to revisit your source material before you get overly confident. I once thought that I had a lecture memorized forward and backward, only to discover that I had dropped a Memory Object somewhere along the way. I never noticed, and no one else did either, because no one else knew the lecture and because what I said still made perfect sense. It just wasn’t correct.

直到我浏览了一遍讲座（已经讲了两遍！）才发现自己漏掉了什么。随着时间的推移，在已经记住的内容中插入或修改单词变得越来越困难。最好尽早对照原文核对记忆，并且偶尔再核对一遍。

It wasn’t until I scanned the lecture (after having given it twice!) that I saw what I had been omitting. Inserting or correcting words into something you’ve memorized gets more difficult with the passing of time. Better to check your memory against the source sooner than later - and again, on occasion.

冥想

Meditation

冥想对不同的人有不同的含义。对我来说，冥想就是坐在沙发上，闭上双眼，手边放着一杯咖啡。对有些人来说，冥想是凝视地平线。对另一些人来说，冥想是盘腿而坐，保持挺直的姿势。无论冥想的形式如何，其目的都是抛开所有压垮你思绪的日常杂念，以便专注于更重要的事情——或者干脆什么都不去想。

Meditation means different things to different people. For me, meditation is sitting on my couch with my eyes closed, a cup of coffee close at hand. For some, it’s staring at the horizon. For others, it’s sitting cross-legged with an erect posture. In whatever form, the purpose of meditation is to shove aside all the daily clutter that weighs your mind down in order to focus on something more important - or to not focus on anything at all.

冥想除了能缓解压力，还能帮助你记忆。重要的是，你每天要找个时间和地点，悠闲地漫步在你的记忆宫殿里，记下缺失或难以记忆的记忆对象，并确保你能顺利地穿过它，不会迷失或困惑。缺失的记忆对象表明你可能需要寻找最初创造的记忆的替代方案。忘记如何从一个空间移动到另一个空间，则表明你需要找到一条更直观的路径来穿越你的记忆宫殿。

In addition to being a stress reliever, meditation helps you memorize. It’s important that you find some time and place each day to take a leisurely stroll through your memory palace, taking note of missing or difficult Memory Objects and ensuring you can travel through it without getting lost or confused. Missing Memory Objects are an indication that you might need to find alternatives to what you initially created. Forgetting how to move from one Space to another suggests you need to find a more intuitive route through your palace.

CR Dunning, Jr. 所著的《沉思共济会》是一本关于共济会背景下冥想的精彩书籍。其副标题是《正念、冥想和工艺想象的基本应用》。

A fantastic book on meditation in a Masonic context is Contemplative Masonry, by C.R. Dunning, Jr. Its subtitle is Basic applications of mindfulness, meditation, and imagery for the craft.

测试

Testing

重要的是，你不能仅仅依靠学习来记住作品。你需要自我测试，或者更好的是，让别人测试你。测试可以有多种形式。也许你只是背诵你记住的内容，并根据需要由另一位兄弟纠正。也许是一位兄弟挑战你背诵作品的一部分，而不背诵其前一部分。也可能是另一个人给你提供作品的不同版本，并问你哪个是正确的。一如既往，发挥你的想象力。

It’s important that you not rely on study alone to memorize a work. You need to test yourself, or better, have someone else test you. This test could take one of several forms. Perhaps it’s just you reciting what you’ve memorized and being corrected by another brother, as needed. Perhaps it’s a brother challenging you to recite a portion of a work without the portion preceding it. It could be another person giving you different variations of a work and asking you which is right. As always, use your imagination.

测试已被证明有助于保留已记住的内容。参考 Roediger 和 Karpicke 的研究《测试增强学习：参加记忆测试可提高长期记忆》，其中写道：“参加记忆测试不仅可以评估一个人所知道的内容，还可以增强后期的记忆，这种现象称为测试效应。”我们用与教育相关的材料研究了这种效应，并调查测试是否仅仅因为测试提供了重新学习材料的机会而促进学习。在两项实验中，学生学习了散文段落，并参加了一到三次即时自由回忆测试（没有反馈），或者重新学习了材料的次数与接受测试的学生相同。然后，​​学生在 5 分钟、2 天或 1 周后参加了最终记忆测试。当 5 分钟后进行最终测试时，重复学习比重复测试提高了回忆效果。然而，在延迟测试中，尽管重复学习增强了学生对自己记忆材料能力的信心，但之前的测试比学习产生的记忆效果要好得多。测试是改进学习的有力手段，而不仅仅是评估学习效果。 “（斜体字是我加的）。

The need for testing has been proven to help retain those things memorized. Reference Roediger and Karpicke’s study, Test-enhanced learning: taking memory tests improves long-term retention, which reads, “Taking a memory test not only assesses what one knows, but also enhances later retention, a phenomenon known as the testing effect. We studied this effect with educationally relevant materials and investigated whether testing facilitates learning only because tests offer an opportunity to restudy material. In two experiments, students studied prose passages and took one or three immediate free-recall tests, without feedback, or restudied the material the same number of times as the students who received tests. Students then took a final retention test 5 min, 2 days, or 1 week later. When the final test was given after 5 min, repeated studying improved recall relative to repeated testing. However, on the delayed tests, prior testing produced substantially greater retention than studying, even though repeated studying increased students' confidence in their ability to remember the material. Testing is a powerful means of improving learning, not just assessing it.” (italics are mine).

虽然你应该使用前面讨论过的间歇学习系统来测试自己，但仅仅自我测试是不够的。你需要别人来测试你。这正是本研究关注的测试类型。对你来说，这意味着找一位兄弟来测试你，也就是听你背诵你记住的内容，并在必要时纠正你或提供帮助。这位兄弟应该是一位已经记住你正在学习的内容的兄弟，或者是一位可以参考监视器或密码并跟着你学习的兄弟。

While you should test yourself using the interval study system earlier discussed, self-testing isn’t enough. You need someone else to test you. That’s the type of testing the study focused on. For you, this means finding a brother to test you, i.e., listen to you recite what you’ve memorized and correct you or offer help, as necessary. This should be a brother who has already memorized what you’re studying on, or who can refer to a monitor or cipher and follow along.

话虽如此，你应该建议测试你的人，只有当你犯了错误或向他寻求帮助时才介入。有时你只是需要一点时间来整理思绪。停顿并不代表错误。

That said, you should advise the person testing you only to intervene if you’ve made a mistake or asked him for help. There will be times when you simply need a second to collect your thoughts. Pauses are not errors.

学习时间

Study Times

找时间学习或默读背诵的内容并不容易。我发现，在上下班路上以及睡觉前默读（在脑子里复习）最容易。当然，每个人的作息时间都不一样。如果一天中某个时间你几乎没时间做其他事情，那么这正是默读背诵内容的好时机。

Finding time to study or mentally rehearse what you’ve memorized isn’t easy. I’ve found that mental rehearsal (going over what I’ve memorized in my head) is easiest during my drive to and from work, and when I go to bed. Everyone’s got a different schedule, of course. If there’s a time of the day in which you’re restricted from doing much of anything else, that’s a good time to mentally go over what you’ve memorized.

我有时会在宿舍的晚上早点到，然后在车里把记住的部分复习一遍。午餐时间也是学习的好时机。无论你的情况如何，重要的是每天抽出几分钟时间学习。如果你能在短短的时间内记住几个单词，就算成功了。记住24英寸的距离，合理安排你的时间。

I sometimes arrive early on lodge nights and go over my memorized parts while still in my car. Lunchtime can also afford you a good opportunity to study. Whatever your situation, the important thing is that you find time to spend a few minutes each day to study. If you can memorize just a few words in that short span of time, that’s a success. Be mindful of the twenty-four-inch gauge, and manage your time wisely.

我们的工艺原则

Principles of our Craft

  • 蜂巢：勤奋，每天学习。
  • The beehive: Be industrious. Study every day.
  • 沙漏：时光飞逝，别再拖延。
  • The hourglass: Time flies. Don’t put it off.
  • 梯子：相信自己的能力，希望取得伟大的成就，并帮助你的兄弟记忆，即使他们帮助你。
  • The ladder: Have faith in your abilities, hope to achieve great things, and help your brothers with memorization, even as they help you.
  • 全视之眼：思考一下你正在阅读的内容、它为什么重要以及它的历史或哲学意义。
  • The all-seeing eye: Think about what you’re reading, why it’s important, and the historical or philosophical significance of it.
  • 锚点：在你的记忆位置找到记忆锚点。
  • The anchor: Find memory anchors in your memory locations.
  • 马赛克路面：要有方法。寻找规律。感恩你所学到的一切，并将你的成功作为更伟大成就的基础。
  • The mosaic pavement: Be methodological. Look for patterns. Be thankful for what you’ve learned and use your successes as foundations for greater things.
  • 指向赤裸心脏的剑：记住，你将根据你的功绩（努力）获得回报。
  • The sword pointing to a naked heart: Keep in mind that you will be rewarded according to your merits (efforts).
  • 泰勒之剑守护的宪法之书：记住不要向站在门廊前的人透露深奥的部分。
  • The book of constitutions guarded by the Tyler’s sword: Remember not to disclose esoteric portions to those standing before the porch.
  • 指南针：不要让自己过度劳累。
  • Compass: Don’t over-extend yourself.
  • 24英寸轨距：规划好时间，并根据自己的节奏进行练习。提前计划，了解每天需要学习多少行才能达到目标。
  • 24” gauge: Budget your time and pace yourself. Plan ahead and know how many lines you’ll need to learn each day to reach your goal.

二十五

25

维护

Maintenance

是你需要制定某种维护计划，尤其是在你不经常使用所记住的内容的情况下。我尝试至少每两周背诵一次我记住的部分。这并不难，也不费时间。这肯定比忘记所记住的内容再重新开始要容易得多！

You need to establish some kind of maintenance schedule, especially if you’re not using what you’ve memorized on a regular basis. I attempt to recite the parts I’ve memorized at least once every two weeks. It’s not difficult and doesn’t take much time. It’s certainly easier than forgetting what you’ve memorized and starting over!

无论你背诵得多么好，你都会忘记一些东西。如果你背诵的内容只是偶尔需要用到，情况尤其如此。比如，我的职责之一是背诵EA学位课程的第三部分。和大多数分会一样，我的分会不需要每个月都进行这项课程。事实上，两次EA学位课程之间可能间隔三四个月。虽然我偶尔会排练我的课程，但没有什么能取代现场表演。如果没有人照看，记忆宫殿就会慢慢崩塌，这意味着你需要时不时地进行一些维护。

No matter how well you’ve memorized your work, you’re going to forget things. This is particularly true if what you’ve memorized is needed only periodically. As an example, one of my roles is to recite the third section of the EA degree lecture. Like most lodges, mine doesn’t need to perform this degree every month. In fact, three or four months might pass between EA degrees. While I do occasionally rehearse my lecture, there’s no substitute for performing it live. Unattended, a memory palace can slowly start to crumble, which means you’re going to have to do some upkeep from time to time.

进行维护时，不必非要坚持原计划。正如我之前提到的，无法回忆起记忆对象可能意味着它本身就不太好。如果牛奶变酸了，你不会把它放回冰箱，指望第二天会变好。你应该把它扔掉，然后买新鲜的牛奶。

When doing maintenance, don’t feel compelled to stick to your original plan. As I mentioned earlier, the inability to recall a Memory Object probably means that it wasn’t a very good one. If milk turns sour, you don’t put it back in the refrigerator in hopes that it’ll improve the next day. You throw it away and buy fresh milk.

记忆宫殿的运作方式也一样。如果一个记忆对象反复让你失望，不要强求。相反，考虑替换它。寻找更好的东西来修补你发现的漏洞。这可能需要你替换一个对象，也可能需要你替换多个对象，甚至需要重新设计一个区域或空间。不要惊慌。这很自然。修补是这个过程的一部分。

Memory palaces work the same way. If a Memory Object repeatedly fails you, don’t force the issue. Instead, consider replacing it. Look for something better to patch the hole you’ve found. That might require you to replace the one object, or it might require you to replace several objects, or even redesign an Area or Space. Don’t panic. That’s natural. Patching is a part of the process.

一旦你完成了记忆宫殿，记住了你想记住的内容，记忆对象可能会开始消退。它们偶尔会重新出现，通常是在你记不住某个单词的时候。但我的经验是，它们最终会消退到很难再找到它们。这并非坏事。正如前文所述，记忆对象就像模具，在不需要的时候（至少在逐字记忆的情况下）会在某种程度上被破坏并丢弃。如果需要，你随时可以创建新的记忆对象，或者让旧的记忆对象重新焕发生机。

Once you’ve completed your memory palace and have memorized what you want to memorize, the Memory Objects will probably begin to recede. They’ll pop back into existence on occasion, usually if you struggle with a word, but my experience is that they eventually recede so far back that it can be difficult to find them again. This isn’t a bad thing. As already discussed, the Memory Objects are molds, and are, in a way, broken and discarded when not needed (at least with verbatim memorization). You can always create new ones or bring the old ones back to life, if necessary.

有趣的是，模型是永久的，或者说近乎永久的。即使记忆对象被丢弃很久，模型依然存在，就像一座没有演员或道具的古老剧院。这意味着，即使记忆对象已经消失，你在背诵记忆内容时，也可能会发现自己的思绪游离于模型之外。我猜这是因为用于空间关系的神经通路与用于记忆对象的神经通路截然不同。

Interestingly, the Model is permanent, or nearly so. Long after the Memory Objects are discarded, the Model remains, like an ancient theater devoid of actors or props. This means that you’ll probably find yourself mentally wandering it when reciting what you’ve memorized, even when the Memory Objects are missing. I assume this is because neural pathways used for spatial relationships differ substantially for those used for Memory Objects.

模型一旦建成，几乎不可能被摧毁。这是一件好事，因为即使没有记忆对象，模型仍然能有效地帮助我们记住所记住的内容。通常，只需走进房间，瞥一眼墙壁，或观察一下背景物体，记忆对象的“幽灵”就会开始工作。文字会自然而然地浮现在你的脑海中。

Models, once built, are almost impossible to destroy. This is a good thing because the Models are still effective at helping us retain what we’ve memorized even without its Memory Objects. Stepping into a room, glancing at a wall, or surveying background objects is usually all that’s necessary for the “ghosts” of the Memory Objects to do their work. The words will come to you.

当你达到这一点时，你可以选择将你的记忆宫殿从逐字模型转换为列表模型。这很简单。只需为每个空间构建一个记忆对象，并将其放置在显眼的地方，例如门口。例如，如果该空间包含一段关于小屋珠宝的段落，则只需将小屋珠宝放在那里即可。如果该段落是关于道德的，则在那里放置一个大方块。我将这些记忆对象视为“标记”。它们可以帮助你保持房屋整洁。

When you reach this point, you may opt to transform your memory palace from a verbatim Model to a list Model. This is simple enough. Simply build a single Memory Object for each Space and place it in a conspicuous place, like a doorway. If the Space houses a paragraph on the jewels of the lodge, for example, simply place the jewels of the lodge there. If the paragraph is about the morality, place a large Square there. I think of these Memory Objects as “markers.” They help you keep your house in order.

值得深思的是：在共济会内部，几乎所有你需要的标记都已经以符号、徽章、象形文字等形式存在。你无需创造它们。你只需将已经提供的东西放在正确的位置即可。这样做可能会带来顿悟——甚至多次顿悟。

And here is something that merits contemplation: Within Freemasonry, almost all of the markers you’ll need already exist in the form of symbols, emblems, hieroglyphs, etc. You don’t have to create them. You simply need to take the things already provided you and put them in the right place. Doing that can lead to an epiphany – several, even.

但那些应该去体验，而不是去描述。

But those should be experienced, not described.

二十六

26

补充技术

Supplementary Techniques

西虽然我相信记忆宫殿是大多数兄弟记忆长篇文章的最佳技巧，但还有其他技巧可以单独使用，也可以作为记忆宫殿的补充。

While I believe that the memory palace is the best technique for most brothers to memorize long passages, there are other techniques which can be used either alone, or as supplements, to the memory palace.

画出你的记忆对象

Draw Your Memory Objects

研究表明，绘画有助于我们记住它们。因此，画下你的记忆物件，是将它们更深刻地印在脑海中的好方法。你甚至可以画多个记忆物件，以巩固它们在一个区域或空间中的关系。你不需要成为一名艺术家。画得可能很糟糕，但这没关系。你不是在展示它们，而是为了增强你的记忆。

Studies show that drawing things helps us to remember them. Drawing your Memory Objects would thus be a great way of impressing them more deeply into your mind. You might even draw multiple Memory Objects to cement their relationship to one another in an Area or Space. You don’t need to be an artist. The drawings might be horrible, but it doesn’t matter. You’re not putting them on display. You’re drawing to enhance your memory.

有人可能会反对，认为绘制我们技艺中深奥部分的记忆对象违背了我们的誓言。我认为这有点牵强。首先，这假设你是一位了不起的艺术家。其次，这假设看到你绘制的记忆对象的人能够以某种方式解读它们。考虑到记忆对象的抽象性质及其可能形成的数十种方式，这似乎不太可能。除非这些对象能够被他人理解，否则你并没有违背誓言。请自行判断。

It could be objected that drawing Memory Objects of esoteric portions of our craft is a violation of our oaths. I think that’s a stretch. First, it assumes that you’re one heck of an artist. Second, it assumes that someone who sees your drawings of Memory Objects could somehow decipher them. Given the abstract nature of Memory Objects and the dozens of ways they might be formed, this seems highly unlikely. Unless the objects can be made intelligible by others, you have not broken your oath. Use your own discretion.

触发

Triggering

你有没有过这样的经历：吃了一种多年未曾吃过的食物，几乎立刻就涌现出那段时光的记忆？不知何故，这种味道似乎能激活你大脑中沉寂已久的神经元，让你想起多年未曾想起的人和事。不过，触发这种感觉的不一定是食物或饮料的味道。触发因素可能是你很久未曾体验过的气味或声音。

Have you ever eaten a food that you haven’t eaten in years and almost immediately experienced a flood of memories from that previous period? Somehow the flavor seems to cause long-dormant neurons in your brain to spark back to life, causing you to think about people and events that you’ve not thought about for years. It doesn’t have to be the taste of food or drinks, though. The trigger could be a scent or sound that you’ve not experienced for a long time.

就像很多事情一样，你可以利用这一点。学习你想记住的东西时，试着嚼一种你不习惯的口香糖。越奇特越好。这种口香糖只在两个场合使用：学习期间和会所的朗诵会期间。如果你实在忍不住嚼口香糖，可以用薄荷糖代替，因为如果你在会所里和修士或新成员交谈，嚼口香糖是不礼貌的。

Like so many things, you can use this to your advantage. When studying something you want to memorize, try chewing a type of gum that you’re not used to. The more exotic, the better. Only use that gum on one of two occasions: during study, and during recital in lodge. You could use a mint instead of gum if you can’t restrain yourself from chewing, which is just bad manners if you’re speaking to brothers or an initiate in lodge assembled.

另一个选择是在学习时使用带有特殊香味的扩香器或房间清新剂。在学习之前，将少量香味滴在手帕上，在背诵之前闻一闻。不过，动作要轻柔。你肯定不想把自己变成一根散发着特殊香味的除臭剂吧。

Another option is to use a diffuser or room freshener with an unusual scent when studying. Prior to lodge, place a tiny amount of that scent on a handkerchief and take a whiff of it just before reciting what you’ve memorized. Easy does it, though. You don’t want to turn yourself into a walking stick of deodorant.

顺便说一句，学习时闻一闻迷迭香已被证明能显著提高记忆力——一些研究表明，记忆力提升幅度高达75%。更多信息，请上网搜索。

Incidentally, the smell of rosemary while studying has been shown to significantly increase memory retention – some studies show an increase of up to 75%. Do a search on the internet for more information.

涂鸦文字（仅限非深奥内容）

Word Doodling (non-esoteric only)

如果你的电脑装有某种文本编辑程序，这种方法会最有效，大多数人都有。你经常可以在网上找到一些非深奥的仪式和讲座内容。不过要注意，这些段落在你的管辖范围内可能仍然被认为是深奥的，在这种情况下，你的誓言可能会禁止你将它们复制粘贴到文字处理程序中。但假设你想记住的单词不是深奥的，你可以将它们复制粘贴到文本文档中，或者直接输入，或许可以参考你的显示器。

This technique works best if you have a computer with some kind of text editing program, which most of you do. Often times you can find non-esoteric portions of ritual and lectures on the internet. Be mindful of the fact that such passages might still be considered esoteric in your jurisdiction, however, in which case your oath would arguably prohibit you from copying and pasting them into word processing program. But assuming the words you want to memorize are not esoteric, you can copy and paste them into a text document, or else type them in, perhaps referring to your monitor.

一旦你把这些单词写进文本文档，你的任务就是简单地移动这些单词，一开始可能只是随机移动，以寻找规律。为了说明我的意思，我再次引用《道德与教条》中的这段话：

Once you have the words in a text document, your task is simply to move the words around, perhaps randomly at first, in search of patterns. To illustrate what I’m talking about, I’ll again use this excerpt from Morals and Dogma:

共济会是世界伟大的和平组织。无论它存在于何处，它都致力于防止国际困难和争端；并将共和国、王国和帝国团结成一个伟大的和平友好联盟。如果共济会成员了解自己的力量并珍视自己的誓言，那么他们的奋斗就不会常常徒劳无功。

“Masonry is the great Peace Society of the world. Wherever it exists, it struggles to prevent international difficulties and disputes; and to bind Republics, Kingdoms, and Empires together in one great band of peace and amity. It would not so often struggle in vain, if Masons knew their power and valued their oaths.”

首先，尽量把这段文字写成最完美的正方形。经过几次尝试，我得到了以下结果：

First, try to form up the paragraph into the most perfect square you can. After a few tries, here’s what I came up with:

还没到那儿。但说实话，我永远也到不了，你也到不了。这些文字并非设计用来排列成一个完美的正方形。但通过对文字进行操作，也就是移动它们，试图把它们拼成一个形状，你就把它们印在了脑海里。大脑喜欢谜题，而你把这段文字变成了一个谜题。

Still not there. But I never will be, honestly, and neither will you. These words were not designed to be organized into a perfect square. But by acting on the words, i.e., by moving them around and trying to form them into a shape, you’re impressing them into your mind. The mind loves puzzles, and you’ve turned this paragraph into a puzzle.

这是第二个练习，我编辑该段落，直到每一行都以两个字母的单词结尾：

Here’s a second exercise, in which I edit the paragraph until every line ends in a two-letter word:

砌体是

石工

and disputes and to bind Republics,
