变化几乎无穷无尽。例如，你可以将段落分成以“the”、“it”或“to”开头或结尾的几个部分。发挥你的想象力。记住，这样做没有对错之分。这有点像在纸上涂鸦。你只是让你的大脑以自由的方式玩弄这些词语，但这样做的同时，你会无意识地在大脑中构建一个词语记录，以及它们之间的关系。

The variations are almost limitless. You can divide the paragraph into segments beginning or ending with the word “the” or “it” or “to,” for example. Use your imagination. Remember, there is no wrong or right way to do this. This is a bit like doodling on a piece of paper. You’re just allowing your mind to play around with the words in a freeform manner, but in doing so, you’ll be unconsciously creating a register of the words, and their relationship with one another, in your brain.

拟声器

Ideophones

您听说过布巴/基基效应吗？

Have you heard of the Bouba/Kiki Effect?

看一下这两张图片：

Take a look at these two images:

。

.

假设其中一个形状名为Bouba，另一个名为Kiki。大声说出这两个名字。你觉得哪一个是 Kiki ？哪一个是 Bouba ？这不是一个刁钻的问题。你不必费心思考，跟着感觉走就好。

Assume that one of these shapes is named Bouba. The other is Kiki. Say those names out loud. Which one do you think is Kiki? Which one is Bouba? It’s not a trick question. You don’t have to meditate on it. Just go with your gut.

停止阅读，直到你做出猜测。

Stop reading until you make your guess.

知道了？

Got it?

好的…

Okay…

如果你和大多数人一样，你会猜测左边的人物是Kiki，右边的人物是Bouba。为什么呢？

If you’re like most of the human race, you guessed that the figure on the left is Kiki, and the one on the right is Bouba. Why?

嗯，这很复杂（难道不是吗？），但归根结底，我们的大脑有一种独特的方式将声音与形状联系起来——无论我们说什么语言。这项测试，以及一项使用Takete和Maluma这两个词的类似测试，都针对西班牙语、英语和泰米尔语使用者进行了测试，结果一致（正如你可能猜到的那样，Takete 最容易让人联想到看起来像一颗变形的飞镖的形状）。

Well, it’s complicated (isn’t everything?), but the bottom line is that our brains have a peculiar way of connecting sounds with shapes – regardless of the language we speak. This test, and a similar one using the words Takete and Maluma, has been posed to speakers of Spanish, English, and Tamil, and the results were consistent (as you might guess, Takete was overwhelming associated with the figure that looks like a deformed throwing star).

这是所谓“声音象征主义”的一个例子，该理论认为某些声音具有特定的原始意义。那些能够唤起对某个想法（例如声音、颜色、气味或情感）生动印象的词语被称为“体音”。这是一个引人入胜的现象，关于其原因存在诸多争议。我们的大脑能够以一些非常奇特的方式将图像和形状（以及记忆对象）与词语和想法联系起来。

This is an example of what is called sound symbolism, which is the theory that some sounds have specific primal meanings. The words, which evoke a vivid impression of an idea (such as a sound, color, smell or emotion) are called idiophones. It’s a fascinating phenomenon and there’s a lot of debate about why this happens. Our brains can link images and shapes (and thus Memory Objects) to words and ideas in some very weird ways.

由此可以得出一个结论：如果你发现一个词让你想起某种形状、颜色或其他任何东西，或者反之亦然，不要仅仅因为你不理解它就忽视这种联系。它的存在本身就意味着它以某种方式根植于你的大脑中，而这种联系非常强大。好好利用它们吧。

A take-away from this is this: If you find that a word reminds you of a shape, color, or anything else, or vice versa, don’t ignore the connection simply because you don’t understand it. The fact that it exists at all means it is somehow hardwired in your brain, and those types of connections are very powerful. Use them.

二十七

27

一些总结

Some Closing Thoughts

一个正如我在本书开头所说，在学习逐字记忆的同时，你也学习了列表记忆。

As I stated at the beginning of this book, in learning verbatim memorization you have also learned list memorization.

由于逐字记忆法用于记忆长串单词，它不如更简单的“表亲”那么“优雅”。为了帮助你记住单词而创建的记忆对象通常很奇怪、滑稽或抽象，而且通常与单词所代表的含义毫无关联。我们为了记住一个单词而拼凑在一起的奇怪东西与这个单词所代表的含义之间很少有关联。

Because verbatim memorization is used to memorize long strings of words, it is less “elegant” than its simpler cousin. The Memory Objects created to help you remember words are usually weird or comical or abstract and they usually have nothing to do with the ideas represented by the words. There is rarely a correlation between the odd collection of things we jumble together to remember a word and what the word represents.

列表记忆可以如此，但并非必须如此。像太阳这样的单个记忆对象可以与空间所包含的任何概念（正义、启蒙、生育等）建立强大的联系。虽然共济会讲座和部分内容所需的记忆宫殿必然是逐字逐句的形式，但几乎所有共济会符号、徽章等的设计都是为了教导或提醒我们思想和概念，而不是文字。古老共济会插图中的寺庙、会所、田野和山丘与列表形式的记忆宫殿有着惊人的相似之处。方形、水平或断柱的外观并非为了提醒我们文字，而是为了提醒我们更大的东西。也许是某种无法用文字完全描述的东西。

List memorization can be like that but it doesn’t have to be. A single Memory Object like the sun can have a powerful connection to whatever concepts a Space holds (justice, enlightenment, fertility, etc.). Though the memory palaces required for Masonic lectures and parts are necessarily of the verbatim varieties, almost all Masonic symbols, emblems, etc. are designed to teach or remind us of ideas and concepts, not words. The temples, lodge rooms, fields and hills in old Masonic illustrations bear a striking resemblance to memory palaces of the list variety. The appearance of a square, level, or broken column, serves not to remind us of words but of something bigger. Perhaps something not fully describable by words.

虽然逐字记忆法使用的记忆对象与列表记忆法使用的记忆对象差异很大，但两种技术使用的模型几乎完全相同。无论你追求哪种记忆类型，模型的选择、构建和导航方式都大致相同。诚然，逐字记忆法的模型内容更密集，其记忆对象的重要性也更低，但除此之外，它与列表记忆法使用的模型完全相同。

While the Memory Objects used for verbatim memorization differ considerably from those used for list memorization, the Models used by both techniques are almost identical. The Models are selected, constructed, and navigated in much the same way regardless of the type of memorization you’re pursuing. True, a verbatim Model is more crowded, and its Memory Objects have less significance, but otherwise it is the same as a Model used for list memorization.

知道如何构建记忆宫殿的好处远不止增强记忆力。宫殿建造者可以更容易地辨别隐藏在艺术、文学、宗教文本、音乐和戏剧中的记忆宫殿的蛛丝马迹。你甚至可以确定它们是如何建造的，以及建造的原因。谁知道在这些隐藏宫殿的墙壁内会发现什么样的光芒呢？

The perks of knowing how to construct a memory palace extend beyond enhanced memory. A palace builder can more easily discern the tell-tale signs of memory palaces which have been concealed in art, literature, religious texts, music, and plays. You may even be able to determine how and why they were built. Who knows what light might be found within the walls of those hidden palaces?

祝您狩猎愉快。

Happy hunting.

* * *

* * *

在《阿德赫伦尼姆》（Ad Herennium）中描述记忆宫殿一千年后，它们仍然被用于记忆。但在文艺复兴时期，记忆宫殿被改造得更加复杂。这种转变很大程度上得益于神学家、哲学家和炼金术士们的推测，他们开始推测，心灵的本能，或者说，设计成可以反映外部现实——反之亦然。这意味着我们不再局限于仅仅通过感官来了解现实。我们可以磨练我们的心智，深入其深处，发现感官无法察觉的真理。

A thousand years after memory palaces were described in Ad Herennium, they were still being used memorization. But during the Renaissance, memory palaces were transformed into something far more complex. This transformation was largely the result of theologians, philosophers and hermeticists who began to speculate that the mind was equipped, or perhaps designed, to mirror the reality outside of it – or vice versa. This meant that we were no longer restricted to learning about reality through our senses alone. We could polish our minds and look deeper inside its recesses to find truths that our senses were unable to detect.

这些人相信，因为人是按照上帝的形象造的，所以人类的大脑天生就拥有整个宇宙的蓝图。嗯，实际上，这蓝图远不止宇宙。我们说的是万物的蓝图，是现实本身的蓝图。

Such individuals believed that, because man is made in the image of God, the human mind comes equipped with a built-in blueprint for the entire universe. Well, more than the universe, really. We’re talking about a blueprint for everything. Reality itself.

不出所料，这一概念进一步演变成了这样一种理论：那些完全理解现实的人也必然能够塑造现实。如果心灵与现实如出一辙，并且可以相互协调，那么心灵与现实就应该处于平等的竞争环境中。如果心灵能够受到“外在”事物的影响，那么心灵难道不应该同样有能力影响这些事物吗？

As might be expected, this concept further evolved into the theory that those who fully comprehend reality must also be able to shape it. If the mind and reality are cut from the same cloth and can be made to align with one another, mind and reality should be on an even playing field. If the mind can be affected by things “outside” of it, shouldn’t the mind be equally capable of affecting those things?

但如何才能实现这一点呢？如今，大多数信奉这一理论或类似理论的人会说，这需要纯粹的意志力，或者每天的确认，或者想象某种力量，这种力量强大到足以让宇宙屈服，满足你的愿望。

But how to make that happen? Today, most adherents to this theory, or one like it, would say that it is accomplished through pure force of will, or daily confirmations, or imagining something with such force that the universe is forced to take a knee and give you what you want.

然而，这些策略对于文艺复兴时期神秘记忆宫殿的实践者来说却格格不入。他们生活在一个宗教狂热和魔法盛行的时代。如果你想让宇宙或其他任何力量屈从于你的意志，你就必须为此付出努力。一种方法是对记忆宫殿进行逆向工程。如果一座宫殿可以用来记录通过感官观察到的事物，那么难道不能精心建造一座宫殿，并在其中填充记忆对象，从而引导——或者说“欺骗”——宇宙“记住”它们，从而使它们突然出现吗？

These strategies were, however, alien to Renaissance practitioners of mystical memory palaces. They lived in an age of religious fervor and magic. If you wanted the universe or any other power to bend to your will, you had to work for it. One approach was to reverse-engineer memory palaces. If a palace could be used to record in the mind things which are observed through the senses, couldn’t a palace be carefully constructed and populated with Memory Objects that caused – one might say “tricked” – the universe into “remembering” them, and thus causing them to pop into existence?

关于这个话题，有很多详尽的大型书籍，其中几本我已经引用过。关于如何主动而非被动地使用记忆宫殿，有很多想法。我之所以介绍这个话题，是因为我认为，一本教授记忆宫殿技巧、主要面向共济会成员的书，至少应该粗略地概述一下，在催生了我们这种思辨性、有组织的技艺的那个时代，少数人是如何使用它的。

Large books with far more details are available on this topic, several of which I have already cited. There were many thoughts on how a memory palace might be used actively instead of passively. I introduce this topic only because I think it appropriate that a book that teaches the memory palace technique, and which is written primarily for Freemasons, should provide at least a cursory overview of how it was used by a select few in the era which gave birth to the speculative, organized iteration of our craft.

* * *

* * *

你可能会像我一样，发现构建记忆宫殿有点让人上瘾。这倒不是坏事。只是一旦你建了一两个，你的大脑似乎就会急于寻找下一个目标。创造的过程很刺激——就像解谜一样。有些人喜欢填字游戏，一上午不玩就过不去。记忆宫殿也能产生同样的效果。

You may find, as I have, that the construction of memory palaces is somewhat addictive. Not in a bad way. It’s just that once you’ve built one or two, your brain may seem a bit anxious to find another target. The creation process is stimulating – rather like solving a puzzle. There are people who love crossword puzzles and can’t let a morning pass without attempting one. Memory palaces can have the same effect.

你可能会发现，即使不使用记忆宫殿技巧，你的整体记忆力也会提升。正如本书前面所讨论的，建造宫殿似乎可以重塑一个人的大脑，使其更加高效。至于为什么会发生这种情况，我将留给研究人员来解释，但我想我们都会同意这是一件好事。

You will probably find that your overall memory increases, even when you aren’t using the memory palace technique. As discussed earlier in this book, the construction of palaces appears to rewire a person’s brain and make it more efficient. I’ll leave it to the researchers to explain why this happens, but I think we can all agree that’s it’s a good thing.

自从我开始创建记忆宫殿以来，我一直在思考创建记忆对象意味着什么。是的，这听起来很简单。我甚至解释过怎么做。但我越来越意识到，我的脑海里——或者你的脑海里，或者任何人的脑海里——除了记忆对象之外什么也没有。

Since I began creating memory palaces, I’ve come to ponder what it means to create a Memory Object. I mean, yes, it sounds straight-forward. I’ve even explained how to do it. But I’ve become increasingly aware that there is nothing in my head – or yours, or anyone else’s – other than Memory Objects.

我们的心智都被困在某个无形的世界里，双手背在虚无缥缈的身后，双腿在虚无缥缈的地板上踱步，焦急地等待着感官探测到某种外部活动并汇报给我们。我们与感官另一端的事物存在着几度的距离。我们根本不知道那里究竟有什么。感官既是大门，又是屏障，我们对“墙”外事物的理解，仅仅基于五个不可靠的信使传递的神秘符号。

We’re all minds stuck in some invisible world with our ethereal hands behind our ethereal backs, pacing ethereal floors with our ethereal legs, waiting impatiently for one of the senses to detect some kind of external activity and report back to us. We are a few degrees removed from whatever it is on the other side of our senses. We’ve got no idea what is really out there. The senses are simultaneously gates and barriers, and our understanding of what lies beyond “the wall” is based solely on cryptic symbols handed us by five unreliable messengers.

我现在明白了为什么我们的技艺部分侧重于五感。以前，我觉得关于感官的讲座有些枯燥乏味。毕竟，感官是生理的，是生物性的，没什么深奥之处。嗅觉就是……嗯，嗅觉。如何从嗅觉中获得“光”？这一切看起来都挺傻的。

I now understand why our craft focuses, in part, on the five senses. Previously, I’d considered the lectures on the senses somewhat boring. After all, the senses are physical. Biological. There’s nothing esoteric about them. Smell is...well, smell. How does one obtain “light” from smell? It all seemed rather silly.

然而，如果我们理解感官是两个现实之间的大门，而守卫大门的信使负责形成我们对墙外事物的感知，那么它们的重要性就显而易见了。

Yet if one understands that the senses are the gates between two realities, and that the messengers who man those gates are responsible for forming our perception of what lies beyond the walls, their importance is obvious.

我的观点只是，记忆宫殿并非新鲜事物。归根结底，我们的现实就是一座记忆宫殿。构建记忆宫殿，是我们自最初被赋予意识火花以来就一直在做的事情。即使是现在，我们也在做。就在此时此刻。

My point is only that memory palaces are nothing new. Ultimately, our reality is a memory palace. Building them is something we’ve been doing since we were first gifted the spark of consciousness. It’s something we’re doing even now. This very moment.

作为共济会会员，我们应当铭记自己真正栖身的宏伟宫殿，它无处不在。我们如同困于自家城堡中庭的国王。我们依靠感官，勾勒出城堡外那片我们无法直接体验的广阔天地。我们茫然地凝视着城堡中心耀眼的光芒在内墙上投射的阴影。我们将这些阴影与感官的描绘进行比较，构建出一些小模型，希望它们能够捕捉到我们无法真正看到的东西的本质。这些模型是我们心灵和灵魂的记忆之物。

As Freemasons, we should be mindful of the grand, omnipresent palaces in which we truly reside. We are kings trapped in the middle chamber of our own castles. We rely on our senses to sketch images of the vast country beyond our castle walls which we cannot directly experience. We stare in confusion at the shadows cast on the interior walls of our castles by the blinding light that resides at their centers. We compare the shadows to the sketches of our senses and construct little models that we hope somehow capture the essence of what none of us can truly see. These models are the Memory Objects of our minds and souls.

你已经看到了构建一个专注于单一主题（例如讲座）的记忆宫殿所需的努力和细心。我们难道不应该同样有条不紊、孜孜不倦地构建那个我们想象成现实的宏伟记忆宫殿吗？

You have seen the effort and care required to build a memory palace dedicated to a single topic, such as a lecture. Shouldn’t we be equally methodical and tireless in the perpetual construction of that grand memory palace which we imagine is our reality?

* * *

* * *

历史上，共济会成员获得学位所需的记忆量令人望而生畏——可以说，这远远超过了传承仪式和传说中的秘密所需的记忆量。正因如此，我怀疑记忆最终只是为了达到目的，也就是说，共济会成员获得学位时所进行的记忆测试，其目的是为了培养出共济会一直以来所珍视的那种人——善于思考的人。

Historically, the amount of memorization required for Masons to achieve proficiency in the degrees has been daunting - arguably far more than necessary to perpetuate the rites and purported secrets of the craft. It is for this reason that I suspect memorization was ultimately an end unto itself, i.e., the memory trials of Masons seeking degrees were designed to produce the kind of man that has always been prized in Freemasonry - the thinking man.

因此，近几十年来降低记忆力要求对共济会科学的危害可能比我们想象的更大。普遍的看法是，这次撤退是为了维持或增加成员人数而必要的。但我认为，这次撤退也源于一种看法，即我们并没有践行我们一贯倡导的平等。毕竟，我们生来就拥有不同的天赋。记忆力可能是其中之一，也可能不是。为什么我们要仅仅因为那些拥有其他宝贵天赋的人不擅长记忆力就取消他们的资格，尤其是如果这些人已经满足了所有其他先决条件，并且对这门技艺充满热情的话？

Consequently, the reduced memorization requirements of recent decades may have been more detrimental to the science of Freemasonry than we suspect. Common wisdom is that this retreat was necessary to maintain or increase membership. But I think the retreat was also caused by a perception that we were not practicing the equality we so often espouse. After all, we are all born with different gifts. Memory might be one of them, or it might not be. Why should we disqualify men with other valuable talents simply because they aren’t good at memorization, particularly if those men have met all other prerequisites and are enthusiastic about the craft?

这个问题问得好。但我认为它没抓住重点。共济会的目标是使人变得更好，而这需要通过等级来实现。候选人不必在第一次加入会所时就获得共济会大师的称号，也不要求他在没有导师帮助的情况下获得任何称号。

It’s a good question. But I think it misses the point. The objective of Freemasonry is to make men better, and that is done in degrees. It isn’t necessary that a candidate be able to achieve the degree of Master Mason when he first appears in lodge, nor is he expected to achieve any degree without the help of a mentor.

至少在美国，学位制度的崩溃是我们降低先辈们曾经严格的记忆标准的原因之一。在我们国家，永久的入会学徒会所或同工会所寥寥无几。根本没有足够的新成员来支持它们作为独立机构。因此，商务会议和许多其他活动只对共济会大师开放。为了不让任何一位兄弟留在门外（既担心他会走失，也因为我们的正义感和平等意识不允许这样做），我们决定尽快让所有人入会。

The collapse of the degree structure, at least in the United States, is one reason we have reduced the once rigorous memory standards of our forefathers. There are few permanent Entered Apprentice or Fellowcraft lodges within our country. There simply aren’t enough new members to support them as independent institutions. Consequently, business meetings and many other activities are open only to Master Masons. Not wanting to leave any brother outside the door (both for fear he might wander away and because our sense of justice and equality forbids it) we have elected to get everyone inside as quickly as possible.

这会将我们引向何方？

Where might this lead us?

想象一下，现在是2050年。你所在的城镇有一所历史悠久的学院，它教授传统学科（科学、文学、数学等）已有两个世纪，并提供涵盖多个领域的四年制学位。尽管这所学院的校友声名显赫，但年轻人不再觉得有必要学习阅读、写作或进行数学计算，因为计算机可以为他们完成这些工作。学生来我们学院的唯一原因是，他们想要获得学位所代表的意义（至少在理论上），以及他们想要体验“大学生活”，而这主要由课外活动组成。

Imagine it is the year 2050. In your town there is a venerable old college which has taught traditional subjects (science, literature, mathematics, etc.) for two centuries, and which offers a four-year degree in a variety of fields. Despite the pedigree of the alumni produced by the college, young people no longer see a need to be taught how to read, write, or perform mathematical computations, because computers can perform that work for them. The only reason students come to our college is that they want the degree for what it represents (at least, in theory), and they want the “college experience,” which primarily consists of extracurricular events.

但随着时间的推移，学位和课外活动的吸引力已不足以维持招生。每年的学生人数都在减少。这令大学理事会感到担忧，因为仍然有很多学生真心想来这所大学学习，但如果没有那些为了光鲜的学位和课外活动而来的学生，这所大学就无法持续发展。

But, over time, the allure of the degree and the extracurricular activities aren’t enough to maintain enrollment. Each year there are a dwindling number of students. This concerns the college board because there are still many students who truly want to come to their college to learn, but the college isn’t sustainable without those other students who come to the school for the fancy-looking degree and the extracurricular activities.

大学理事会采取了两个措施。首先，增加并推广其课外活动。其次，将“四年制学位”的学制缩短至三年，此举表面上看是积极的，增加了每个教室的学生人数，使大学看起来比实际更健康。

The college board takes two steps. First, it increases and promotes its extracurricular offerings. Second, it reduces the required period for a “four-year degree” to three years, which has the ostensibly-positive effect of increasing the number of students in each classroom and makes the college look healthier than it really is.

然而，入学人数持续下降。仍有少数学生真心想学习那些古老且几乎被遗忘的科学，他们不愿依赖计算机代劳思考，但学生人数不足以维持学院的运营。因此，董事会再次增加了课外活动，并再次缩短了四年制学位的学制，这次缩短至两年。空荡荡的教室再次挤满了人。

Yet, attendance continues to dwindle. There remain a few students who truly want to learn the old and largely forgotten sciences, and who do not wish to depend on computers to do their thinking for them, but there’s not enough to keep the college viable. So, the board again increases its extracurricular activities and again reduces the time it takes to get a four-year degree, this time to two years. The hollowed classrooms are again full.

不过，请注意，到目前为止，获得学位的学术要求保持不变。虽然学生可以在两年内获得“四年制”学位，但学习内容并没有减少。学生仍然需要掌握知识才能毕业。这意味着攀登的路途缩短了，但山坡却陡峭得多。曾经一年就能学到的东西，现在必须在六个月内学会！

Note, however, that up till now, the academic requirements to obtain a degree have remained the same. Though a student can get a “four-year” degree in two years, there has been no reduction in what must be learned. Students still have to know their stuff to graduate. This means the climb is shorter but the hill is much steeper. What could once be learned in a year must now be learned in six months!

那些上大学学习的学生虽然有些抱怨，但还是继续前进。

Those students attending college to learn grumble a bit but march on.

那些不来学习的学生抱怨得更大声，抱怨学术标准太严格。他们认为，不应该指望一个人在两年内就能学会四年才能学到的东西！于是他们开始辍学。

Those students who are not there to learn grumble much louder and complain that the academic standards are too tough. No person, they argue, should reasonably be expected to learn in two years what was once learned in four! They begin to drop out.

学院再次面临入学人数减少的问题。董事会认为有必要将四年制学位的教育要求缩短为一年。否则，学院将不复存在，这对那些仍在学习的学生来说又何其公平？

Again, the college is faced with dwindling attendance. The board feels compelled to reduce the educational requirements for a four-year degree into a single year. If not, it will cease to exist, and how would that be fair to those few students who are present to learn?

现在，每三个月的学制都相当于一个“传统”年，这意味着 9 月份还是大一的学生，12 月份就会升为大二，3 月份就会升为大三，6 月份就会升为大四。

Each three-month period is now rated as the equivalent of a “traditional” year, which means that a student who was a Freshman in September will be a Sophomore in December, a Junior by March, and a Senior by June.

通过这种方式，董事会认为学生们仍然能够获得他们渴望的“大学经历”。他们仍然有机会佩戴校徽和校帽，参加课外活动，并在毕业典礼上正式宣布自己是大学毕业生。

In this way the board feels that the students are still getting the “college experience” they yearn for. They still have an opportunity to wear school rings and hats, can participate in extracurricular activities, and get to proclaim themselves college graduates when all is said and done.

问题在于那该死的学习曲线。即使是那些有学术精神的学生，也要求他们把四年的学习压缩到一年，这真的公平吗？

The problem is that darn learning curve. Is it really fair to expect even the academically-minded students to compress four years of learning into one year?

不，这甚至可能根本不可能。

No. It might not even be possible.

解决方案？你现在肯定已经猜到了。降低学历要求。

The solution? You have surely guessed it by now. Reduce the academic requirements.

结果同样可以预见。那些不太热衷学习的学生的出勤率有所上升……但只是暂时的。而那些来学校学习的学生的出勤率却迅速下降。毕竟，除了一座发霉的老图书馆和它著名的历史之外，学校几乎没有什么可以提供给这些学生的。这远远不够。随着这些学生的流失，学校很快就会失去教学能力。如果没有人想学习，教学还有什么价值呢？

The results are equally predictable. Attendance by those who don’t really care to learn increases...for a while. But attendance by those who came to the college to learn evaporates. After all, the college doesn’t really have much to offer those students except a musty old library and its famous history. That’s not going to be enough. And with the loss of those students, the college soon loses its ability to teach. What value is there in teaching if no one present wants to learn?

学院如今已不复当年之勇。董事会无奈之下，决定将这所昔日的学术机构改造成社交俱乐部，在原有的教室里安装全息投影仪、餐厅、冥想实验室，或者任何公众喜欢的设施。但其他濒临倒闭的机构也在效仿。究竟是什么让这所学院如此独特？只有它的历史。而这终究不够。

The college becomes a shell of its former self. Desperate, the board decides to convert the former academic institution to a social club, filling its former classrooms with hologram machines, restaurants, meditation labs, or whatever else the public fancies. But other dying institutions are doing that, too. What makes the college unique? Only its history. And that ultimately won’t be enough.

最终，将四年制学位课程缩减为一年，并将学习要求几乎降至零，并没有拯救这所大学。充其量，它只是为它争取了一些时间。

In the end, collapsing the four-year degree program into a single year and then reducing the learning requirements to almost nothing didn’t save the college. At best, it bought it some time.

这所学院的经历，在世界上的每一所学术机构中都存在。即使老一辈的人为这些古老学府的消亡而惋惜，他们却没有意识到，还有更重要的东西正在消逝。

The experiences of this college are mirrored by every academic institution in the world. Even as the old-timers bemoan the loss of these venerable institutions, they fail to recognize the loss of something more important.

学院曾经教授的一切。

Everything that the college once taught.

在接下来的几年里，所有计算机所能认知的事物都被人类遗忘了。数学变成了一门神秘的艺术。阅读和写作被广泛视为某种原始的魔法。思考也遭到质疑——既然世界上所有的智慧都蕴藏在最新计算机的原子存储器中，我们脆弱的人类又何必思考呢？

In the years that follow, anything that can be known by a computer is forgotten by man. Mathematics becomes an arcane art. Reading and writing are widely viewed as some primitive form of magic. Thinking is viewed with suspicion – why should we frail humans think when all the wisdom of the world is contained in the atomic memory of the newest computers?

思考变成了一门神秘的科学，受人尊崇，却鲜有人实践。一些古老而失传的工具被用于家居装饰和神秘仪式——书写工具、一沓纸，以及一种被称为“书”的东西——但几乎没有人知道它们是如何被使用的。

Thinking becomes an occult science that is honored by many but practiced by few. Some tools of the old, forgotten ways are used for household decoration and arcane ceremonies – writing instruments, a pad of paper, and something called a “book” - but almost no one knows remember how they were used.

共济会目前正处于这假设的未来困境之中。我们取消了等级制度，以增加共济会大师会议的出席人数，并降低了成为共济会大师的学习要求。我们通过夸耀自己的血统、社交机会和可获得的炫耀来推销自己。

Freemasonry is currently somewhere in the middle of this hypothetical future quagmire. We have collapsed the degrees to increase lodge attendance for Master Masons’ meetings and we have reduced the learning requirements to be a Master Mason. We are promoting ourselves by citing our pedigree, social opportunities, and the availability of bling.

这能让我们维持几年。然后呢？

That can keep us afloat for a few years. Then what?

让我回到最初的观点。早期共济会成员认为我们的机构能够教导人们思考。思考什么？思考科学、道德、宗教、艺术，甚至思考现实本身。记忆的要求并非为了压制人们，而是为了提升人们。

Let me circle back to my original point. Early Freemasons saw our institution as one which could teach men to think. About what? The sciences, morality, religion, art, and even reality itself. Memorization requirements were not intended to keep men down. They were intended to elevate men.

* * *

* * *

希望你喜欢这本书。欢迎反馈和评论。如果你觉得这本书有价值，或者至少有趣，请与他人分享。

I hope you’ve enjoyed this book. I welcome feedback and comments. If you’ve found this book valuable, or at least interesting, please share it with others.

祝所有旅行者一路顺风。

Godspeed to all traveling men.

结局

Finale

对于沉思冥想的心灵来说，这宇宙的结构如同一座迷宫，其中处处可见可疑的路径、对事物及其符号的虚假模仿、蜿蜒复杂的自然褶皱和节疤。必须借助时隐时现的、时而闪烁的感官之光，不断在经验和个体本性的森林中开辟道路。然而，那些提供服务的向导（正如前文所述）本身也令人困惑，反而增加了迷途者和流浪者的数量……

“至少就我们而言，我们被对真理的永恒热爱所征服，投身于不确定、陡峭和荒凉的道路，信任并依靠神的帮助，使我们的思想抵御如同战场上布下的舆论狂潮，抵御我们内心的疑虑和顾虑，抵御大自然的迷雾和乌云，抵御在我们周围四处飘荡的幻想：这样，我们最终才能为今生和子孙后代收集到一些更可靠、更确定的指示。”

“For the fabric of this universe is like a labyrinth to the contemplative mind, where doubtful paths, deceitful imitations of things and their signs, winding and intricate folds and knots of nature everywhere present themselves, and a way must constantly be made through the forests of experience and particular natures, with the aid of the uncertain light of the senses, shining and disappearing by fits. But the guides who offer their services are (as has been said) themselves confused, and increase the number of wanderings and of wanderers...

“We, for our part at least, overcome by the eternal love of truth, have committed ourselves to uncertain, steep, and desert tracks, and trusting and relying on Divine assistance, have borne up our mind against the violence of opinions, drawn up as it were in battle array, against our own internal doubts and scruples, against the mists and clouds of nature, and against fancies flitting on all sides around us: that we might at length collect some more trustworthy and certain indications for the living and posterity.”

- 弗朗西斯·培根爵士，《大复兴》

- Sir Francis Bacon, The Great Instauration

。

.

罗伯特·弗拉德（Robert Fludd）的《托马斯·塞孔杜斯的超自然、自然、超自然和反自然微观世界史》中的一幅插图。这架梯子的横档从下到上依次为：感觉、想象、推理、理解、智力、言语。

An illustration from Robert Fludd’s “Tomas secundus de supernaturali, naturali, praternaturali et contranaturali microcosmi historia.” The rungs of this ladder are labeled, from bottom to top: Sense, Imagination, Reason, Understanding, Intelligence, The Word.

附录二：古语解释

Appendix 2: Archaic Words Explained

我们的共济会中有很多古老而难懂的词汇。在尝试记住任何你不理解的词汇之前，花时间学习它们的含义非常重要。下面我列出了一些比较难的词汇及其定义。然而，我并不是共济会古老术语领域的“权威”。如果我的定义看起来不太正确或恰当，请上网查找或向弟兄寻求帮助。

There are a lot of archaic and difficult words in our craft. It’s important that you take the time to learn the meanings of any words you don’t understand before trying to memorize them. Below I’ve listed a few of the more difficult ones, in addition to their definitions. I’m not, however, an “authority” in the field archaic Masonic terminology. If my definition doesn’t seem quite right or appropriate, look it up online or ask a brother for help.

此外，我提供的定义假设这些词语出现在共济会的语境中。例如，在我们的仪式中，“警报”通常是指敲门声或一系列敲门声，而在共济会之外，这个词的含义要广泛得多。

Also, the definitions I’ve provided assume the words appear in a Masonic context. For example, an “alarm” within our ritual is typically a knock or series of knocks on a door, while outside of Freemasonry the word has a much broader meaning.

  • 关于：周围
  • About: around
  • Accord：和谐一致，不违背个人良心的决定
  • Accord: harmonious agreement, a decision that does not conflict with a person’s conscience
  • 因此：适当地，以正确的方式
  • Accordingly: appropriately, in the correct manner
  • 称谓：头衔或名字
  • Appellation: title or name
  • 警报：敲门，或连续敲门
  • Alarm: knock, or series of knocks
  • Allude：间接提及某事物，即不实际使用其名称
  • Allude: refer to something indirectly, i.e., without actually using its name
  • 起立：站起来
  • Arise: stand up
  • 出席：负责、回应
  • Attend: take responsibility for, respond to

  • Before (as a location): in front of

  • Bind: attach two things or concepts to each other

  • Caused: required to do something

  • Charge (as a noun): a demand or requirement
  • Charge（用作动词）：要求或需要某物
  • Charge (as a verb): to demand or require something
  • 限制：将某物保持在一定范围内，保持在界限之内
  • Circumscribe: keep something within certain limits, stay within boundaries
  • Clothe（动词）：通常是“整理围裙”Compose：将个人聚集在一起组成一个团体（lodge）
  • Clothe (a verb): usually “arrange the apron” Compose: bring together individuals to form a group (lodge)

  • 约定：在固定时间和地点发生的活动

  • 已建：已建造、已建造

附录 3：符号

Appendix 3: Notations

讲座篇幅冗​​长，可能难以记忆。但与角色相关的台词（你必须做或说某件事，然后等待其他兄弟发言或行动，才能说或做其他事）也同样令人望而生畏。

Lectures can be difficult to memorize because of their length. But lines associated with roles (in which you must do or say something and then wait for other brothers to speak or act before saying or doing something else) can be equally daunting.

尽管讲师通常需要记住的单词比只需要记住与一个角色相关的台词的兄弟要多得多，但讲师可以从头到尾不停地讲课，而不用担心等待另一个兄弟的提示，而这个提示可能永远不会出现，或者可能以错误的形式出现。

Though lecturers typically have many more words to memorize than a brother who needs to memorize only those lines associated with one role, lecturers proceed from start to finish without interruption and without the hazard of waiting for a cue from another brother which may never come, or which may come in the wrong form.

此外，讲师在演讲时几乎无需进行任何动作。虽然他们偶尔会用手或头部做出一些手势，但大部分时间都固定在一个位置。这种身体上的空闲状态让讲师能够专注于自己的演讲，几乎不受任何干扰。

Additionally, lecturers have few if any actions to perform as they speak. Though they may make an occasional gesture with their hands or head, they spend the majority of their time planted in just one location. This physically idle state allows lecturers to focus on their words with few distractions.

记忆互动角色的共济会成员则没有这种特权。他们就像戏剧中的演员。虽然他们的台词可能比讲师的台词更短、更少，但他们的台词是不连续的。讲师可以“轻松”地讲完课，而扮演角色的共济会成员必须背诵台词或表演动作，然后等待（通常要等很长时间）才能再次被提示说话或表演。这意味着，除了记住自己的台词和动作之外，非讲师成员还需要记住其他人的肢体和言语提示。

Masons memorizing interactive roles don’t have this luxury. They are like actors in a play. Though their lines may be shorter and fewer in number than those of a lecturer, their lines are discontinuous. A lecturer can “cruise” through his lecture while a Mason playing a role must recite his lines, or perform his actions, then wait, often for a very long time, before being cued to again speak or act. This means that, in addition to memorizing his lines and actions, a non-lecturer also needs to memorize the physical and verbal cues of others.

如果你记住的是角色而不是讲座内容，你可能会发现在密码或监视器上做一些小标记很有帮助，这可以帮助你描述其他参与者的行为和言语。随着你对共济会仪式的学习不断深入，你会发现，例如，等级的划分，都有特定的节奏。了解这种节奏对记忆过程大有裨益，而标记是识别这些节奏的一种方法。

If you are memorizing a role instead of a lecture, you may find it helpful make little notations in your cipher or monitor that can help you characterize the actions and words of other participants. As your studies of Masonic rituals advance, you’ll observe that there is particular rhythm to, for example, the degrees. Knowing this rhythm is a great help in the memorization process, and notations are one method for recognizing those rhythms.

接下来的页面中，我添加了可用作注释的符号，当然您也可以自行设计。这些注释最好写在与相关行或动作相邻的外边缘。

On the following pages I’ve included symbols that can be used as notations, though you’re of course free to develop your own. These notations are best made in the outer margins adjacent to pertinent lines or actions.
